<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--MistakenForDead     08-18 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Mistaken For Dead,0138</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boarding Home Operator Charged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operator of a boarding home where an
87-year-old resident was mistaken for dead and nearly embalmed has
been charged with three counts of operating an unlicensed nursing
home.
   The charges filed against Robbie Caldwell are minor misdemeanors
and carry a maximum fine of $100, City Prosecutor Albert Stewart
said Thursday.
   A resident of the boarding home, Carrie Stringfellow, apparently
lost consciousness Aug. 5 and was mistaken for dead. She was
transported to a funeral home, where her murmurings startled a
mortician who was preparing to embalm her.
   Ms. Stringfellow, who is blind, was taken to Mercy Medical
Center. She was released from the hospital Wednesday and transferred
to a nursing home. Doctors said she apparently remembers nothing of
the events at the funeral home.
  
</TEXT>
