<FIRST>r i PM-APArts:Flight007     08-18 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Flight 007,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Korean Airliner Disaster, Anglo-American Style</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1983 Korean Airlines disaster is returning to
television in an Anglo-American docudrama focusing on
behind-the-scenes political intrigue.
   ``Tailspin: Behind the Korean Airliner Tragedy'' recreates the
American political response to the Soviet downing on Aug. 31, 1983
of KAL Flight 007 in which 269 people were killed.
   The 90-minute film stars Chris Sarandon as John Lenczowski, then
Soviet affairs director for the National Security Council, and
Michael Murphy as Richard Burt, then the State Department's
assistant secretary for Soviet affairs.
   ``Tailspin'' will be aired Aug. 20 on cable TV's Home Box Office
as the first in a three-project partnership between HBO in the
United States and Granada Television in Britain. The trans-Atlantic
line-up includes producer John Smithson and director David Darlow,
who are British, and writer Brian Phelan, an Irishman. Besides
Sarandon and Murphy, the American cast includes Harris Yulin and
Michael Moriarty.
   In an on-set interview last December in London, producer Smithson
called the project ``a serious and intellectual work of the type you
don't often see on American TV.''
   In more than 150 hours of interviews with up to 60 people, some
claimed the downing was a deliberate, cold-blooded Soviet attack;
some that the airliner was on an espionage mission, and some that it
was all a tragic blunder. Missing American records fueled
allegations of a cover-up.
   ``Tailspin'' doesn't take sides. Smithson said it is interested
not in fixing blame but in examining the middle-level,
decision-making process in American government.
   In one scene, Sarandon, as Lenczowski, argues in a White House
boardroom about the wording of a speech President Reagan would later
deliver.
   ``We're interested in the political battle in Washington at the
time between the State Department and the NSC, the center and the
right,'' said Smithson.
   He said the emergence of a Soviet policy of glasnost, or
openness, made ``Tailspin'' a period piece with perceptions of the
Soviet Union as ``the evil empire'' soon to be outmoded.
   ``This is a curious piece of modern history, an entirely
pre-glasnost piece,'' said Smithson. ``It marks a turning-point
where we're beginning to see the softening of Ronald Reagan.''
   Director David Darlow said he intended the film to be ``an
international political thriller.''
   ``If we've succeeded, it will have a sort of `All the President's
Men' feel about it,'' said the director, referring to Alan Pakula's
acclaimed 1976 film about the Watergate conspiracy.
   In telling its story from the inside, Darlow distinguished his
film from ``Shootdown,'' the NBC TV-movie with Angela Lansbury that
aired last Nov. 28. That version examined the crises of the
outsiders _ families of the victims and others.
   ``Tailspin'' focuses, he said, on three groups: the hard-line
anti-Soviets, represented by Lenczowski; the middle ground,
represented by the State Department; and Pentagon officials who,
Darlow said, saw the incident as ``a gigantic screw-up by the
Soviets.''
   Sarandon, a 1975 Academy Award nominee for ``Dog Day Afternoon,''
came to the project directly from filming in Hungary. He had no time
to meet the real Lenczowski, now a strategic studies consultant at
the Council for Inter-American Security in Washington.
   But he thinks attitudes to the KAL tragedy have changed following
the U.S. downing of a civilian Iranian airliner in July, 1988.
   ``Since that was, as our government says, accidental, I think
Americans will be more open-minded over the shooting down of the
Korean airliner,'' Sarandon said.
   Bridget Potter, HBO's Senior Vice-President for Original
Programming, agreed, saying the later incident means the earlier one
``cannot be seen in isolation.''
   ``It can happen again,'' she said. ``Mistakes are going to be
made.''
   Potter said the HBO-Granada partnership had resulted in a truly
international style of TV that works for both British and U.S.
audiences.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
