<FIRST>r a PM-NoPledging     08-18 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-No Pledging,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fraternity Eliminates Pledge Period, Spending on Alcohol</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Animal House'' is out and temperance in at Zeta
Beta Tau.
   The national fraternity next month becomes the first to eliminate
the traditional pledge period, that rugged rite of passage when
hazing can break both spirits and bones.
   ZBT, like others, also is cutting off fraternity spending on
alcohol.
   ``It's not easy to implement, it may be painful, but nevertheless
it's an idea which we felt should be followed through,'' said ZBT
executive director James E. Greer Jr., one of the movers behind the
decision.
   The rules are aimed at breaking the image of the stereotypical
fraternity house _ John Belushi-like lunacy, heavy drinking, random
abuse of pledges _ while keeping positive aspects such as bonding
and community service, Greer said Thursday.
   Zeta Beta Tau, which has 5,000 active members at more than 100
chapters in the U.S. and Canada, is the first national fraternity to
put an end to pledging. A dozen other national fraternities are
considering similar plans, said Jonathan Brant, director of the
National Interfraternity Conference.
   ``It's critical to eliminate hazing, and this is a viable
option,'' said Brant, whose group includes 59 national fraternities.
``We are supporting them, and hope through their success others will
learn the right lessons.''
   Potential ZBT members will be initiated as brothers within 72
hours of receiving their invitation to join, said Greer. Once in,
there will be a combination of orientation and education for the new
members rather than a torturous pledge period capped by ``Hell
Night.''
   ``We've had, as have other organizations, a continuation of
hazing incidents _ none life-threatening or severe, but we worry
about it,'' said Greer. ``We wanted to take the bull by the horns.''
   Greer said no single incident prompted the decision, but several
highly publicized incidents involving other fraternities have
focused attention on the organizations and hazing in the past two
years:
   _ A Rutgers University pledge died of alcohol poisoning after a
fraternity house party last year. James Callahan, 18, had a blood
alcohol level of 0.43 _ more than four times the legal limit.
   _ A pledge at the University of Lowell in Massachusetts was
stuffed in a sleeping bag while fraternity members turned on heaters
nearby. The pledge survived, but arrived at the hospital with a body
temperature of 109 degrees.
   _ A University of Delaware pledge charged in a lawsuit that a
corrosive oven cleaner was dumped on his head during ``Hell Night''
activities.
   ``The national fraternities don't like being identified as the
root cause of problems,'' said Greer. ``We have to find some answers
and remain on the cutting edge of solving problems.''
   While ZBT's Supreme Council unanimously approved the new policy,
Greer acknowledges response from its members _ both active and
alumni _ has not been uniformly positive.
   ``In the beginning, there was a lot of shock and denial and anger
that the national fraternity would do this,'' said Greer, a Class of
'64 ZBT at California State University at Long Branch.
   ``We've had letters and phone calls from alumni, calling this a
break with tradition, saying they don't understand what we're doing.
But overall, it's been far more positive than negative.''
   Greer said his organization knew it was risking a possible
fall-off in membership and dues this year, but was confident its
decision would quickly turn into a recruiting advantage for ZBT.
   ``We're dealing with a smarter, more savvy freshman. His parents
read the papers, they know what's going on with fraternities,'' said
Greer. ``Once we get past the initial anxiety, it'll be to our
advantage.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
