<FIRST>u a AM-HostageStandoff 2ndLd-Writethru a0401 08-18 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostage Standoff, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0401,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Man Reported Holding Eight Children and Wife</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with standoff ending in death of wife, self-wounding
of gunman; quotes from police; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who held his wife and eight
children at gunpoint shot her to death and critically wounded
himself Thursday after a 6{-hour standoff in which he played Russian
roulette with the hostages, police said.
   Dang Cha Xiong, 35, identified as a refugee from Laos, was in
critical condition at a city hospital, authorities said.
   ``Apparently none of the children were injured,'' said police Lt.
Andy Jackson. He said Dang was under court order to stay away from
his family.
   Deputy police chief Lucien Neely said Dang told police he would
surrender, but police then heard shots inside the apartment.
Officers rushed the dwelling, finding the children unharmed in a
front room and the two wounded parents in a rear bedroom. The wife
was pronounced dead at Dameron Hospital in Stockton.
   Neely said the gunman apparently had played Russian roulette with
the hostages during the standoff. The identity of the woman was not
immediately avaailable, police said.
   A tenth hostage, a 12-year-old boy, escaped and reported the
incident to police about 2 p.m., Jackson said.
   A special weapons and tactics team went to the apartment and
attempted negotiations, but the gunman did not released the
hostages, Jackson said.
   Jackson said the man was armed, but did not specify the weapon.
He had threatened the children, but there was no indication anyone
had been harmed, Jackson said.
   The boy told police that Dang had played Russian roulette with
the hostages, apparently sticking a bullet in the cylinder of a
pistol and pulling the trigger.
   Seven of the eight children, between one and 13 years of age,
were Dang's, police said.
   A man with an assault rifle on Jan. 17 killed five children and
wounded 30 other people before killing himself in a schoolyard in
this city 75 miles east of San Francisco.
</TEXT>
