<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--SpaceJournalist     08-18 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Space Journalist,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candidates Selected for First Journalist In Space</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese television station selected seven
employees as candidates to accompany a Soviet space mission and
become the first journalist in space, the network said.
   The Tokyo Broadcasting System staffers will travel to the Soviet
Union for tests later this year, the company said Thursday.
   Two finalists will undergo 18 months training at Glavkosmos, the
Soviet space agency.
   The seven include two 23-year-old assistant directors, the
network's 42-year-old Moscow bureau chief and its 47-year-old deputy
foreign editor. Two of the candidates are women.
   The successful candidate will join a Soviet mission to the space
station Mir in late 1991 and will put together daily television and
radio broadcasts during the six-day trip.
   Three Japanese astronauts, including one woman, are currently
being trained by the U.S. National Aeronautics and Space
Administration for a U.S. space mission scheduled for mid-1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
