<SECOND>PM-Lites,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OCEAN CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the winner circles, these victors were
a shade above the others.
   The ``Miscellaneous Sun Tanning Tournament,'' held in this
seaside vacation resort Thursday, attracted competitors in
categories such as best tanned underarms, best left arm tan _ ``for
folks who drive a lot'' _ and the Count Dracula division, for those
who avoid the sun, said city publicist Mark Soifer.
   ``We had a very pale young man win that award,'' Soifer said of
13-year-old Sean Martin of Cheltenham, Pa. ``He uses a lot of
sunscreen.''
   The best overall tan went to a repeat winner: Carl ``Mr. White
Feet'' Savino of Ocean View. Savino, an avid gardener, wears work
shoes every day.
   Bare-headed competition for the Golden Dome Award was tight, said
Soifer, who dreamed up the categories.
   Anthony Scavillo of Williamstown took ``top'' honors for the
second year in a row, but an honorable mention went to 8-month-old
Mathew Bishop of Danbury, Conn.
   ``He had the cutest little bald head,'' Soifer said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EMMAUS, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men are more likely than women to think about
sex while bicycling, and women are more likely than men to think
about cycling during sex, according to cyclists who told a magazine
the sport generally improves their sex lives.
   Sixty-six percent of the 1,675 respondents to a mail-in survey by
Bicycling magazine said they believed cycling has made them better
lovers, and 44 percent said it increased their sex drive, while 11
percent said it decreased.
   ``All this time you were logging your miles, this little sport
was becoming the hottest thing since naked volleyball,'' the
magazine said in its September issue, due on newsstands next week.
   Asked whether they thought about sex while cycling, 1,146 men, or
85 percent, said they did, while 234 women, or 77 percent,
acknowledged such thoughts. Asked whether they thought about cycling
during sex, 19 percent of the men and 23 percent of the women said
they did.
</TEXT>
