<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls     08-18 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>RTC Takes Over Six More S&amp;Ls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new agency created by Congress to resolve
the savings and loan crisis is taking control of another six
thrifts, bringing the total under government control to 268 in 33
states.
   The Resolution Trust Corp. announced action Thursday against four
institutions in Texas and two in Illinois. The S&amp;Ls will remain open
during normal business hours and all deposits are protected up to
the government insurance limit of $100,000.
   The agency will look for buyers to take over the S&amp;Ls, or
determine whether depositors should be paid off and the institutions
closed.
   The six, and their assets at the end of March, are:
   _Security Savings and Loan Association, Peoria, Ill., $356
million.
   _Black Hawk Federal Savings and Loan Association, Rock Island,
Ill., $74 million.
   _Southside Savings and Loan Association, Austin, Texas, $48
million.
   _Hearne Building and Loan Association, Hearne, Texas, $28 million.
   _Guadalupe Savings and Loan Association, Kerrville, Texas, $28
million.
   _Taylorbanc Savings Association, Taylor, Texas, $127 million.
   The RTC, created by S&amp;L legislation signed by President Bush on
Aug. 9, last week sold the deposits of three small institutions to
healthy institutions and is preparing to resolve the cases of
additional thrifts.
</TEXT>
