<FIRST>r a PM-Nation'sIcebox     08-18 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nation's Icebox,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Nation's Icebox' Title Surrendered To International Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRASER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a warm ending to a cold war, Fraser
surrendered the title ``Icebox of the Nation'' to International
Falls, Minn.
   Fraser Town Manager Clay Brown said Thursday the town trustees
voted 5-2 on Wednesday night to accept a $2,000 out-of-court
settlement offered by International Falls for sole use of the chilly
title.
   Both cities have spent thousands of dollars in litigation over
the title in the last two years, he said, adding that Fraser still
will be allowed to use it in Colorado.
   ``We don't have the dollars to continue the legal battle,'' said
Mayor C.B. Jensen. ``But in our hearts we still believe we are the
icebox of the nation.''
   International Falls uses the nickname to attract corporations to
its cold-weather testing grounds. Fraser's frigid reputation also
has attracted companies _ Zerex antifreeze and Malt-O-Meal cereal.
Fraser also is ``The Town Goodyear Put on Spikes.''
   ``The thing started out as a friendly wager and has gotten way
out of hand,'' said Brown. ``The board did this in part for the
people of Minnesota.''
   Part of the settlement calls for Fraser and International Falls
to become sister cities.
   ``We want to get on with this and promote our state,''
International Falls Mayor Jack Murray said Thursday. ``This will
help the economy of the small communities in Minnesota. Everything
has worked out for the best.''
   Fraser, a town of 470 about 60 miles northwest of Denver, said it
can document use of the phrase back to 1958, when tax dollars were
used to buy a sign for the town. International Falls, a city of
5,000 on the Canadian border, claimed it had the term printed on
hockey jerseys in 1955. Newspaper stories referred to Fraser by that
nickname in 1945.
</TEXT>
