<SECOND>AM-Richardson Execution, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0761,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pipe-Bomb Killer Executed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with execution; picks up 3rd graf:
`The U.S. ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN THOMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATMORE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herbert Lee Richardson was executed in
Alabama's electric chair early Friday for the 1977 pipe-bomb killing
of an 11-year-old girl.
   Richardson was pronounced dead at 12:14 a.m.
   The U.S. Supreme Court refused Thursday to intervene in the case
after the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta upheld a
lower court's decision to reject a stay of execution.
   Gov. Guy Hunt earlier refused to grant clemency for Richardson,
who was married last week in a prison ceremony.
   Richardson, 43, was condemned to die in the electric chair at
Holman Prison for the murder of Rena Mae Callins, whose body was
blown apart on the porch of her home when she picked up a pipe-bomb
and it detonated.
   Richardson contended the device was not meant to explode, only to
scare the girl's family. The girl's aunt had broken off a
relationship with him shortly before the pipe-bomb was planted.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Varner of Montgomery, who rejected
Richardson's motion for a stay, said it is ``beyond the bounds of
reason ... to believe that a device which maimed and killed an
11-year-old child by exploding in her hands could be thought of ...
as not presenting a serious risk of harm.''
   ``I can't rest until he gets the chair,'' said Margie Callins,
the girl's mother.
   In Montgomery, Lucia Penland of the Alabama Prison Project said
Richardson ``was what most of us would call an all-around American
boy with a bright future before he went to Vietnam.''
   She also said, ``The terrible tragedy of Mrs. Callins and her
family cannot be understated.''
   Courts in recent weeks have rejected defense claims that
Richardson wrongly was denied a state-funded psychologist to show
that he possibly was suffering post-traumatic stress disorder
stemming from his Vietnam War experiences.
   Richardson was married Aug. 9 at Holman, prison system
spokeswoman Debbie Herbert said.
   ``They let him out of the cell to go into the visiting room and
she (the bride) was there along with some other guests and after the
prison chaplain married them, they had some cake and then he
returned to his cell,'' Mrs. Herbert said.
   The governor's press secretary, Terry Abbott, said that according
to the clemency plea, Richardson and his wife, Katie, met 3{ years
ago. ``He wrote a letter to her church, saying he listened to their
broadcast and she started visiting,'' Abbott said.
   The church was identified as El Bethel Primitive Baptist Church
in Mobile.
</TEXT>
