<FIRST>r a PM-BarberKilling     08-18 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barber Killing,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted of Killing Barber Over $8 Haircut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was sentenced to life in prison for killing
his barber because he was dissatisfied with an $8 haircut.
   Paul W. Williams, 34, was found guilty of murder and two counts
of menancing Thursday by a Denver District Court jury. He was
convicted in the death of Bobbie Willis, 47, proprietor of Barber
Bob's Barber Shop.
   ``People don't kill someone over a haircut in this country,''
Judge Robert Hyatt told Williams before delivering the sentence.
``But I'm convinced that is exactly what you did.''
   Hyatt noted Williams' two previous felony convictions, one for
armed robbery and the other for burglary, and three misdemeanors.
   ``You must have such an explosive temper that you are literally
unable to control it,'' the judge said.
   Eight witnesses testified they watched Williams angrily confront
Willis in the barber shop last Dec. 17. Two of the witnesses, shop
employees, said they saw Williams shoot Willis.
   They said Williams became extremely angry at Willis after he
claimed the barber botched his haircut by exposing a scar on the
back of Williams' head. They said Williams vowed to return to the
shop and get even.
</TEXT>
