<DOCNO> AP890818-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 0345EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SatelliteLaunch     08-18 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Satellite Launch,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Launches Navigation Satellite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $65 million Navstar navigation
satellite rocketed into orbit early today, a half hour after liftoff
from Cape Canaveral.
   A three-stage Delta 2 rocket blazed away from its launch pad at
1:58 a.m. and left a fiery trail in the sky as it sped over the
Atlantic Ocean and climbed toward space.
   The Air Force reported 30 minutes after liftoff that the
128-foot-tall rocket had performed flawlessly and had propelled the
satellite into an initial elliptical orbit ranging from about 100 to
11,000 miles above the Earth.
   ``The Delta 2 has put its payload into a successful orbit,'' said
Lt. Col. Ron Rand, the launch control center commentator.
   On Sunday, ground controllers will command an on-board motor to
fire to shift the satellite into a circular orbit about 11,000 miles
up.
   The $30 million Delta rocket carried a Navstar Global Positioning
System Satellite, the third in a new series of spacecraft which
enable military units such as aircraft, ships, submarines, tanks and
field troops to determine their location within 50 feet and in some
cases to within 10 feet.
   The satellites, effective in any kind of weather, also keep track
of military units' speed within a fraction of a mile per hour and
the precise time within a millionth of a second.
   Each 3,675-pound Navstar contains an atomic clock with an error
rate of one second every 300,000 years.
   American and allied military users receive information from a
coded channel. Civilian users, also with access to the satellite
system, would monitor an open channel providing them with less
accurate position information within 300 feet.
   The satellite launched today is the third of 21 upgraded Block 2
Navstars that the Air Force plans to orbit to complete a global
system by 1992. The first two were launched in February and June.
   Seven earlier Block 1 Navstars also are orbiting the Earth. The
new model has more power and improved systems and has added the
coded military channel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
