<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 0348EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Economy     08-18 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Economy,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Posts $3.8 Billion Current Account Deficit in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soaring imports contributed to a $3.8 billion
deficit in trade and tourism last year, official reports said today.
   The State Administration of Foreign Exchange recorded an
increase, however, in China's foreign currency reserves, excluding
gold, to $17.3 billion from $15.2 billion in 1987, the China Daily
said.
   The report said China posted a $7.13 billion surplus in its
capital accounts, including direct investment and international
loans.
   The $3.8 billion deficit in the current account, which includes
trade and tourism, was largely due to a doubling of the nation's
trade deficit because of sluggish export growth and soaring imports,
it said.
   According to International Monetary Fund accounting procedures,
China's exports in 1988 totaled $41 billion, up 18.2 percent over
1987, while its imports grew 27.4 percent to $46.3 billion, the
report said.
   The resulting $5.3 billion trade deficit was double that of 1987,
the report said.
   China's Customs Administration on Thursday reported a $700
million trade deficit for July, the official Xinhua News Agency said.
   The nation's import growth slowed from 37.7 percent in June to 16
percent in July. Imports totaled $5.18 billion, while exports grew
0.1 percent over June to $4.4 billion, the Customs Administration
said.
   From January to June, China posted a trade deficit of $5.79
billion, up from $1.22 billion in the first half of 1988, according
to Customs statistics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
