<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 0330EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-18 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Nikkei Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar firmed against the yen Friday, while
share prices declined in slow trading.
   The dollar opened at 143.50 yen, and ranged between 143.05 and
143.58 yen. It closed at 143.58 yen, up 1.20 yen from its 142.32-yen
finish Thursday.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
which had gained 5.96 points Thursday, shed 26.97 points, or 0.08
percent, closing at 35,063.14 points.
   The index fell in thin trading as the majority of institutional
and foreign investors avoided buying and stepped off to the
sidelines, dealers said.
   ``Because the dollar-yen rate is now at a turning point,
investors were reluctant to make major moves, which made trading
directionless and thin,'' said a dealer with Nomura Securities,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In currency dealings, traders attributed the dollar's higher
opening to a smaller-than-expected U.S. trade deficit released
Thursday, which triggered dollar-buying in New York.
   The U.S. trade deficit fell to $8.2 billion, down by 18.9 percent
from the previous month's $10.1 billion.
   Traders said some market players sold off to take profits after
the dollar's jump in New York.
   But they predicted a yen rise because of investors' expectations
the U.S. economy is growing and the nation's monetary policy would
not be relaxed further.
   Toru Kanai, foreign exchange analyst with New Japan Securities,
Co. said the dollar in Tokyo inched down due to fears for the
dollar-selling intervention by central banks and concerns over a
release of the U.S. consumer price index for July, scheduled for
later Friday.
</TEXT>
