<FIRST>r a PM-Landlord-Discrimination     08-18 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Landlord-Discrimination,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Landlord Contests Minnesota Legal System on Living-In-Sin Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state of Minnesota has a triple
standard on premarital sex, says the lawyer for a man appealing a
finding of discrimination for refusing to rent to an unmarried
couple.
   James Anderson, who represented Marshall area resident Layle
French before the state Court of Appeals on Thursday, said the
state's fornication law is in conflict with a law that gives
unmarried couples the right to housing.
   Furthermore, he said, the state university system forbids couples
to cohabitate in dormitories _ an apparent violation of the
anti-discrimination law ordinary landlords must follow, Anderson
told the three-member panel.
   ``I don't see how they can have it both ways,'' he said.
   Hundreds of supporters of French, a carpenter, have turned out
for rallies throughout the state. In addition, petitions and letters
of encouragement have arrived from around the country, including one
from a group of about 40 Jewish Orthodox believers in the New York
City borough of Brooklyn, Anderson said.
   About 400 people from around the country have contributed $1 each
to a defense fund for French, which includes another $2,000 from
larger contributors, Anderson said.
   ``All discrimination is not bad,'' Anderson said. ``Layle's
discriminating against what many people view as immoral _
fornication.''
   Andrea Mitau Kircher, an assistant state attorney general,
countered Anderson's argument by saying the state university system
may be subject to different laws than ordinary landlords. She also
said the state's fornication law is possibly in violation of the
state Constitution and has been raised unsuccessfully as a defense
in similar cases.
   ``Landlords can't make rental decisions on the basis of marital
status,'' Kircher said.
   ``Living-in-sin'' issues are in legal flux elsewhere in the
United States:
   _In Denver, the City Council voted 7-6 in May to revoke a
living-in-sin ordinance that prohibited unmarried people from living
together.
   _In Massachusetts, three couples filed a lawsuit five years ago
charging they were illegally barred from public housing in Worcester
because they were unmarried. State law, like the one in Minnesota,
prohibits discrimination on the basis of marital status. A
commission and court have ruled in their favor, and the case is
pending before a state appeals court.
   In the Minnesota case, French agreed in February 1988 to rent his
former house in Marshall to Sue Parsons. But he said he quickly
changed his mind and returned her damage deposit after he decided it
would be against his religious beliefs. Parsons had told French she
would be living with her fiance. The two are now married.
   French said he is willing to pay the woman $348 in damages she
sustained by having to change her rental plans, but he refuses to
pay a $700 civil penalty imposed by an administrative law judge who
ruled June 7 that French violated the state's anti-discrimination
law.
   The appeals panel said it would rule within 90 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890818-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 0410EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Korea-Election     08-18 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Election,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Assembly Race Seen as Political Weather Vane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Election officials guarded polling
places today during balloting for a National Assembly seat in a
Seoul race that is viewed as a test of support for the governing
party.
   There were six candidates, including one sponsored by dissident
groups. Political analysts said the race was too close to call and
officials results were not expected until Saturday.
   The District Election Management Committee, already concerned
with charges of illegal campaigning, said today more than 100
election officials were stationed at polling places to guard against
violence and election fraud.
   President Roh Tae-woo of the Democratic Justice Party sent a
letter to party members in the district urging support for Rha
Woong-bae, a former deputy prime minister. Roh called the race ``a
litmus test which would determine the course the nation would take.''
   Kim Dae-jung, head of the largest opposition party, the Party for
Peace and Democracy, said the election was a midterm appraisal of
the government and predicted voters would side with the opposition.
Lee Yong-hee, a three-term lawmaker, is that party's candidate.
   The Yongdungpo district in southwestern Seoul is seen as a
microcosm of Korean political thinking. The district includes urban
middle-class workers, and laborers and because many of the voters
are newcomers to Seoul it reflects the regional antagonism in Korean
politics.
   In the last election, the winning candidate and two opposition
candidates were within 551 votes of each other. Election officials
say there are 168,812 registered voters in the district.
   Today's election was called after the Supreme Court ruled in May
that the 1988 election of governing party candidate Kim Myung-sup
was null and void because of illegal campaigning. Kim is not running.
   Charges of unfair campaigning have been widespread and include
vote buying, distribution of illegal materials, slander and illegal
meetings.
   On Thursday, the Central Election Management Committee ruled Roh
violated the law by sending letters to non-party members asking
voters to support the Democratic Justice Party candidate.
   The other candidates are Lee Won-bum, a former lawmaker from the
Reunification Democratic Party; Park Sang-woong of the New
Democratic Republican Party; Ko Young-koo, a lawyer running with
support from dissident groups; and Kim Hyung-joo, an independent
candidate.
</TEXT>
