<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-AirStrike     08-18 0135</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Air Strike,0139</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Airways Hit by One-Day Strike Over Sacking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A one-day strike by cabin crews forced British
Airways to cancel three-fourths of its flights today, the airline
said.
   Members of the Transport and General Workers' Union voted earlier
this month to strike in support of a cabin attendant who was fired
for allegedly selling complimentary drinks and pocketing the cash.
   Available staff were being used on international flights, and all
of British Airways domestic shuttle services were canceled.
   The airline reduced the crews assigned to flights to the minimum
required by the Civil Aviation Authority and either reduced or
eliminated catering services.
   The transport union's membership strength is concentrated among
short-haul crews based at Heathrow Airport. Most of the long-haul
staff has joined a breakaway union, Cabin Crew '89.
