<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Australian     08-18 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Australian,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Secretary Expresses Regret Over Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign secretary expressed regret
over the death of an Australian missionary slain in a hostage drama
and lawmakers today called for an investigation to determine if she
was shot by troops.
   Jacqueline Hamill, 36, of Sydney was among five hostages and 16
convicts who died Tuesday before troops recaptured the jail at Davao
City, 610 miles south of Manila. Convicts had seized the hostages
during religious services Sunday.
   Miss Hamill arrived in the Philippines last month.
   ``We regret she had to lose her life that way,'' Foreign
Secretary Raul Manglapus told reporters. ``She was pursuing a
vocation which required her to expose her life in extraordinary
ways. Under those circumstances, of course, sometimes it is not
possible to give full protection. We regret that happened.''
   In Sydney, officials said Philippine President Corazon Aquino had
written Prime Minister Bob Hawke to express ``heartfelt sorrow''
over Miss Hamill's murder, saying security forces were left with no
choice after the prison inmates started killing the captives.
   Mrs. Aquino also expressed condolences to Ms. Hamill's family,
the officials said.
   Miss Hamill bled to death after being shot in the back, according
to Philippine officials.
   Doctors said she apparently had been shot from a distance because
there were no powder burns on the body. This led to speculation that
she may have been shot by military snipers who returned gunfire when
convicts tried to escape using their captives as shields.
   Rep. Ramon Mitra, speaker of the House of Representatives, and
Sen. Victor Ziga of the Senate Defense Committee said they wanted an
investigation to determine whether Miss Hamill was shot by soldiers.
   ``That's very crucial,'' Ziga said. ``I have not heard of any
occasion where rescuers shot at prisoners and endangered the lives
of the hostages.''
   The Australian Embassy in Manila has also asked for clarification
of the circumstances of her death.
   Military Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa has promised the
armed forces will cooperate.
</TEXT>
