<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Strikes     08-18 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Strikes,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Russian Workers in Estonia Call Off Strikes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of Russian workers in Estonia
called off their crippling nine-day walkout today and labor leaders
began intensive talks with the Baltic republic's government, strike
organizers said.
   ``While the negotiations go on, the cannons are silent,'' strike
committee member Marat Chekatovsky said in a telephone interview
from the Estonian capital of Tallinn.
   Employees at about 50 factories and at the republic's ports and
railroads agreed to return to work after strike leaders and Estonian
officials set an agenda for negotiations Thursday, Chekatovksy said.
   State-run Moscow Radio reported early today that the talks were
meant to ``ease the highly charged political and economic situation
in Estonia and calm down ethnic passions.''
   The Russian workers walked out to protest a law passed Aug. 8 by
the Estonian parliament that set the Soviet Union's first residency
requirements for voters and candidates. Russians and other
non-ethnic Estonians, who make up about 40 percent of the republic's
population of 1.6 million, complained that about 80,000 of them
would be disenfranchised.
   The national Presidium on Wednesday declared the law
unconstitutional in a decision approved by President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   Chekatovksy said that although the strike might be renewed, it
had accomplished many of its organizers' goals.
   ``Moscow and the whole Soviet Union and the world started to pay
attention to us,'' he said.
   Strike leaders on Thursday said they planned to continue the
strike until Estonian leaders agreed to accept the Presidium's
decision and change the law, but Chekatovsky said strike committee
and factory representatives voted late Thursday to return to work.
   The strike ``was starting to work against us,'' he said,
referring to the growing economic difficulties it caused in the tiny
Baltic republic.
   Izvestia, the government daily, on Thursday quoted Railway
Minister Nikolai Konarev as saying the walkout had idled 3,000
railcars in Estonia, of which more than 700 were left on railway
lines, blocking dozens of trains from proceeding.
   In Tallinn alone, where all stations that load and unload freight
were paralyzed by the walkout, 34 trains carrying perishable
foodstuffs and other goods waited to be discharged Thursday, Konarev
said.
   In another area threatened by nationalist labor unrest, Russian
workers in Moldavia staged a two-hour warning strike Wednesday. They
were protesting a proposed law that would make Moldavian the
republic's official language.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
