<HEAD>Leland to Be Buried in Simple Casket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Mickey Leland, who rose from humble
circumstance and died helping the poor, will be buried in a casket
made of pine boards.
   Leland had asked to be buried in a ``plain pine box,'' as was
John de Menil, the late Houston millionaire Leland credited with
introducing him to a world of art and culture. De Menil died in 1973.
   ``In a letter Mickey wrote to his mother some time ago, he said
that was his wish, if he predated her in death,'' said the Rev.
William Lawson of Wheeler Avenue Baptist Church.
   Leland, D-Texas, who was killed in a plane crash while on a fact
finding trip to Ethiopia, will be buried in the Golden Gate Cemetery
in a private service.
   The congressman's family has been told that his remains will not
be returned to Houston until Tuesday at the earliest, Lawson said.
