<FIRST>r a PM-SCLCConvention     08-18 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SCLC Convention,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Activists: Time for Bush to Create Housing Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocates for the homeless say they're waiting for
HUD Secretary Jack Kemp to back up his rhetoric with cash for
housing programs.
   As Kemp spoke Thursday to a gathering of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference, his audience gave several standing ovations
but held to a wait-and-see attitude.
   ``We don't think it's reasonable or moral to have property
boarded up while people sleep in the streets and in shelters,'' said
SCLC President Joseph Lowery. ``While we are waiting, we've got to
utilize whatever funds are available to the best advantage. That's
why we are anxious to work with HUD.''
   Kemp delivered a brief address that reiterated his position of
improving housing for the poor and adopting a get-tough stance with
the scandal-ridden Department of Housing and Urban Development.
   But Washington homeless advocate Mitch Snyder responded to Kemp's
speech with an attack on the Bush administration for swiftly bailing
out savings and loan associations while ignoring funding needs for
housing.
   ``I didn't hear a ... word from Mr. Kemp about money. And I've
been waiting for him and his boss to start talking about money,''
Snyder said.
   Snyder said the housing budget proposed by the Bush
administration ``contained less money for housing than the last
budget that was introduced by Mr. Reagan.''
   Bush's 1990 budget allows $15.1 billion for housing, compared to
the $12.9 billion in the 1989 budget, drafted under Reagan. The 1988
budget, also under Reagan, allowed $18.6 billion for housing.
   Kemp spoke at the SCLC's 32nd annual convention about cleaning up
his department.
   ``I want to clean it out. I want to make sure it works for the
needy, not the greedy,'' Kemp said. ``We're going to make it work
for the poor again. I pledge that to you.''
   He left soon after the speech for Washington.
   Comedian-activist Dick Gregory, a panelist, expressed displeasure
with Kemp's speedy departure.
   ``We need to bring Kemp not to speak, but to listen,'' Gregory
said.
   The SCLC has placed homelessness atop its national agenda. In
April, with the help of Snyder and several local homeless advocacy
groups, it seized a boarded-up, foreclosed Atlanta house and cleaned
it up for use by the homeless.
   The SCLC then arranged for a Florida S&amp;L to sell the house to a
homeless couple for $10,000.
</TEXT>
