<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     08-18 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Rain Causes Flooding, Power Outages in Utah</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms flooded towns in Utah and Arizona today, while
showers fell across much of the southern and central United States.
   Heavy rain warnings were issued from Tennessee and Kentucky
across the central Atlantic Coast and from Colorado across New
Mexico and western Texas, in Utah and central Arizona.
   Thundershowers rolled over much of Utah beginning late Thursday,
bringing hail and winds up to 67 mph.
   ``My peach tree spiraled up in the air about 30 feet and then
came down in the backyard. I've never seen anything like it
before,'' South Salt Lake resident Dorothy Russett said.
   Orangeville, Utah, reported 1.14 inches of rain in an hour, and
two canals overflowed. Flooding also was reported in Castle Dale and
Price.
   The storm caused power lines over much of Salt Lake City to arc
about 6:30 p.m. Thursday and ``transformers were sparking
everywhere,'' a fire dispatcher said. Authorities reported many
scattered outages and said a few dozen customers were without power
early today.
   Heavy rain caused flooding at Tucson, Ariz., and winds gusted to
52 mph near Phoenix, while small hail fell at Lichtfield Park.
   Hail clattered over portions of central Kentucky, with floods in
Paris and roaring winds that uprooted trees and damaged buildings in
Scott.
   A waterspout formed over Biscayne Bay, Fla., Thursday night, then
moved across the Venetian Causeway and damaged a house.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT included
3 inches at Virginia Beach. Va., 1} inches at Jackson, Ky., and
nearly an inch at Prescott, Ariz.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
Virginias across Georgia, Alabama, southern Mississippi and parts of
Gulf Coast, over southern Florida and the northern Plains, and from
eastern Montana across New Mexico and northern Arizona. Sunny
weather was expected over the rest of the nation.
   Highs were predicted in the 90s over North Dakota, Utah,
southwest Oregon and central California, southern Arizona, Texas,
the lower Mississippi Valley and Florida; near 110 degrees in the
desert Southwest; and in the 70s and 80s over much of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 43
degrees at Alpena, Mich., to 90 degrees at Blythe, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 71 foggy; Boston 65 fair; Buffalo 51 fair;
Charleston, S.C., 70 fair; Cleveland 59 partly cloudy; Detroit 54
partly cloudy; Miami 80 fair; New York 68 cloudy; Philadelphia 70
fair; Portland, Maine, 59 fair; Washington, D.C, 73 hazy.
   _Central: Chicago 68 fair; Denver 68 partly cloudy; Des Moines 64
fair; Fort Worth 74 foggy; Indianapolis 65 cloudy; Kansas City 63
fair; New Orleans 73 partly cloudy; St. Louis 66 fair;
Minneapolis-St. Paul 63 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 66 cloudy; Phoenix 87 partly cloudy; Salt Lake
City 64 cloudy; San Diego 67 cloudy; San Francisco 57 fair; Seattle
63 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 55 fair; Toronto 52 fair.
</TEXT>
