<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 0644EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SmithFuneral     08-18 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smith Funeral,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Funeral Mass Mourns Rep. Larkin Smith</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BILOXI, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Larkin Smith's widow characterized her
husband as a good family man as well as a loyal public servant.
   ``Larkin loved his family,'' Sheila Smith said Thursday during
the funeral Mass for the freshman Mississippi congressman. ``He
always held my hand and held me close to him. He always made me feel
special.''
   Standing with their daughter, Tracy, and 6-month-old grandson,
Bryce Anthony, Mrs. Smith said she and her husband ``always joked
about death'' and ``he wanted his epitaph to read, `Mission aborted,
gone home.'''
   The 45-year-old Republican was killed Sunday night as he traveled
to his home in Gulfport from Hattiesburg, where he had thrown out
the first pitch in a youth baseball series. The bodies of Smith and
pilot Chuck Vierling were found Monday in the scattered wreckage of
a single-engine Cessna 177.
   Investigators with the National Transportation Safety Board have
said Vierling, 58, apparently strayed from his anticipated flight
path on the 70-mile trip before clipping a tree in the DeSoto
National Forest.
   NTSB officials said Thursday that they had ruled out mechanical
problems as a cause of the crash. The investigation now centers on
weather conditions and the pilot's actions, said Jeff Kennedy, a
NTSB investigator.
   About 20 congressmen arrived from Washington to attend the
funeral at the Mississippi Coast Convention Center in Biloxi. Most
of the state's top political leaders and several hundred law
enforcement officers from Mississippi, Alabama and Louisiana also
were among about 3,000 mourners.
   Catholic Bishop Joseph Howze of the Biloxi Diocese, who delivered
the eulogy, said Smith ``lived a life of faith, hope and love in
following after the pattern set by Christ.''
   Howze said Smith, a member of a Pass Christian parish, ``shared
the challenge of creating a better world'' and demonstrated ``a
solid commitment to everything he encountered.''
   ``He was dedicated, he was honest, he was professional, he was
helpful,'' said Joe Price, chief deputy with the Harrison County
Sheriff's Department, which Smith headed before going to Washington,
D.C., in January.
   Smith spent 22 years in law enforcement, serving also as police
chief in Gulfport.
</TEXT>
