<DOCNO> AP890818-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 0707EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland-Sketches     08-18 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Sketches,0717</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veteran Solidarity Activist Candidates for Prime Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are sketches of the three candidates
proposed by Solidarity leader Lech Walesa on Thursday for the post
of prime minister:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BRONISLAW GEREMEK _ In April, when Solidarity was legalized after
a seven-year ban, Geremek faced a tough decision: whether to return
after years of opposition activity to the academic world of medieval
studies or continue to serve Solidarity's march to democracy as a
top adviser.
   The 57-year-old professor, fluent in French and proficient in at
least two other languages, chose Solidarity.
   Geremek became a well-known figure in the opposition in the late
1970s when he lectured on officially taboo topics of Polish history
and culture in private apartments as part of the so-called ``Flying
University'' created in the late 1970s.
   He crossed paths with workers during the Gdansk strikes in August
1980.
   Soon after the strikes broke out, Geremek and Tadeusz Mazowiecki,
another Solidarity candidate for prime minister, rushed north with a
letter signed by intellectuals urging authorities to find a solution
without force.
   The strikers invited Geremek and Mazowiecki to stay at the strike
as their advisers.
   The historian's life has not been the same since.
   He was arrested Dec. 13, 1981, when martial-law was declared. He
was released a year later and then fired in 1985 from his academic
job because of his continued role as a Solidarity adviser.
   Geremek was elected a deputy to parliament in the June elections
and then chosen to lead the Solidarity caucus.
   He is one of Walesa's chief representatives in meetings with top
foreign officials. Since the union was legalized in April, he has
traveled to West Germany and France for meetings with senior
officials and last week met Pope John Paul II in Rome.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JACEK KURON _ The longtime rebel, now 55, is one of the fiercest
fighters for greater democracy in Poland.
   The Communist Party lost the young recruit by expelling him from
the party eight months after he joined in March 1953 for refusing to
submit to a required session of self-criticism.
   A historian and teacher, Kuron's 1964 ``Open Letter to Party''
criticized the Communist system for abusing workers. For it, he
served three years in prison.
   Authorities accused him of instigating student demonstrations in
1968 and kept him in jail for another 3{ years.
   In 1976, he helped found the Committee for the Defense of Workers
to help workers fired from their jobs and forced to stand trial
after worker riots that year.
   A tireless pamphleteer, Kuron seemed born for politics. There was
hardly an important opposition declaration he didn't sign in the
1970s, and in 1980 he became an adviser to strikers in Gdansk.
   He, too, was rounded up on the December 1981 night that
martial-law was proclaimed.
   Released in an amnesty in 1984, Kuron immediately began holding
news conferences and issuing reports on the conditions of those
still in jail.
   Elected a deputy in the June elections, Kuron is on the presidium
of the Solidarity caucus in parliament.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   TADEUSZ MAZOWIECKI _ Mazowiecki, 62, is the least public
candidate for prime minister, a close confidant of Walesa with
strong ties to the Roman Catholic Church.
   Mazowiecki, trained as a lawyer, was one of the founders in 1957
of the Warsaw Club of Catholic Intelligentsia, known in Polish as
KIK, an influential forum that served as a bulwark for Catholic
opposition to communist ideology.
   He served in parliament as part of ZNAK, a group of Roman
Catholics who supported regeneration of Poland based on Catholic
values.
   Mazowiecki initiated a letter by more than 60 intellectuals
urging authorities to find a peaceful solution to the strikes that
broke out on the Baltic coast in August 1980 and led to the
formation of the independent Solidarity trade union.
   He was jailed during martial-law, and when released became
Walesa's assistant and remained a top adviser to Walesa during the
years that the union was banned.
   He did not run for parliament, preferring to edit Tygodnik
Solidarnosc, the Solidarity weekly revived after the union was
legalized in April.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
