<HEAD>Police Search for Highway Robbers</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: To CORRECT to teachers' sted teacher's, SUB 2nd graf, `Police
said...' Pickup 3rd graf, `Kim Yong-man...'</UNK>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police began a search today for four
men who made off with $1 million in cash during a robbery on a busy
highway.
   Police said the robbers, all in their 20s or 30s, Thursday
stopped in front of a car carrying two men transporting teachers'
salaries near Kongju, in the central part of the country.
   Kim Yong-man, 33, told police three of the robbers, one of whom
had a gun, forced him and his companion to get out of the car. The
three bandits then jumped in the car containing the cash and drove
off, followed by the fourth robber in another car, police said.
   They said many cars were traveling on the highway when the
robbery occurred about noon. One witness said she saw a man holding
a gun when she drove by, but thought it was an officer, police said.
   The stolen money was to be paid as salaries to teachers and
school staff in the Kongju district.
   Salaries in Korea are usually paid in cash.
