<SECOND>PM-Bank Fraud, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0509,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Argentine Financier Pleads Guilty In $38 Million Bank Fraud</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Finkielstein has...', to CORRECT spelling of
Finkielstain.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Argentine financier faces a maximum sentence
of 25 years in jail and fines and restitution totaling $114 million
after pleading guilty of defrauding his now-defunct bank.
   Jacobo Finkielstain, 51, of Buenos Aires entered his plea
Thursday before U.S. District Judge Michael Mukasey on charges he
participated in a scheme to defraud the Central Bank of New York, of
which he was 99 percent owner, of $38 million.
   He pleaded guilty as part of an agreement with prosecutors on
five counts of a 29-count indictment that was handed down in
January. His trial had been scheduled to begin Monday.
   He will be sentenced Oct. 20.
   The Central Bank of New York, a federally insured bank, was
closed and placed in receivership by the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp. in September 1987.
   Finkielstain has extensive real estate holdings in Argentina and
owns several companies, including the movie production house that
produced the film ``The Official Story,'' which won an Academy Award
in 1986 for best foreign film.
   He faces a maximum sentence of 25 years in prison, fines totaling
$76 million and an additional $38 million in restitution, U.S.
Attorney Benito Romano said in a statement.
   Finkielstain remains free on $30 million bail on condition he
stay in the United States.
</TEXT>
