<DOCNO> AP890818-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 0934EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DoingBusinessWithMarxists 1stld-writethrndEasternShoreNewsSummary
  08-18 0824</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Doing Business With Marxists, 1st ld-writethru, a0425,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Leland Tragedy Could Help Open the Door in Ethiopia</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update, adds 2 grafs after 5th previous, ``The Soviets''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethiopia, a proud and historic country now
under Marxist rule, could be the prize as the Soviet Union gradually
loosens its ties to client states and the United States tries to
cope with famine and hunger in Africa.
   The death in an air crash last week of Rep. Mickey Leland, a
Texas Democrat who was a strong friend to Ethiopia and anyone
suffering from hunger, touched off a cooperative search that is
likely to lead to better relations _ provided two U.S. conditions
are met.
   Those conditions, as outlined by senior State Department
officials, are a continuing improvement in human rights and a
serious effort by Addis Ababa to reconcile with separationists in
Ethiopia's Eritrea region and an autonomous movement in Tigray.
   ``There exists a window of opportunity evolving from this
tragedy,'' said Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y., who served with Leland
on the House Select Committee on Hunger and was in the helicopter
that spotted the Leland plane's wreckage.
   ``The Soviets have said they are cutting Ethiopia off. Ethiopia
needs to be adopted and supported by somebody.''
   On Thursday, former President Carter announced Thursday that he
will serve as a neutral observer when Ethiopian officials and
leaders of a rebel group hold preliminary peace talks next month at
Carter's policy center in Atlanta, Ga.
   Carter said the talks between the government of Ethiopia and the
Eritrean People's Liberation Front will last for several days and
will lay the groundwork for further negotiations toward ending the
Ethiopian civil war.
   Congress prefers the United States not deal with Marxist-Leninist
governments. Laws restrict official business with Ethiopia, and the
1961 Foreign Assistance Act bars U.S. aid to many comunist
countries, with exceptions.
   Other laws prohibit U.S. support for international loans to
countries that systematically violate human rights and bar aid to
countries that have not paid their debts _ both of which apply to
Ethiopia.
   Ethiopia is eligible for humanitarian assistance, and during a
1988 famine the United States provided about $120 million _ the
largest outlay to any African country that year.
   Not one Ethiopian died in the drought, a U.S. official said
Thursday with evident pride.
   U.S. foreign policy is governed by complex considerations and not
just the political stripe of a country _ as evidenced by President
Bush's offer of economic development aid to Poland and Hungary in a
bid to encourage capitalism in those East European countries.
   The fact that there are about 2,000 political prisoners in
Ethiopia is considered a much larger obstacle to friendlier U.S.
relations than the governing Marxist philosophy in Addis Ababa.
   Ethiopia is the oldest independent country in Africa and one of
the oldest in the world. Its ties to Moscow began with the signing
of a military assistance agreement in 1976. The next year Ethiopia
scrapped its weapons pact with the United States, and Soviet arms
and Cuban troops helped Ethiopia expel Somali forces from the Ogaden
region in 1977 and 1978.
   The United States did not break off relations with Ethiopia,
which date back to 1903. But its embassies are not headed by
ambassadors _ a sign of U.S. distaste for the regime of President
Mengistu Haile Mariam.
   Nonetheless, Uncle Sam has been ready with a helping hand.
   ``Our major interest is the welfare of the people,'' said a
senior U.S. official of humanitarian assistance to Ethiopia or any
other Marxist country.
   There are strategic motivations, as well, for the gradual
improvement in relations.
   Ackerman stressed foreign policy considerations in an interview
Wednesday.
   The guerrillas in Eritrea and Tigray ``are beating (Mengistu) to
a pulp,'' Ackerman said. ``If Ethiopia gets severed you basically
have Arab control of the whole border of the Red Sea. It would be
giving the region away to the Arab world. Government by
fundamentalism is a tremendous threat.''
   Therefore, the congressman said, the Bush administration should
upgrade its relations with Mengistu.
   ``He is willing to make concessions, to act out of his need for
survival,'' Ackerman concluded.
   Some State Department officials offer a somewhat different
analysis. The Eritrean People's Liberation Front, which has been at
war with the central government for 27 years, is about 50 percent
Christian in background, and fundamentalism is not a driving force
in neighboring Somalia.
   Still, Ackerman and the State Department officials agree that it
would be good to improve relations.
   ``A friendly and coherent Ethiopia would have an effect on its
neighbors, too,'' said a senior U.S. official. ``Access to that part
of the world is important. It shouldn't be overstated. It is an area
that is important to be open and not to have doors closed to us.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid heads the AP's State Department
staff.
</TEXT>
