<SECOND>PM-Lottery Ticket,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Families Feud Over Who Owns $24 Million Lottery Ticket</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The eight folks who showed up to claim a $24
million lottery prize last month aren't smiling any more, now that
one of them has sued six of the others claiming they aren't entitled
to any of the winnings.
   James Macieko, 42, of Bellmore contends in court papers filed
Thursday that he and his fiancee, Catherine Salenga, 38, of Dix
Hills, were the only true winners in the July 12 drawing, the
fifth-biottery history.
   He charged that he was intimidated and threatened with the loss
of the prize money to include the other six, all members oggest in state
lf the
Welsch family of New York, in the winning ticket. The Welsches deny
the charge.
   Macieko is the former owner of the Liberty Card Store, where the
winning ticket was purchased. He and Salenga sold the shop to
brothers William, Frank and Joseph Welsch a year ago.
   Macieko said he had played Lotto at the card shop twice a week
for the past 10 years using the same numbers _ 1, 4, 9, 16, 24, 32.
In court papers, Macieko contends he had an arrangement with William
Welsch to play those numbers twice a week on his behalf.
   During a July 17 news conference to announce jackpot winners,
Macieko and Salenga, the three Welsch brothers and three other
family members said they had been buying tickets as a group everreplied
that although Macieko picked the numbers, Welsch had
bought the ticket _ and that made Welsch the winner.
   ``I pleaded with him, `Don't do this to me,''' Macieko said in
court papers. Welsch then agreed to give Macieko and Salenga a cut
of the prize, he said.
   Macieko said that at first, he accepted a share of the prize,
because he feared that ``if I didn't accept the offer as proposed, I
would get nothing.'' But in his suit, he argues that he and his
fiancee should get the whole amount.
   The Welsches denied any wrongdoing, saying that the story told at
the news conference is the true one.
   ``Macieko is a greedy S.O.B.,'' said Frank Welsch. ``Those two
are trying to horn in and get a greater part of the share.''
   The first of 20 yearly prize checks was to be sent this week, but
the court ordered the distribution of the money postponed while the
case is pending.
