<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia 1stLd-Writethru   08-18 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0503,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prague Rejects Polish Condemnation of 1968 Invasion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 4 grafs to UPDATE with East German reaction. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament and state-run media
today criticized a resolution passed by the Polish parliament
condemning the 1968 Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia.
   The government said Thursday it will come down hard on any
protests Monday marking the 21st anniversary of the invasion that
crushed the brief reform period known as ``Prague Spring.''
   In its reaction to the Polish parliament's vote Thursday, the
presidium of the Czechoslovak parliament said it ``is taken aback by
these declarations which ... are a gross interference in internal
affairs of Czechoslovakia and categorically rejects them.''
   The resolution adopted by the Polish Sejm, the lower house of the
National Assembly, said the Soviet-led invasion ``violated every
nation's inalienable right to self-determination and its natural
desire for democracy, freedom and respect of human rights.''
   On Tuesday, Hungary's Communist Party said its ``present
leadership ... does not concur with the 1968 military intervention
in Czechoslovakia'' but that assessing the event ``should be the
right and task of the Czechoslovak people and the Czechoslovak
Communist Party.''
   The 1968 invasion crushed a short-lived liberalization period
spearheaded by then Communist Party leader Alexander Dubcek, who was
ousted in April 1969.
   Communist East Germany, meanwhile, strongly defended the invasion.
   New Germany, the East German Communist Party daily newspaper,
claimed that the United States and West Germany led ``imperialist
forces'' trying to influence Czechoslovak affairs in the days before
the Warsaw Pact invasion.
   The newspaper commentary reiterated the hard line East Germany
has adhered to while allied Hungary, Poland and the Soviet Union
have introduced economic and social reforms and begun a reassessment
of their pasts.
   East Germany has resisted the reforms advocated by Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, and it has given little attention in the
state-run media to the democratic advances sweeping Poland and
Hungary.
</TEXT>
