<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-ChildSlayings     08-18 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Child Slayings,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspect Confesses to Slaying of Fourth Girl</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 26-year-old man who confessed to the brutal
slayings of three young girls that terrorized a suburban Tokyo
neighborhood said he also kidnapped and killed a fourth girl, a
newspaper said today.
   The deaths of the four girls have deeply shocked Japan, and Prime
Minister Toshiki Kaifu and other government officials today urged
police to fully investigate the string of murders.
   Tsutomu Miyazaki, a printing shop assistant, recently admitted
under police questioning that he killed Masami Yoshizawa, the Japan
Broadcasting Corp. and Asahi Shimbun newspaper quoted police as
saying.
   Miyazaki confessed he had kidnapped and killed Masami, age 7, and
``buried her in the mountains,'' Asahi Shimbun said. Masami has been
missing since October, when she left her home in Saitama prefecture,
north of Tokyo, to play.
   A Tokyo Metropolitan Police official declined to comment on the
reports.
   Miyazaki is under arrest for kidnapping and killing 5-year-old
Ayako Nomoto. On Sunday, two days after his arrest, he also
confessed that he had kidnapped and killed two other girls, Mari
Konno and Erika Namba, both age 4, police officials said.
   In a country with remarkably little crime, the killings and
Miyazaki's confessions have received extensive media coverage.
Television stations have shown pictures of the inside of his home,
filled from floor to ceiling with comic books and about 4,500
videos, including many animated films.
   Viewers also have heard his former co-workers, teachers and
school mates, neighbors, parents of victims and handwriting analysts
comment on the cruelty of the murders.
   But some people have criticized the reporting for going too far.
In its current issue, the liberal weekly magazine Asahi Journal said
that competition among the media had been excessive.
   Miyazaki was handed over to prosecutors Sunday. Under Japanese
law, prosecutors have a maximum of 20 days to collect evidence
against him before releasing him or bringing formal charges.
</TEXT>
