<FIRST>r i PM-China 2ndLd-Writethru   08-18 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0508,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Holiday Scrapped; President Reportedly Detains Defense
Chief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to ADD date of scheduled celebrations. Pickup
4th graf pvs, ``Military reviews...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has scrapped plans to mark its 40th National
Day with a military parade, according to official reports, in an
apparent move to avoid reminding people of the crackdown on the
pro-democracy movement.
   In another development, Chinese sources said President Yang
Shangkun, a central figure in the June crackdown, had ordered the
defense minister and several commanders detained to strengthen his
control of the military.
   National Day marks the establishment of communist rule in China.
This year's celebrations, scheduled for Oct. 1, were to have been
the most elaborate in five years.
   Military reviews, held annually from 1949 to 1959, were suspended
for 25 years. When they were revived in 1984, the reviews were to
have been part of National Day celebrations every five years.
   But Beijing Mayor Chen Xitong said Thursday no parade was planned
this year. He gave no reason, but his decision came two months after
the government dispatched troops and tanks to crush the seven-week
democracy movement.
   Beijing has been under martial law since May 20, and troops armed
with assault rifles have guarded the city since the crackdown began
June 3-4.
   The government says 200 people were killed when soldiers marched
on Beijing. Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence reports say
up to 3,000 people died.
   Chen said National Day flower displays will be set up again this
year in Tiananmen Square, the site of the student-led pro-democracy
demonstrations, but that only organized groups would be allowed in.
   Fireworks, parties, sports events and theatrical performances are
planned at parks, gymnasiums and theaters throughout the city, he
said.
   In 1984, Beijing celebrated National Day with a day of
festivities in the square, including a 1,200-piece military band, 18
formations of foot soldiers and 24 formations of military equipment
including anti-tank missiles, rocket mine-laying vehicles and
artillery. A civilian parade included 140,000 people.
   In the military power struggle, soldiers loyal to Yang went to
the Beijing residence of Defense Minister Qin Jiwei on Wednesday and
took him and one of his armed guards away, said the Chinese sources,
who demanded anonymity.
   The sources contacted The Associated Press separately. One is a
military officer who telephoned Hong Kong Thursday morning from
Beijing, and the other is a businessman, based in Hong Kong, who
says he has extensive contacts within the Chinese military.
   A Defense Ministry official said today he knew nothing about the
reports. Other offices in the Defense Ministry did not answer their
telephones today.
   Qin and Yang have been competing to become first vice chairman of
the Central Military Commission, China's top military body. The post
was left vacant by the dismissal of Zhao Ziyang on June 24 after he
expressed sympathy for the pro-democracy demonstrators.
   Other troops detained the heads of the Beijing, Guangzhou and
Nanjing military districts, who supported Qin, the sources said.
</TEXT>
