<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Trotsky     08-18 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Trotsky,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Press Publishes Trotsky Letters Criticizing Communist Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet press has published letters Leon Trotsky
wrote more than 60 years ago criticizing the Communist Party, the
latest step toward improving the image of the late party leader.
   In its August edition, the monthly youth journal Molodoi
Kommunist published several letters Trotsky wrote in the 1920s
complaining about the party bureaucracy.
   ``There is a tendency toward a greater and greater contradiction
between a few thousand people in command and the rest of the party
members,'' Trotsky wrote in a 1923 letter that appeared in Pravda
that year.
   The criticism is particularly relevant now as the party tries to
halt a loss of prestige and faith among the citizenry. President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev has called for a ``renewal'' of the 20
million-member party.
   As Trotsky did a half-century ago, many Soviets now blame the
party bureaucracy for impeding reform.
   Because of that criticism and other differences, dictator Josef
Stalin ordered Trotsky ousted from the party in 1927 and exiled him
two years later. Stalin had his foe killed in Mexico in 1940.
   Trotsky was close to Soviet founder Vladimir I. Lenin and helped
direct the 1917 coup that brought the Bolsheviks to power. He was
branded an enemy when Stalin took over.
   In November 1987, Gorbachev became the first Soviet leader in
decades to mention Trotsky publicly but condemned his call for world
revolution. Since then, Pravda has published an article
acknowledging the key role Trotsky played in the Russian Revolution
and Civil War.
   Officials have so far taken the stance that Trotsky's views were
wrong and his full rehabilitation soon is unlikely.
   In the letters reprinted in Molodoi Kommunist, Trotsky said
democracy was impossible to achieve in the Soviet Union but ``at the
same time, absolute centralism is incompatible with the nature of
the mass party.''
</TEXT>
