<FIRST>r a PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0439 08-18 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0439,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Goes Boating</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 4 grafs new with Bush boating; picks up at pvs 2nd graf,
Officials said</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush took an ocean spin in
his speed boat today as he interspersed relaxation with updates on
political developments in Poland.
   Under bright, sunny skies, the president went by car to nearby
Biddeford where the power boat, Fidelity, was tied up in a yacht
harbor. Accompanied by local fishing buddy Bob Boilard, sons George
and Neil and the wife of his other son, Marvin, the president sped
out to sea, trailed by Secret Service agents in other boats.
   He cheerily waved off reporters' attempts to engage him in
conversation. ``Photo op,'' he said, referring to his rule about not
answering questions at occasions where he wants to be photographed
only.
   Bush on Thursday vowed to play golf every day until returning to
Washington on Sept. 4.
   Officials said the president was monitoring the moves that could
lead to a non-communist government in Poland but wasn't directly
involved in phone conversations with Polish or other East bloc
leaders.
   On the first full day of his three-week vacation, Bush passed up
an opportunity to respond directly to news that Polish President
Wojciech Jaruzelski had approved Solidarity leader Lech Walesa's
plan for a coalition government.
   However, administration officials privately were enthusiastic.
   Bush was on the golf course when reporters asked his reaction to
the developments in Poland.
   ``No comment,'' he replied.
   But the president was in a jovial mood as he raced around the 18
holes of a local course with his son, George W. Bush of Texas, and
club pro Ken Raynor.
   When reporters ran into a blank wall on the Poland issue, they
asked how his vacation was going.
   ``Now we're talking,'' the president replied.
   Vowing that he would play golf every day before he returns to
Washington, Bush joked to the accompanying pool of reporters, ``You
guys mind coming with us?''
   Bush was surrounded at Kennebunkport by numerous offspring and
grandchildren as well as his wife, Barbara, at the family home on
Walker's Point.
   He went boating on the ocean and played tennis under
picture-perfect bright sunny skies.
   Bush and his advisers were said to be pleased at the apparent
trend in Poland, but were choosing their words cautiously.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the
administration didn't want to ``upset the apple cart.''
   Bush was briefed on the Polish developments by Deputy National
Security Adviser Robert Gates, who accompanied him to Kennebunkport.
   ``Two years ago, no one in the United States would have predicted
this could happen,'' said a senior administration official who spoke
on condition of anonymity. ``Of course we're happy, extremely
happy.''
   Fitzwater said Bush, who voiced strong support for recent
political reforms during his trip to Poland last month, was not
endorsing Walesa or any other candidate.
   ``It is a sensitive situation there in terms of the general
movement away from the communist control,'' Fitzwater said.
   Bush and Walesa discussed the possibility of Walesa becoming
prime minister when the two had lunch in Gdansk last month,
Fitzwater said.
   Walesa has voiced reservations this week about accepting the post.
   Bush and Walesa ``talked about the political process and the
prospects and about Lech Walesa's personal feelings about his
role,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``The president understands the various pressures that are on Mr.
Walesa and he (Walesa) is very concerned about the new government,
about Solidarity's ability to step in and take over the new
government.''
</TEXT>
