<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1007EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Mood 1stLd-Writethru   08-18 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Mood, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0455,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surprise, Hope And Sober Optimism Greet Historic Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 7th graf, `President Wojciech...' to UPDATE with reported
choice for prime minister. Pickup 8th, `The continuing...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poles are excited by stunning changes that
could lead to a non-communist government nearly eight years after a
martial law crackdown, and they hope the transition will revive the
nation's collapsing economy.
   Even in June, when the freest Polish elections in 40 years were
held, it would have been hard to believe the independent Solidarity
movement would do so well that it would force the first
non-communist government in the East bloc.
   A 20-year-old Catholic university student said she was surprised
at the historic changes that took place during her vacation the last
two weeks.
   ``I didn't expect all this when going for a holiday,'' she said
Thursday.
   ``The elections were only two months ago. ... But the abundance
of events is so great, out of proportion to the calendar,'' added a
middle-age man who was out with his dog.
   The young woman's homecoming and the man's evening walk were the
routine events of a day during which the seemingly inconceivable had
occurred.
   President Wojciech Jaruzelski, a Communist, was reported Thursday
to have agreed to nominate a prime minister from Solidarity, the
trade union he sought to crush with martial law in 1981. A
government official today said Jaruzelski's choice was Tadeusz
Mazowiecki, a journalist and longtime Solidarity activist.
   The continuing influence of the opposition union had shown the
world that the course of communism could be challenged, albeit as
much from the pressure of a national economic crisis as from
arguments about democracy.
   For the first time in the East bloc, the communists appear to be
on the verge of turning over the power to form a government.
   ``Now those who were under the wagon are on it,'' Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa told the West German ZDF television network after
his historic meeting with Jaruzelski Thursday.
   But in Warsaw's streets during the sultry summer evening,
surprise was tempered by a nearly exhausted faith in government.
   ``The point is not who it is going to be, as long as it is a
person who pulls us out from the pit,'' said a middle-age bookstore
worker waiting for the tram home.
   ``We want people who would care for the good of the country. We
don't care whether it is Solidarity, the Communist Party or some
other. The point is to get us out of this pit,'' said a retired
teacher a half-mile away at the central train station.
   His daughter-in-law spoke for others absorbed in dealing with
daily difficulties posed by inflation and shortages.
   ``One leads such a monotonous way of life _ home, work, family,
children, lines _ that one does not have time to be interested in
politics,'' she said.
   But she added, ``I think this is a great prospect of something
new.''
</TEXT>
