<FIRST>r a PM-FourKilled     08-18 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Four Killed,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Children Killed in Fire Believed Started by TV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire apparently started by a faulty
television set raced through a home this morning, killing four
children, police and firefighters said.
   Killed in the early-morning blaze on the city's north side were
Mary Massey, 11, Paula Massey, 10, Rena Hines, 12, and Lena
Ferguson, 6.
   The 6-year-old was visiting the other three children, whose
parents, James Massey and Patricia Hines, managed to escape, said
Syracuse Police Investigator Rod Carr.
   Carr said all four children were found dead by firefighters in a
bedroom on the second floor of the home shortly after 5 a.m. The
parents woke up when they smelled smoke but were unable to get
upstairs to the children, authorities said.
   There were no smoke detectors in the home, which was engulfed in
flames when firefighters arrived. Fire investigators believe the
fire started in a faulty television set, Carr said.
   ``I can't say it would have made a difference, but the parents
woke up after they smelled smoke,'' said Deputy Fire Chief Richard
Buck. ``Smoke detectors might have given them a few more minutes.''
</TEXT>
