<FIRST>r a PM-Designer-Contempt     08-18 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Designer-Contempt,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Designer Found In Contempt For Ads Placed About Estranged Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge found fashion designer Hattie
Belkin in contempt of court after learning she ran an advertisement
offering cash to men who would tell her they underwent vasectomies
performed by her estranged husband.
   Oakland County Circuit Judge Francis X. O'Brien also ordered
Wednesday that Ms. Belkin pay $1,000 to her husband, Dr. Richard
Belkin. The couple own Hattie boutiques, featuring Ms. Belkin's
designs, in Palm Beach, Fla.; the Detroit suburb of Birmingham; and
Scottsdale, Ariz.
   As part of the couple's bitter divorce proceeding, O'Brien had
ordered Ms. Belkin not to interfere with her husband's practice. The
judge said Ms. Belkin could go to jail if she interferes again.
   The contempt hearing was prompted by an advertisement Ms. Belkin
placed in the July 27 edition of the Northeast Detroiter, a weekly
newspaper. In it, she offered $25 payments for information about
vasectomies performed at her husband's clinic.
   Ms. Belkin placed the ad in an effort to determine her husband's
income, said her attorney, Mayer Morganroth. She would not comment
on Wednesday's hearing.
   O'Brien said he believed she acted out of frustration with the
couple's 2-year-old divorce case, scheduled to go to trial Sept. 7.
``Obviously, we are dealing with a lot of bucks,'' he said. ``The
point is, the longer it takes, the more frustrating it becomes.''
   The couple's single largest asset is the boutique chain.
</TEXT>
