<DOCNO> AP890818-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1207EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0507 08-18 0872</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0507,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Not Considering Increase in Aid to Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New throughout with Fitzwater reaction, Dole trip, developments
in Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is not considering expanding the
$119 million economic aid package he has proposed for Poland despite
the non-communist government taking shape in the East bloc nation,
his spokesman said today.
   Asked in Kennebunkport, Maine, where Bush is vacationing, whether
the changes in Poland would justify more financial incentives,
presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater told reporters: ``It's
really premature to think along those lines.''
   He also said he administration would have no comment on reports
of the selection of Tadeusz Mazowiecki, editor of the newspaper of
the independent trade union Solidarity, as the new prime minister
until the parliamentary process is completed and the new leaders are
ratified.
   ``The situation is changing rapidly there,'' Fitzwater said. ``We
would prefer not to have any further comment on the process until we
have some assurances on how the government is going to be formed.''
   Meeting last month with Bush in Poland, Solidarity chairman Lech
Welesa asked for $10 billion in U.S. aid to rebuild the Polish
economy, which is saddled with a $39 billion debt to Western
governments and banks.
   Bush responded with the $119 million package that will include
$100 million over three years for loans to Poles trying to start
capitalist enterprises; $5 million to clean pollution in Krakow and
$4 million to be spent through the U.S. Labor Department to study
social and work issues in Poland.
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole and her husband, Senate Republican
leader Bob Dole, left Washington today on a 10-day trip that wil
include meetings with officials in Poland next week.
   Sen. Dole said, ``I think right now it's a time of great
excitement and expectations. But I do believe that if you look at it
realistically, there are some tough days ahead.''
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Thursday that the
administration was still drafting proposed legislation on the
president's aid package for presentation to Congress when it returns
from recess next month.
   Fitzwater on Thursday described the political change in Poland as
``a sensitive situation there in terms of the general movement away
from the communist control.''
   Bush does not want ``to do anything or say anything to upset the
apple cart. ... We're very reluctant to involve ourselves in a more
direct fashion,'' he said.
   ``Certainly a non-communist government would be a remarkable and
history-making occurrence,'' Fitzwater said.
   But one senior administration official described the mood as
jubilant.
   ``Two years ago, no one in the United States would have predicted
this could happen. Of course we're happy, extremely happy,'' said
the official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   ``These changes are the most important upheavals in Eastern
Europe and in the Soviet world since the death of Stalin,'' Zbigniew
Brzezinski, a native of Poland who was former President Carter's
national security adviser, said today on ``CBS This Morning.'' ``And
they have enormous implications for the future of communism and the
East-West relations. ... We are seeing the end of an entire era.''
   State Department spokesman Boucher issued a statement clearly
designed to warn the Kremlin not to invoke the Brezhnev doctrine,
used in the past to justify the use of force to prevent assertion of
greater independence by Poland, Czechoslovakia and Hungary.
   ``Poland faces a difficult period of transition from a state
dominated by one party to a more pluralistic and democratic system.
The process must be managed within Poland,'' Boucher said.
   ``We emphasize that this continues to be a matter for the Polish
people to decide,'' he said.
   Asked whether his statement was aimed at Moscow, Boucher would
say only: ``You know as well as I do what the history of Poland is.''
   One specialist on Soviet affairs predicted Gorbachev would ``grin
and bear'' the formation of a non-communist government in Poland,
unless he chose to jeopardize his own reforms and efforts to improve
relations with the West.
   ``The test of how far Gorbachev is willing to let things go in
Eastern Europe has come earlier than anyone expected,'' said Leon
Aron, a scholar of Soviet affairs at the conservative Heritage
Foundation in Washington.
   But as long Walesa does not humiliate Poland's communists or try
to withdraw from the Kremlin-led Warsaw Pact military alliance,
``Gorbachev may have to grin and bear it,'' Aron said.
   ``Gorbachev also realizes that any attempt at stopping these
developments in Poland would mean violence, major threat to
East-West relations and ultimately, probably, he would dig his own
grave within the Soviet Union,'' said Brzezinski.
   Polish emigres were less confident.
   ``It seems to be too good to be true,'' said Zdislaw Rurarz, who
defected from his post as Polish ambassador to Tokyo when communist
authorities declared martial law and suppressed Solidarity on Dec.
13, 1981.
   ``I cannot imagine that the U.S.S.R. has abandoned Poland and is
ready to end its domination of that country,'' Rurarz said in a
telephone interview.
   ``All depends on the reaction from Moscow,'' said Jan Nowak, an
emigre Pole who fought the Nazis and the communists for control of
Poland before fleeing his homeland after World War II.
</TEXT>
