<HEAD>Jenrette Sent to Jail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds dropped word to fourth graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA WOMACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. John Jenrette today was sentenced
to 30 days in jail and fined $2,000 for stealing a necktie and shoes
from a discount department store.
   The former South Carolina Democratic congressman was also put on
two years probation, told to do 200 hours of community service and
to continue psychiatric and alcoholism treatment.
   ``I apologize to the court,'' Jenrette said in the courtroom in
this Washington suburb. ``I can only say that I'll never be back.
Why I let this happen, I don't know. I've totally wiped out all of
my income and have lost all hopes of getting my law license back.''
   Jenrette, 53, served 13 months in prison after he was convicted
in 1980 of bribery in the Abscam affair. He is still on probation
from that conviction and it is not clear how today's sentence will
affect his federal conviction.
   Jenrette was convicted on two counts of petty larceny for
switching price tags at a discount department store on Dec. 7.
   Two security guards from the store testified during the trial
that they saw Jenrette steal the items.
   The former lawmaker claimed the incident was all a mistake. He
testified that he brought his own tie into the store to compare it
with the one he was thinking of buying, and Rosemary Long, his
self-described girlfriend, said she saw the tie in his car trunk a
week before the incident.
</TEXT>
