<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1232EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Refugees     08-18 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Refugees,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diplomatic Efforts Under Way to Resolve Refugee Crush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl and East German
leader Erich Honecker have agreed to high-level negotiations to deal
with a crush of East German refugees at West German embassies,
officials said today.
   Bonn government spokesman Herbert Schmuelling told reporters Kohl
received a letter from Honecker on Thursday night in reply to a West
German letter earlier this week pressing for joint efforts in the
refugee situation.
   A meeting between Kohl and Honecker has not been ruled out, but
government sources said the talks would likely be handled by other
senior authorities.
   Kohl said in a television interview today he was prepared to meet
with Honecker personally, if necessary to ease the ``strained'' ties
between the two countries.
   Schmuelling refused to say what Honecker's letter said but
confirmed that a meeting of East and West German officials ``at a
high level'' was in the works.
   Kohl's chief of staff, Rudolf Seiters, arrived in East Berlin
today, according to reporters there. Government sources who spoke on
condition of anonymity said Seiters would meet with East German
Deputy Foreign Minister Herbert Krolikowski to discuss the refugee
problem.
   More than 300 East Germans seeking to emigrate are being
sheltered at West Germany's embassies in Budapest, East Berlin,
Prague and Warsaw.
   The Foreign Ministry closed its embassy in Budapest on Monday
because the refugees had overwhelmed the facility. Another 300 or
more East Germans have arrived since the gates were locked and have
taken shelter with international aid groups at churches and
temporary encampments.
   East Germans frustrated with the lack of reform in their
Communist-governed country have been pouring out by the hundreds
this summer through neighboring Hungary, which began dismantling its
barbed-wire border with Austria in May.
   Most of those holed up at Bonn's embassies in Eastern Europe are
East Germans who were caught trying to escape to Austria from
Hungary.
   Hungarian border guards have noted the failed escape attempts in
the passports of many of those caught, and East Germans fearing
punishment if they return home have appealed to West Germany for
help.
</TEXT>
