<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Cambodia     08-18 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Cambodia,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Fact-Finding Mission Thanks Thailand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a United Nations
fact-finding team said Friday that Thailand's help would be needed
if an international force is dispatched to Cambodia to help bring
peace to that country.
   Lt. Gen. Martin O. Vadset also thanked Prime Minister Chatichai
Choonhavan for assistance during the team's inspection tour of the
Thai-Cambodian border.
   The 15-member team departs Saturday after spending a week inside
Cambodia and three days at the frontier. The team was dispatched by
an international conference in Paris that is trying to bring peace
to Cambodia.
   Vadset declined to say what the team would report to the
conference Monday.
   Vadset's task was to lay the groundwork for a group to monitor
the withdrawal of Vietnamese troops from Cambodia and perhaps act as
a peacekeeping force.
   A three-party Cambodian coalition is fighting the pro-Hanoi
government in Cambodia and the Vietnamese army, which invaded
Cambodia in late 1978. There are fears the fighting could escalate
after the pullout of the Vietnamese.
   Without citing details, Vadset said Thailand's assistance would
be needed if an international force went into Cambodia.
</TEXT>
