<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Irish-Photographer     08-18 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Irish-Photographer,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Photographer Granted Bail, Told to Stay Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A free-lance photographer from
West Germany who was arrested on a weapons charge was granted bail
Friday and ordered to stay out of Northern Ireland.
   A high court judge said that Nick Vogel of West Berlin would be
permitted to return to the British province only for court
appearances. Bail was set at about $1,560.
   Vogel, 22, was arrested early Tuesday in West Belfast, and was
charged with possession of a rifle magazine under suspicious
circumstances.
   Police said the magazine was from a .22-caliber semiautomatic
carbine. They said said a search of a Vogel's car also turned up
flares, knives, 17 firecrackers, two plastic containers of petrol, a
pouch with three six-inch steel darts and information on martial
arts.
   Police said Vogel had said the magazine was from a rifle he
owned, and that he kept it in the car to hit the starter motor when
it stuck.
   Vogel, who did not speak during the hearing, has said he was in
Belfast on assignment from Stern magazine.
</TEXT>
