<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1314EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     08-18 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Says Border Crossing Endangers Armistice Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. command said Friday a border
crossing at Panmunjom by two South Korean dissidents returning from
North Korea threatens the armistice in effect on the divided
peninsula since 1953.
   ``Most critically, the North Koreans' unilateral decision to
allow the transit puts in question their adherence to the armistice
itself,'' said a statement by the U.S.-led command, which represents
nations that supported South Korea in the 1950-53 war.
   A spokesman said the statement was intended to clarify the
command's position. He did not say what action, if any, would be
taken.
   Im Su-kyong, a raducal student, and the Rev. Moon Gyu-hyun
returned home Tuesday after visiting North Korea illegally and were
arrested immediately by South Korean authorities. The command said
they crossed the border at Panmunjom without proper authorization.
   South Korea accused North Korea of ``intentional provocation''
and using Panmunjom for propaganda purposes.
   In its statement, the U.N. Command also said North Korea had
brought hundreds of people to the demilitarized zone for
demonstrations in July and August against the United States and
South Korea.
   ``The North deliberately altered the rules, thus introducing
uncertainty and raising tensions in a sensitive area where the
potential for confrontation and violence is always high,'' it said.
   North Korea denied the crossing was illegal. It said the
armistice agreement applied only to foreigners or people wishing to
enter the territory under control of the other side, and ``it is
natural for Ms. Im and Moon to go back to their residence area.''
   The U.N. Command says any person, military or civilian, who
crosses the border must have specific authoritization from the
Military Armistice Commission that supervises implementation of the
agreement.
   It pointed out that many Koreans from both sides had crossed in
the past by mutual agreement, but that South Korea had not given
permission for the dissidents to do so.
</TEXT>
