<FIRST>u a PM-AndrewsAppeals     08-18 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Andrews Appeals,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pardons Board Rejects Plea For Clemency in `Hi-Fi' Murder</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in last graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Board of Pardons today rejected a
plea for clemency from convicted ``Hi-Fi'' murderer William Andrews,
scheduled to die by injection early Tuesday after nearly 15 years on
death row.
   The board's 2-1 decision left the nation's longest-standing
resident of death row with pending appeals in state and federal
courts of his 1974 conviction for torturing and murdering three
people during a stereo store robbery in Ogden.
   In all, five people were forced to drink caustic drain cleaner
and were then shot in the head; two survived the August 1974 attack.
   Board Chairman H.L. Haun and panel member Edward Kimball decided
that although Andrews did not shoot the victims, his help in forcing
them to drink the drain cleaner and his knowledge that co-defendant
Pierre Dale Selby intended to kill them made commutation of the
death sentence impossible.
   The aggravating circumstances of the crime known as the ``Hi-Fi
murders'' _ one of the most notorious in modern Utah history _ far
outweighed any mitigating factors, Haun said.
   After the drain cleaner was administered, ``When the victims did
not die quickly enough, the decision was made to shoot the victims.
Mr. Andrews waited outside while this took place, but he left his
loaded pistol for Mr. Selby to use,'' Haun said.
   ``Mr. Andrews knew of Mr. Selby's intent and shared in it,'' he
said.
   Selby was executed by injection in August 1987 after the pardons
panel unanimously rejected his plea for commutation.
   Board member Victoria Palacios voted to commute, saying that
while Andrews' culpability was undeniable, ``I would commute the
death sentence and recommend he never be paroled.''
   Andrews, 34, a Jonesboro, La., native, showed no emotion. While
being led from the hearing room at Utah State Prison, however,
Andrews said, ``I thank Miss Palacios for being fair and
considerate.''
   One of the survivors of the attack, Orren Walker, testified at
Andrews' and Selby's commutation hearings and wiped tears from his
face after today's decision. His son was among those killed.
   Pardon Board Administrator Paul Sheffield said the board received
thousands of letters and telegrams from throughout the world, 90
percent of them favoring clemency. Much of the mail has stemmed from
efforts of Amnesty International, which has made the case an example
in its effort to abolish capital punishment.
   In the appeals, Andrews contends his constitutional rights were
violated by being forced to accept as a public defender an
inexperienced attorney, and a judge's failure to instruct the jury
it could convict him of second-degree murder.
   The appeals also raised again the argument that a mistrial should
have been declared for Selby and Andrews, both black, when a juror
found a note bearing the words, ``Hang the niggers,'' during a lunch
break. There were no blacks on the jury; the sole potential black
juror was excluded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
