<FIRST>r a AM-People-Woods     08-18 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Woods,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unusual Acting Tips from Star of `True Believer'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Woods, known for his intense portrayals in
such movies as ``Salvador'' and ``The Onion Field,'' has used some
unusual techniques to prepare himself and his co-stars on the set.
   Like the time he ``whacked'' Robert Downey Jr. ``across the side
of the head and knocked him over, knocked his glasses across the
room,'' Woods told Smart magazine in its September-October issue.
   The moment came during the filming of ``True Believer.'' Downey
is ``a really great actor,'' Woods said, ``but he was missing the
magic that I knew he was capable of'' during a close-up. So Woods
whacked him. A stunned Downey finished the scene, then laughed.
   ``I hate to see anybody that brilliant not be really up to the
mark, you know what I mean? I just woke him up for a second,'' Woods
said.
   ``I would appreciate it if he did it for me. I can't really
remember if anybody has ever done anything like that to me.
   ``Bobby De Niro once sent me a pair of red high-heeled pumps from
Frederick's of Hollywood before I did a scene in `Once Upon a Time
in America,''' Woods recalled.
   ``So I just walked in, wearing my tux and my old-rubber-head
makeup and these big, fluffy, feathery, high-heeled, blazing-red
spiked heels. I think maybe I was being too serious or something,
and that kind of lightened me up a bit.''
 
</TEXT>
