<FIRST>r a AM-DrugAgent     08-18 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Agent,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Records Indicate Agent Was in Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal drug agent who allegedly transported
cocaine from Miami to Boston for a price was in danger of losing his
home because of heavy debts, according to public records.
   Edward K. O'Brien, 44, a supervisory special agent with the Drug
Enforcement Administration, was arrested Monday at Logan
International Airport.
   O'Brien, who was making $59,540 a year, may have suffered under
the stress of debt and a divorce from his wife of 18 years, sources
told The Boston Globe.
   He had been ordered to pay $475 a week in child support and a
$9,000 home equity loan on a Springfield house as a part of a
divorce settlement last year.
   Court records indicate O'Brien defaulted on a loan of $80,000
from Robert H. Clark Jr. of Southwick, and a loan of $56,421 from
Robert Oulette of Freetown. Both loans were made last year.
   Clark initiated foreclosure proceedings in Land Court in Boston,
and Judge John E. Fenton Jr. issued the foreclosure order June 26,
public records showed.
   Oulette sued in New Bedford District Court, and a lien was placed
on O'Brien's home in Sandwich in April.
   O`Brien bought the home in March 1987 for $150,000. Barnstable
County Registry of Deeds records show O'Brien borrowed $30,000 from
Paul H. Dugan, who sold him the house.
   O'Brien owes $120,000 on a mortgage from the Plymouth Five Cents
Savings Bank on the house, the newspaper reported Friday.
   He has not been indicted or arraigned.
</TEXT>
