<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1501EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DrugArrest     08-18 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Arrest,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diplomat Vetoed Arrest Plan for Indicted Colombian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. ambassador to Venezuela vetoed what he
described as an ``ill-planned ill-thought out'' plan by U.S. agents
to arrest the kingpin of the Colombian drug cartel, a State
Department spokesman said Friday.
   The aborted plan to arrest Jorge Ochoa last fall during a trip to
Caracas, Venezuela, was disclosed Thursday at a hearing of the
Senate Judiciary Committee on narcotics trafficking.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said at a briefing
Friday that ``the plan to capture Mr. Ochoa was not coordinated with
... the appropriate Washington agencies and the embassy in Caracas
and the Venezuelan government.''
   ``The Department insists, as do other law enforcement agencies,
on well-coordiated operations,'' Boucher said. ``There have been a
number of well-coordinated cases which have resulted in the
conviction of major traffickers, and these were the results of sound
planning and good coordination.
   ``Such coordination insures that we advance our anti-narcotics
objectives, without unecessary risks'' to government workers.
   The former U.S. Ambassador to Venezuela, Otto Reich, was quoted
by the Washington Post in its Friday editions as saying that
``everyone in the country was against'' the plan.
   ``It was an ill-planned, ill-thought out operation and the
government of Venezuela said no. ... It would have cost the lives
innocent Americans and Venezuelans,'' Reich said. Boucher confirmed
Reich's version.
   At the Senate hearing on Thursday, a former assistant U.S.
attorney in Miami, Richard Gregorie, said the Customs Service and
the Marshals Service developed a plan to arrest Ochoa in Caracas and
fly him to the United States for trial.
   Ochoa has been indicted by U.S. grand juries several times, but
the Colombian Supreme Court abrogated that country's extradition
treaty with the United States two years ago and he cannot be
arrested by his country's authorities on a U.S. warrant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
