<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-US     08-18 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-US,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressmen Say There's Confusion on Eastern Europe Withdrawal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. congressmen said Friday that a reorganization
of Soviet forces in Eastern Europe is making it difficult to assess
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's promised withdrawal of 50,000 soldiers.
   The members of the House Armed Services Committee, who were
ending an 11-day trip to the Soviet Union, praised their hosts for
granting them unprecedented access to military facilities that they
said will help build trust between the superpowers.
   But they said the trip had not clarified how the withdrawal from
Eastern Europe will affect the Soviet Union's fighting capability.
   ``We don't know what combat power is left in Eastern Europe after
the restructuring,'' said Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio.
   He said some units may be equipped with artillery for the first
time.
   ``We came here confused and we left confused,'' he said.
   Committee chairman Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., said that in the
process of withdrawing six divisions from its Eastern European
allies by the end of 1990, the Soviets are separating some regiments
and attaching them to divisions that will remain in Eastern Europe.
   Previously, U.S. officials assumed that entire divisions would be
withdrawn completely, he said. But Aspin added, ``We have no
evidence to indication those cuts aren't going to be made.''
   Aspin said the Soviet Union has no obligation to outline the
details of the unilateral withdrawal that Gorbachev announced at the
United Nations in December. But he urged the Soviets to make their
actions as clear as possible.
   ``The building of trust is what really counts,'' he added.
   The visit was one of a series of high-level contacts in an era of
better U.S.-Soviet relations.
   The congressmen said they hoped that members of the Supreme
Soviet's new committee on defense and state security would visit in
January or February.
   During their visit the congressmen also saw the Soviet space
shuttle assembly facility and its high-energy laser. Two of them
visited a chemical weapons decommissioning plant in Chebayevsk.
   They visited Soviet ground forces in East Germany and in the
Soviet Union, as well as U.S. military headquarters in West Berlin.
   Rep. Larry Hopkins, R-Ky., said he was impressed with the size
and advanced technology of the chemical plant. ``I was less
impressed with their candor and contingencies in case of an
accident,'' he said.
   He urged that the two countries reach an agreement that would
permit experts from the two sides to work together to dismantle
chemical weapons.
</TEXT>
