<FIRST>r a AM-SmithPlane     08-18 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smith Plane,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Board Says No Mechnical Failure in Crash That Killed Congressman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BILOXI, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators say mechanical failure
didn't cause the Cessna 177 crash that killed U.S. Rep. Larkin Smith
and his pilot.
   The comments of National Transportation Safety Board investigator
Jeff Kennedy came Thursday, as Gulf Coast residents mourned the
deaths of Smith and pilot Chuck Vierling in separate funerals.
   Smith, a 45-year-old freshman congressman from Mississippi's 5th
District, and Vierling, 58, died Sunday night when their
single-engine plane crashed into the DeSoto National Forest en route
to the Gulf Coast.
   Investigators with the NTSB have said Vierling apparently strayed
from his anticipated flight path on the 70-mile trip before clipping
a 70-foot pine tree.
   ``There was no structural failure of the airplane,'' said
Kennedy, who spent three days in Mississippi before returning
Thursday to his Miami office. ``Right now, we've ruled out any
in-flight breakup of the aircraft. He did not lose any of the
components of the airplane.
   The investigation now centers on weather and the pilot's actions,
Kennedy said.
   It could be four months before the NTSB rules on the cause of the
crash.
   The Armed Forces Institute of Pathology in Washington, D.C., is
examining tissue samples to determine if Vierling was physically
impaired during the flight.
