<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1445EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Inflation Bjt   08-18 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inflation, Bjt,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inflation Continues to Brake from Steep First-Half Acceleration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose just 0.2 percent in July,
continuing their slowdown from the steep acceleration experienced
earlier in the year, the Labor Department said Friday.
   While retail prices were up 5.9 percent for the year's first
half, the moderation actually began in June, when prices also rose
0.2 percent.
   Private analysts and the White House said the two-month softening
was a sign that the economy has moved beyond the worst inflationary
period.
   ``It's pretty clear that inflation's peaked out,'' said Lawrence
Chimerine, senior economic adviser at the WEFA Group in Bala Cynwyd,
Pa.
   ``We believe inflation is on a downward trend,'' said White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, with a vacationing George Bush in Maine.
``Economic indicators seem to be moving in the right direction and
the economy is growing steadily.''
   The Labor Department said the June and July figures both resulted
from drops in energy and clothing prices, combined with only small
gains in food costs. Rising energy and food prices had paced
consumer cost increases from January through May.
   Analysts and the Bush administration also took the summer's price
moderation as fresh evidence that the Federal Reserve Board is
succeeding in its attempts to guide the once-soaring economy to a
``soft-landing'' _ moderate growth with restrained inflation.
   ``The overall trend has been that the economy is, in fact,
achieving the soft landing everyone was hoping for.'' said Sandra
Shaber, an economist with the Futures Group, a Washington
forecasting firm. ``In other words, growth is continuing but
inflation is under control.''
   Easing inflation has been the goal of the Federal Reserve for
more than a year as it raised interest rates with the hope of
cooling the economy but not sending it into a recession.
   Whether the new moderation will now prompt the Fed to resume
nudging interest rates downward, as it began to do in June, was a
matter of dispute.
   Fitzwater said the report ``should take the pressure off interest
rates.''
   But Chimerine and William Dunkelberg, dean of the Temple
University School of Business in Philadelphia, said they do not
expect any major moves by the central bank in the immediate future.
   ``At this point, the Fed is going to sit tight and say there's no
scare on the inflation side. ... The economy is showing signs of
slowing, but there's really no need to make a dramatic move
either,'' Dunkelberg said.
   Chimerine and Shaber expect little further immediate improvement
in the inflation rate. Each expects inflation in the coming months
to be in the range of 4.5 percent to 5 percent, compared with the
4.4 percent rate for 1987 and 1988.
   Last month, energy prices fell 0.7 percent. Gasoline prices,
which had shot up 21.2 percent in the first five months of 1989,
fell 2.2 percent, thier steepest fall since October 1986.
   Other, less significant, energy prices rose. Fuel oil was up 1.5
percent, reversing June's 1.2 percent decline, while electricity and
natural gas costs rose 0.7 percent and 0.4 percent respectively.
   Clothing costs were off 0.8 percent, due in large part to
unusually high end-of-season price cuts for women's clothing, the
department said.
   At the same time, food and beverage prices edged up just 0.3
percent after rising a hefty 9.3 percent in the first five months of
1989 as the effects of last year's drought lingered.
   Prices for cereal products, beverages and sweets all rose
substantially, but were offset by a 0.7 percent decline in the costs
of meats, poultry, fish and eggs.
   Excluding the volatile food and energy areas, consumer prices
rose a moderate 0.4 percent.
   Tobacco costs rose 2 percent while new-car prices fell 0.4
percent.
   All the prices changes are seasonally adjusted, a process
designed to remove from the calculations influences that are
periodic and predictable.
   The various July changes, unadjusted, left the overall Consumer
Price Index at 124.4 percent of its 1982-84 base. That means a
hypothetical selection of goods costing $100 in the base period
would have cost $124.40 in July, 30 cents more than in June.
   In a separate report, the department said Americans' average
weekly earnings, after adjusting for inflation, rose 1.5 percent in
July after a 0.1 percent increase in June.
   The July rise stemmed from a 0.8 percent increase in average
hourly earnings and a 0.9 percent increase in average weekly hours,
which were partially offset by a 0.2 percent increase in prices as
measured by an index for urban wage earners.
   Average weekly earnings in July, before adjusting for inflation,
were $338.01, up 4.2 percent from a year earlier. Taking the 5.1
percent inflation rate for urban workers into account over the last
12 months, real weekly earnings were down 0.9 percent.
</TEXT>
