<FIRST>r w AM-Movies-CigaretteAds     08-18 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Movies-Cigarette Ads,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drugs, Sex, Violence and Cigarettes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crazed drug kingpins, seductive women,
high-tech gadgets and harrowing escapes are all part of the latest
James Bond movie, ``Licence to Kill.''
   So is a Lark cigarette. And the placement and timing of a health
warning about the dangers of smoking has lawmakers fuming.
   Philip Morris paid $350,000 to the filmmaker, United Artists, to
have the cigarette appear in the film, according to congressional
testimony.
   In response to concerns from the American Lung Association,
American Heart Association and American Cancer Society, the movie
also contains the surgeon general's warning about the effect of
smoking. The warning comes during the final credits.
   But Reps. Tom Luken, D-Ohio, and Bob Whittaker, R-Kan., have
expressed reservations about the placement of the warning.
   ``We believe that the health warning should appear at the
beginning of the film, as many viewers of the film will leave before
they see a warning in the movie's credits,'' Luken and Whittaker
said in a letter to the chairman of the Federal Trade Commission.
   Luken said Friday he is sending the letter to Janet D. Steiger,
the FTC chairman, that also asks whether the commission has the
authority to issue rules on tobacco advertising in movies.
   In the letter, the lawmakers note that the FTC has issued no
rules on cigarette advertising in films.
   ``The federal government should take every possible step to
protect our children from the siren songs of the merchants of
addiction,'' Luken said in a statement.
   Luken, chairman of the House Energy and Commerce subcommittee on
transportation and hazardous materials, and Whittaker, the panel's
ranking Republican, are co-sponsors of a bill that prohibits all
tobacco ads and promotion that can be seen or heard by people under
the age of 18.
   The bill is titled, ``Protect Our Children From Cigarettes Act.''
</TEXT>
