<FIRST>r i AM-Pope     08-18 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope to Appeal to Youth in Spain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II will urge the young to
spread Roman Catholicism when he addresses an unusual rally Saturday
in Spain that promises to resemble a huge Scout jamboree.
   The church has brought in 160 bishops, including Cardinal John
O'Connor of New York, and expects at least 300,000 youngsters at the
international rally, the highlight of John Paul's three-day visit to
Spain.
   Young people from 55 countries are traveling to Santiago de
Compostela for the church-sponsored fourth World Youth Day,
including groups from communist Cuba, Bulgaria and the Soviet
republic of Lithuania.
   Most are housed in tents, turning the city of 85,000 and its
environs into a giant campground.
   A flotilla of about 600 motorboats and fishing vessels sailed
into nearby La Coruna on Friday, recalling pilgrims who traveled by
sea to Santiago de Compostela in northwestern Spain.
   The purpose of all the activity is to capture the imagination of
young people and convince them to be standard-bearers in the
church's crusade for a more Christian, less secular world, Vatican
officials said.
   ``What this represents is a growing attention to youth and
working with youth as a pastoral priority of the Roman Catholic
Church,'' said Monsignor Peter Coughlan, undersecretary of the
Vatican's Pontifical Council for the Laity, which organized the
event.
   The pope's itinerary also includes visits Sunday evening and
Monday to the northern cities of Oviedo and Covadonga, which he did
not reach in his previous trips to Spain in 1982 and 1984.
   During those stops, the 69-year-old pontiff will say Masses
dedicated to the subjects of labor and devotion to Mary.
   While his message at Santiago is for world youth, the Oviedo and
Covadonga trips are aimed specifically to Catholics in Spain, whose
adherence has declined in the 11 years since church and state were
officially separated in the overwhelmingly Catholic country.
   In addition to the rally Saturday night on a mountain just
outside Santiago, Pope John Paul II will celebrate Youth Day with a
Sunday Mass.
   Coughlan said the pope's attention to youth was both personal and
strategic.
   John Paul has had a long-standing interest in young people
through his work as a university professor, bishop and cardinal. In
addition, Coughlan said, the pontiff realizes the young are
increasingly becoming the world's majority, especially in
underdeveloped countries.
   ``The future of the church in places like Zaire is caught up with
youth,'' he said in an interview.
   Santiago de Compostela was chosen for the rally to emphasize the
historical roots of Catholicism as the church approaches its third
milennium, Vatican officials say.
   The city became one of the three main pilgrimage sites of
Christianity, along with Jerusalem and Rome, after the bones of the
apostle St. James were said to have been discovered there in the 9th
century.
   Many youngsters participating in the rally walked part of the
traditional 500-mile Way of St. James that stretches from the
Pyrenees to Santiago.
   In a message for World Youth Day published in advance, John Paul
said Santiago's history reminds Catholics that they must spread
their faith.
   ``The world of today is a great land of mission, even in the
countries with an ancient Christian tradition,'' he said.
``Everywhere today, neopaganism and the process of secularization
constitute a great challenge to the evangelical message.''
   Among ``secular'' practices the church opposes are abortion,
artificial birth control and divorce.
   John Paul celebrated the first World Youth Day in Rome in 1986,
and the second in Buenos Aires, Argentina. The Vatican plans to hold
the event outside Rome every other year.
   This year's special day followed a week of church-sponsored
cultural and religious conferences in Santiago de Compostela that
brought Catholic youth leaders together.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
