<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1541EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FlynnDivest     08-18 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flynn Divest,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boston Mayor Wants City Funds Out of Companies that Discriminate
in N. Ireland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Raymond L. Flynn said Friday he is working to
get city pension money and trust funds away from companies that do
business in Northern Ireland and fail to reduce job discrimination
against Catholics.
   ``We have to make sure the British government understands the
importance of fair employment practices and opening their economy to
all,'' said Flynn, who said he witnessed widespread job
discrimination against Roman Catholics when he visited Northern
Ireland last year.
   The unemployment rate is twice as high for Catholics as it is for
Protestants in British-ruled Northern Ireland. Catholics are a
minority there but a majority in the Irish Republic.
   Flynn filed a home rule petition Thursday calling for the
divestiture and signed an executive order requiring city contractors
owned by companies doing business in Northern Ireland to subscribe
to the MacBride Principles.
   The principles, named after the late Irish diplomat Sean
MacBride, winner of the 1974 Nobel Peace Prize, are aimed at
reducing job discrimination against Catholics. The guidelines
provide for equal access to jobs and promotion, the banning of
religious emblems from the workplace, public advertising of jobs and
for companies to monitor their affirmative action efforts.
   Francis Costello, Flynn's adviser on Irish affairs, said the
principles were modeled after the Sullivan Principles, which address
investment in South Africa.
   The home rule petition must be approved by the City Council and
the Legislature. The executive order, which affects contracts worth
several million dollars, does not need City Council approval.
   Costello said he expected the plan would win legislative approval
since Massachusetts, in 1984, became the first state in the nation
to pass a law embracing the McBride Principles. Ten other states and
a half-dozen cities have taken similar action.
   Costello said previous legislation has been largely symbolic and
that Flynn's proposals are enforceable. He said Flynn would campaign
for other mayors to take similar steps.
   Flynn said Chicago Mayor Richard M. Daley was considering such a
proposal.
   The contractor order would not affect hiring practices of
contractors locally but would take their contracts away if their
owners don't follow the employment standards in Northern Ireland.
   Costello said the MacBride standards for Northern Ireland are no
more severe than the affirmative action requirements on minority
hiring in the United States.
   ``This is not an effort against American companies at all,''
Flynn said. ``Certainly we do not want to hurt job opportunities or
the economy of Northern Ireland.''
   But Alan White, deputy consul general for Great Britain in
Boston, said that is exactly what would happen.
   Pressure to abide by the principles has had ``a discouraging
effect on new American companies trying to establish themselves in
Northern Ireland,'' he said.
   ``If you follow the MacBride Principles, you have to sack
Protestants and hire Catholics,'' said White, which would only add
to the tense environment in Northern Ireland.
   White said Flynn should give a law passed earlier this year by
British Parliament a chance to work. The law outlaws job
discrimination in Northern Ireland, but does not require affirmative
action.
   Boston has about $11 million in pension funds invested in seven
of the 24 American companies doing business in Northern Ireland and
$2 million in trust funds invested in nine of the companies.
   More than half of the $11 million in pension money and nearly
one-fourth of the trust funds are invested in Digital Equipment
Corp. Other companies are NYNEX, Ford Motor Co., General Motors,
Exxon, Sunoco and Dunn &amp; Bradstreet.
   About 30 percent of Boston's 600,000 people are of Irish
extraction, said Bill O'Donnell, community relations manager for the
Boston Redevelopment Authority.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
