<FIRST>r a AM-DrugMothers     08-18 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Mothers,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Arrested On Charges of Using Drugs During Pregnancy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose newborn tested positive for
cocaine was being held on $20,000 bond Friday on charges she used
drugs during pregnancy.
   Marcelle D. Bruce, 25, was arrested Friday on felony charges of
criminal neglect. A warrant charges her with being ``a cocaine user,
causing her infant baby's health and life to be in danger.''
   She is the fourth woman in Greenville in less than a week to be
arrested on such charges.
   The infant was born last weekend at Greenville Memorial Hospital
and remains in the hospital, said police Detective D.L. Butler.
   Police will take the baby into protective custody next week, Ms.
Butler said. She said the infant could be placed in foster care by
the state.
   Of the babies born to the other three women arrested, one is in
the hospital and two are in foster care, officials said.
   A meeting is planned next week among police, state officials, the
solicitor's office and the hospital to work out a formal system for
handling these drug cases, Ms. Butler said.
   ``This is just the beginning,'' she said. ``You're going to see a
whole lot more of these in the future.''
   The hospital has supported the police, but some hospital
employees questioned the prosecution of mothers who come to the
hospital to deliver their children.
   A woman who gives birth to a drug-addicted baby should be treated
as a medical rather than criminal matter, said Rosemary Boling, head
nurse at Memorial's nursery.
   ``If the mother knew she would be criminally prosecuted, she
might avoid prenatal care. That would put an already at-risk (baby)
at even more risk,'' said Dr. Paul Catalana, an instructor in
Memorial's pediatric residency program.
   But county Assistant Solicitor Catherine Christophillis said the
arrests protest the babies and offer a chance to get the women into
treatment programs.
   ``It's not like I'm out here saying all these mothers should go
to jail,'' Ms. Christophillis said. ``My goal is to rehabilitate
them if they want to, to provide an opportunity for them and then
take a look and see if they want to do it.''
</TEXT>
