<FIRST>u a PM-TruckFire-Ammunition 3rdLd-Writethru a0614 08-18 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Truck Fire-Ammunition, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0614,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Killed, One Critically Injured As Ammunition Truck Catches Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with man in serious condition;
add quote from witness, and to CORRECT `population' to populated in 8th
graf pvs. Picks up 9th graf pvs, `I-17 was...'. SUBS penultimate graf to
add detail on shipment, clarifying that it had come from Texas but had
been stored in Arizona in the interim.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCK SPRINGS, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck hauling 40,000 rounds of
military aircraft ammunition caught fire on an interstate highway
early today, killing a woman and seriously injuring her companion,
authorities said.
   Hours after the fire broke out, the northbound lanes of the
interstate were still closed as shells continued to explode. But the
accident happened in a remote area and no one had to be evacuated,
officials said.
   ``It was like fireworks,'' Rock Springs Fire Chief Pete Davis. He
said ammunition and shell casings were scattered 100 yards around
the truck and explosions kept everyone at a distance for hours.
   Sgt. Allan Schmidt, spokesman for the Arizona Department of
Public Safety, said the couple aboard the truck were believed to be
husband and wife. ``Somehow, the gentleman was either thrown free or
got out,'' he said. The woman was found dead.
   The man was in serious but stable condition in John C. Lincoln
Hospital in Phoenix at midday, hospital spokesperson Lisa Boulay
said. The couple's names were not immediately released.
   The truck-trailer rig, under contract to the military, was on
Interstate 17 en route to the Navajo Army Depot near Flagstaff when
a fire apparenty engulfed it about 1 a.m., Schmidt said.
   It was hauling 20 millimeter aircraft cannon ammunition.
   Smoke was still coming from the truck and ammunition was still
exploding sporadically five hours later, said Schmidt.
   The accident occurred in a rural, sparsely populated area about
30 miles north of Phoenix. Schmidt said there were no evacuations.
   I-17 was completely closed for three hours, but the southbound
lanes were later reopened and were accommodating traffic in both
directions. They are separated from the northbound lanes by several
hundred feet.
   ``No one is going near this vehicle,'' said Schmidt. ``There are
still occasionally explosions, as rounds go off. We do not really
know how far ammunition has been thrown from the vehicle, but it has
been thrown.''
   Two teams of ordnance experts from Luke Air Force Base, near
Phoenix, and the Army's Fort Huchuca in Sierra Vista, in southern
Arizona, were dispatched to the scene.
   Lt. Col. Ed Cooke of Kelly Air Force Base in San Antonio
confirmed the truck carried 40,000 rounds of Class D ammunition,
weighing 37,000 pounds. Cooke said said the ammunition had been
stored in Arizona but came originally from a Kelly-run storage
facility located at Lackland Air Force Base, also in San Antonio.
   Schmidt said authorities either got erroneous information from
the military or misunderstood it when they initially reported the
truck carried 800,000 rounds of ammunition.
</TEXT>
