<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1557EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CrashTest     08-18 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash Test,0299</SECOND>
<UNK>Airplane Smashes Into Concrete Barrier in Test</UNK>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An F-4 Phantom jet smashed into a
concrete barrier at 480 mph in a test to learn how to protect a
nuclear reactor from a plane crash.
   The surplus plane, strapped to rails and propelled by rockets,
slammed into a million-pound barrier at Sandia National Laboratories
on April 18, 1988. Details of the test were reported Thursday during
the 10th International Conference on Structural Mechanics in Reactor
Technology at Anaheim, Calif.
   ``The crash data are going to give us an unprecedented ability to
predict the impact force when an aircraft crashes into a building,''
said Walter A. von Riesemann, supervisor of Sandia's containment
technology division.
   ``We'd previously done some fairly accurate computer analysis,
but the computer models were untried on the real thing. Not
anymore.''
   Researchers need to estimate the structural response of a
building in such an accident. To do that they must know how the
impact force changes throughout the brief time the crash is in
progress, Sandia officials said.
   The F-4 jet weighed 42,000 pounds at impact, which included more
than 1,200 gallons of water to simulate the weight of fuel and
provide proper mass distribution, Sandia officials said.
   Sixteen high-speed framing cameras recorded the crash, shooting
from 500 to 2,000 frames per second.
   The concrete block, supported by air bags that enabled it to be
moved with just 2,000 pounds of force, suffered minor damage, with
the engines penetrating no more than 2.4 inches.
   The target was able to move, acting much like a bathroom scale,
with the force of impact determined by measuring how much the block
moved.
   The test was funded by the Muto Institute of Structural Mechanics
Inc. of Tokyo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
