<FIRST>u w AM-US-Somalia     08-18 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Somalia,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Cutting Military Training, Presence To Protest Abuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is reducing its military
training and presence in Somalia to protest ``gruesome'' human
rights abuses by security forces in the strategically placed east
African nation, U.S. officials said Friday.
   The decision comes as the administration seeks to renegotiate an
agreement for use of the Red Sea port of Berbera by U.S. Navy
vessels moving to and from the Indian Ocean. The pact expires next
year.
   Although U.S. military assistance to Somalia in the past two
years has dwindled sharply, the decision to cut it further indicates
U.S. frustration with the government's inability to reign in the
security forces and control a growing mutiny throughout the country,
the officials said.
   ``As a token of our frustration with the security forces, we
decided to reduce our military activities,'' said one official.
``The government of Somalia knows it's no longer business as usual.''
   Officials are still examining what programs to cut, ``but we'll
be looking at training areas,'' and that will mean pulling out some
U.S. military advisers, the official said.
   Somalia, which had shifted its alliance from the Soviet Union to
the West in 1977, flirted with Libya last year and received some
military supplies. But with the U.S. decision to suspend weapons
deliveries, Somalia has been buying arms on the open market to use
against some rebels.
   ``There's general, communal strife throughout Somalia,'' said one
official. ``Gvernment control outside Mogadishu is slipping,'' he
added, speaking only on condition of anonymity.
   In the northern part of the impoverished country of 6 million,
the Somali National Front has gained ground against government
troops, while in the south, Ogadeni tribesmen are conducting a
hit-and-run guerrilla campaign.
   Reliable information is hard to come by because journalists have
been prevented from visiting the country and dissidents are afraid
to speak out.
   But the State Department says there are credible reports that
last month, security forces summarily executed dozens of Somalis on
the beach near Mogadishu following clashes between Moslems and
government troops that left 400 people dead.
   ``The events are tragic, gruesome,'' said the official. ``I hope
the government can find their way out of it, but they seem to have
lost their way.''
   The United States had been encouraged earlier this year when
President Siad Barre, under strong congressional pressure from
Washington, freed 200 to 300 political prisoners. Barre, an
autocratic ruler who has run the one-party state since 1969, also
agreed to speak to some opposition figures.
   To encourage further progress, the administration asked Congress
for $21 million to help Somalia pay its arrears to the International
Monetary Fund, said the official.
   But with the rioting in mid-July and the mass executions,
Congress turned down the request, he said.
   ``We decided not to fight it. We can't make a credible argument
to Congress. We can't show anything positive,'' he said.
   The administration has sought to stave off congressional
criticism of Somalia's human rights violations in recent years
through backstage pressure on Barre to improve his record.
   Congress last year froze nearly $40 million in food and
development aid for Somalia, and the administration decided to
suspend all lethal weapons supplies after U.S. rifles and ammunition
were used against rebels and civilians in the north.
   Most of the U.S. aid since then has been of non-lethal military
equipment, as well as training of Somali personnel.
   The Somali National Front, which is the largest anti-government
force, has been fighting Barre's forces for seven years. At least
one senior government commander reportedly deserted in recent weeks.
   But most of the country's six major tribes appear to be warring
against the government or each other, said the U.S. official.
``Events are running beyond anyone's control. It strains one's
credulity to think someone is masterminding it. But responsibility
for controling the situation lies with the government forces,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
