<FIRST>r i AM-Cugat     08-18 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cugat,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Band Leader Xavier Cugat Released From Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Band leader Xavier Cugat was released
from a hospital Friday, a month after he was admitted for a heart
ailment, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   Cugat, 89, has recovered fully from a problem in his left
ventricle that kept him in the Quiron Clinic's intensive care unit
for two weeks following his admission July 20, said the spokeswoman,
Isabel Mas.
   She said he was ``in perfect shape.''
   Cugat, who is generally credited with introducing tropical
rhythms into American dance music, has suffered four heart attacks
and a stroke since 1980.
   The band leader became a U.S. star in the 1930s, playing Latin
dance music at the Coconut Grove club in Los Angeles' Ambassador
Hotel and later at the Waldorf-Astoria in New York. He also appeared
in several Hollywood movies.
   Cugat was born Jan. 1, 1900, in the northeastern Catalonian town
of Gerona, but moved with his family to Cuba as a child.
   In 1970, he turned over his band to Tito Puente, and a decade
later returned to Barcelona, where he has lived in the Hotel Ritz
for several years.
</TEXT>
