<HEAD>Three Paintings Missing from Spanish National Palace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three paintings valued at $2.3 million,
including two works by the Spanish master Diego de Velazquez, are
missing from their places in the Royal Palace, an official said
Friday.
   The paintings were reported missing from a restricted area in the
national museum by members of a restoration crew, said the palace
official, who asked not to be identified. He said they were last
seen a week ago.
   ``Robbery is certainly one of many possibilites, but we're by no
means certain that the paintings were stolen,'' the palace spokesman
said.
   The two Velazquez paintings are valued at $820,000 each, the
official said. One painting portrays a cleric holding up a piece of
paper bearing the artist's signature. The second depicts a woman's
head.
   The third painting, by Carreno de Miranda and valued at $615,000,
portrays the bust a woman from the era of Charles II.
   An article printed six months ago in the Spanish news daily
Diario 16 raised concerns over inadequate security at the palace, a
popular tourist attraction, after several youths showed reporters
how they could get in undetected.
