<FIRST>u w AM-US-Lebanon     08-18 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Lebanon,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Says Syria's Allies Still Pushing Drive In Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Friday again criticized
Syria's allies in Lebanon for shelling Christian enclaves in the
war-torn country and urged them to observe a cease-fire on all
fronts.
   Spokesman Richard Boucher said recent reports indicated Syrian
troops were not actively engaged in the fighting. But he stressed
the reports dealt with a 12-hour period and it was too early to say
whether Syria had heeded a U.S. call to lay down its arms.
   ``The most urgent thing, the most important thing, is for people
to accept a cease-fire,'' Boucher said.
   Deferring again to the Arab League to try to stop the fighting,
Boucher said, ``We would welcome a resumption of their efforts.''
   He said that Amal and Druze militias were continuing their drive
against Christian enclaves and that the Christians were retaliating.
   ``We feel there is no justification for continued military action
in the face of urgent appeals and we urge all sides to implement and
immediately observe a cease-fire on all fronts,'' Boucher said.
   On Monday, the State Department sharply condemned Syria and its
allies for the eruption of large-scale ground fighting in Lebanon
and said the turmoil in the Middle Eastern country made U.S. efforts
to gain the release of American hostages more difficult.
   ``Syria-supported forces have joined the latest round of fighting
in Lebanon,'' Boucher said Friday. ``This represents an
irresponsible escalation of the violence. Syria and its allies
should refrain from any further escalation and accept immediately
international and Arab League calls for a cease-fire and a lifting
of the blockade'' of Christian ports.
   At the same time, Boucher urged the Christians to observe a
cease-fire and to join in the ``political reconstruction'' of
Lebanon. This means, in effect, agreeing to new power-sharing
arrangements with Muslims that would reduce Maronite influence in
the country.
</TEXT>
