<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica     08-18 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Crack Down on Defiance Campaign, Fire on Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police whipped and opened fire
Friday on hundreds of black workers protesting a lockout at their
workplace, and the company director said at least 17 employees were
injured.
   Also Friday, police arrested a leader of the anti-apartheid
movement's national defiance campaign and banned a weekend rally
that was planned as part of the 3-week-old campaign.
   A court sentenced Trevor Tutu, son of Archbishop Desmond Tutu, to
18 months in prison for making a false bomb threat at Johannesburg's
international airport.
   The clash outside a pie company began after about 400 workers
gathered at its gate to protest being locked out. Louis Silber,
managing director of Mama's Pies, said the lockout was imposed
because of a 4-week-old wage dispute.
   The Food and Allied Workers Union said police used whips and live
ammunition to disperse the workers and made several arrests.
   Capt. Reg Crewe, a spokesman at police headquarters in Pretoria,
said police acted only after workers began pulling on the locked
gates and ingored an order to disperse. He said officers initially
used whips but fired shotguns when some fleeing workers threw stones.
   He said four people were slightly injured by shotgun fire. He
said no one was arrested.
   It was the second violent labor clash in two days. On Thursday,
police said at least 10 people were injured outside the
British-owned Eveready plant in Port Elizabeth in clashes between
striking workers and people recruited to fill their jobs.
   Mohammed Valli Moosa, an official of the banned United Democratic
Front and an organizer of a 3-week-old defiance campaign, was
arrested at his Johannesburg office.
   A police officer said he was held under emergency regulations
allowing detention of anyone deemed a threat to public safety.
   Valli Moosa has been one of the highest-ranking activists not
under any restrictions. He was one of three activists who escaped
detention last year and took sanctuary at the U.S. Consulate in
Johannesburg.
   One of the other escapees, Murphy Morobe, said Valli Moosa's
arrest violated the government's promise that the three could leave
the consulate without fear of being detained again or placed under
restrictions.
   The United Democratic Front, a nationwide coalition, and 16 other
anti-apartheid groups last year were ordered to halt all activities.
   They intended to defy the order and declared themselves legal at
a rally Sunday, the group's sixth anniversary.
   Police officials banned the rally but did not say if all defiance
rallies planned Sunday would be banned.
   The rallies were organized as part of a nationwide defiance
campaign that began Aug. 3, when blacks sought treatment at
segregated white hospitals. Since then, dozens of activists have
defied restrictions imposed on them.
   Archbishop Tutu described the ban as ``inflammatory'' and called
for an alternative ``service of witness'' at his church in Cape Town.
   The younger Tutu was convicted of violating the Aviation Act by
falsely telling police there was a bomb in his luggage. He pleaded
innocent and said he would appeal.
   He also was convicted on five other charges stemming from two
other incidents.
   In addition to the 18-month sentence, Tuto was fined $440.
   Shortly after the Dec. 31 bomb incident at Jan Smuts Airport,
Tutu convened a news conference and told reporters he deliberately
courted arrest as part of a publicity stunt on behalf of his
advertising agency.
   The other charges include three counts of slandering police and
traffic officers, one count of interfering with police last year
when they tried to arrest a friend of his on suspicion of drunken
driving, and one count of maliciously damaging a police officer's
hat.
</TEXT>
