<HEAD>Two Guards Shot In New York City Armored Car Heist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men armed with assault rifles shot an armored
car guard to death and wounded another in a botched holdup at a
shopping center Friday, authorities said.
   The guards had just finished making a delivery to the Long Island
Savings Bank in an exclusive section of the borough of Queens when
they were confronted at 11:20 a.m., said Detective Joseph McConville.
   The guards exchanged gunfire with the two men, and at least a
dozen shots were fired, McConville said. One guard was shot in the
head and the other was hit in the chest, arm and groin, McConville
said.
   The 26-year-old guard who was shot in the head was pronounced
dead at 12:15 p.m. at Booth Memorial Hospital, police said. The
other guard was in critical condition at the hospital.
   The gunmen fled in a car. No money was taken.
   The guards' names were not released pending notification of their
families.
   A third security guard who was inside the armored van when the
shooting broke out was not wounded.
   The bullet-marked car was recovered a short time later in a
wooded area near a city highway. Investigators found three guns near
the vehicle, but believed the gunmen were still aarmed.
   Police helicopters and bloodhounds searched a park and an
apartment complex near the highway.
