<FIRST>u i AM-India-Blast     08-18 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Blast,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes in Bus; Kills 15, Wounds 30</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARBAKSH SINGH NANDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb planted in the luggage rack of a
bus exploded Friday as the vehicle was passing a market in a
northern town, killing at least 15 people and wounding 30, police
said.
   The victims of the blast at Chintpurni in Himachal Pradesh state
included two women and two children, police said.
   There were no claims of responsibility for the explosion but Sikh
militants agitating for an independent nation in Punjab were
suspected, police officials said.
   The bus was coming from the Sikh holy city of Amritsar in
neighboring Punjab state and was passing Chintpurni's main market
when the explosion occurred.
   Most of the victims were on the bus, but at least four people on
the street sustained injuries, said police officials in the town.
   They spoke on condition of anonymity in telephone calls from
Chandigarh, the capital of Punjab, about 70 miles north of
Chintpurni.
   Ravi Kanth Bahl, a doctor in a government-owned hospital in the
neighboring town of Una, said at least 12 people died before they
could be treated.
   ``I was told many more bodies would be coming,'' he said in a
telephone conversation from his hospital, the largest in the area.
Bahl said the blast appeared to have been ``extremely powerful''
because the victims' bodies were unidentifiable.
   A similar blast on a bus bound for Nsw Delhi from Chandigarh on
Aug. 9 left at least 18 people dead. Police said the explosion was
caused by a time bomb planted by the militants.
   Sikhs form only 2 percent of India's 880 million people but are
in a majority in Punjab. Radicals from the community have been
fighting for an independent nation since 1982, claiming they are
discriminated by the Hindus, who make up 80 percent of the country's
population.
   At least 1,200 people have been killed in Punjab this year in
violence blamed on the militants. In the latest violence, at least
18 people were killed on Thursday and Friday, Press Trust of India
said.
   The toll included 12 militants shot and killed by police and the
others were victims of the radicals, the news agency said.
</TEXT>
