<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1728EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Falklands     08-18 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Falklands,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain and Argentina Agree To Talks on Restoring Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain and Argentina announced Friday they
would hold talks in October in Spain to consider restoring ties
severed by their war in 1982 over the Falklands Islands.
   Both sides called the agreement to meet in Madrid Oct. 17-18 a
breathrough and said they were optimistic that relations would be
normalized.
   A joint statement, issued after three days of talks in New York,
said the Madrid discussions would be held without prejudice to
sovereignty over the islands claimed by both Argentina and Britain.
   The negotiators will consider diplomatic and consular relations,
confidence-building measures to avoid military incidents, trade and
financial relations, air and sea communications links, fisheries,
contacts between the Falklands and the South American mainland and
cultural, scientific and sports relations, according to the report.
Sovereignty is not on the agenda.
   The Falklands, 325 miles off of Argentina's southern coast, are a
British colony. Britain has not eased its position on sovereignty
and British Ambassador Sir Crispen Tickell said the agreement to
hold normalization talks was due to the initiative of Argentina's
new president, Carlos Saul Menem.
   Tickell held the negotitaions with Argentine special
representative Ambassador Lucio Ggarcia del Solar.
   Both men read the communique and Tickell said later:
   ``I would call this (agreement) a breakthrough. This development
is very important for Anglo-Argentine relations and now enables us
to go forward on a new basis. ... I am optimistic because we have
agreed to an agenda and to hold talks without prejudice to the
sovereignty position on either side.''
   Garcia del Solar told reporters, ``These contacts (with Britain)
began since President Menem openly said he wanted a solution on the
basis shown in this communique today.''
   Argentina invaded and occupied the Falklands in April 1982 but
Britain sent a task force and recaptured the islands in a 74-day war
that claimed nearly 1,000 lives.
   The Falklands, known in Argentina as the Malvinas, has a
population of about 2,000 and most of the islanders are of British
descent.
   Britain has said it will not relinquish sovereignty over the
islands and Menem dropped the previous government's insistence that
Argentina's sovereignty claim would have to be the first issue
considered in normalization talks.
   The communique said it was agreed that the Madrid talks ``would
take place under the terms of a formula to protect the position of
each side with regard to sovereignty or territorial and maritime
jurisdiction over the Falkland Islands, South Georgia and the South
Sandwich Islands and the surrounding maritime areas.''
</TEXT>
