<FIRST>r a AM-VFWConvention     08-18 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-VFW Convention,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flag Burning, Quayle Highlight VFW Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 25,000 members of the Veterans of Foreign
Wars gather this weekend for their 90th annual convention and an
agenda that includes resolutions against desecrating the American
flag and a speech by Vice President Dan Quayle.
   The flag ``will be the convention's most emotional issue,'' VFW
spokesman Wade LaDue predicted Friday.
   The five-day convention, which begins Monday, is expected to be
the 2 million-member organization's largest in recent memory, LaDue
said.
   Defense Secretary Richard Cheney, Veterans Affairs Secretary
Edward Derwinski and Gen. Colin L. Powell, who was nominated last
week to be chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, also are scheduled
to speak to the convention.
   The VFW also plans to honor Adm. William Crowe Jr., the retiring
chairman of the Joint Chiefs, four Navy aviators who shot down
Libyan MiG fighter jets over the Mediterranian Sea on Jan. 4, and
singer Wayne Newton.
   A memorial service for fallen comrades is scheduled for the eve
of the convention Sunday.
   Quayle is scheduled to address the gathering's opening session
Monday morning.
   That afternoon, the veterans will begin considering about 500
resolutions covering a wide range of issues. Twenty-five resolutions
are expected on the flag desecration issue alone, LaDue said.
   The U.S. Supreme Court on June 21 ruled that burning the flag as
a political protest is protected by the First Amendment guarantee of
freedom of speech.
   The decision prompted widespread protests on both sides of the
issue, and President Bush proposed a constitutional amendment
banning desecrating the flag, which the VFW supports.
   Larry Rivers, the group's commander-in-chief and a Marine who
served in Vietnam, said Friday that the nation's veterans are not
ready to concede that flag burning is a free-speech issue.
   At a banquet Monday night, the VFW will honor Newton for
entertaining troops around the world and Crowe for his contributions
``to the cause of national security, unity and world peace.''
   Derwinski is scheduled to speak Tuesday. The veterans' affairs
secretary is expected to discuss such topics as health care for
veterans.
   It will be Derwinski's second appearance before veterans here in
three weeks. On July 31, he appeared in Bush's place at the Disabled
American Veterans convention.
   On Tuesday night, the VFW will hold its annual parade in front of
Las Vegas' convention center.
   The four Navy aviators involved in the Libyan incident will be
honored on Wednesday. Navy representatives will accept the honor on
behalf of the aviators, who have not been identified for security
reasons, LaDue said.
   The convention ends Friday with Walter Hogan, a Korean War
veteran from Greenfield, Wis., assuming the post of
commander-in-chief.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
