<DOCNO> AP890818-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1736EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Hostages     08-18 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Offers to Coordinate Future Activities with Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel has agreed to coordinate its military
activities with the United States if Washington stops criticizing
the Israeli abduction of a Shiite Moslem cleric, Israeli sources
said Friday.
   The kidnapping of Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid at his south Lebanon
home by Israeli commandos July 28 caused retaliatory threats against
American hostages in Lebanon.
   Some members of Congress denounced the abduction. President Bush
called for the release of all people held against their will and did
not exclude Obeid, who is affiliated with Hezbollah, the pro-Iranian
extremist group believed to sponsor hostage-holders.
   The captors of Lt. Col. Willian R. Higgins, a U.S. Marine
kidnapped while on U.N. duty in south Lebanon, said they hanged him
in retaliation three days after Obeid was seized, but there were
reports he had been killed months ago.
   Joseph Cicippio, one of the seven other American hostages, was
threatened with death, then given a reprieve.
   An Israeli source close to the government said Friday ``an
understanding'' was reached between Foreign Minister Moshe Arens and
Secretary of State James A. Baker III soon after the Obeid abduction
that they would adopt a joint policy for the hostage crisis.
   He added, on condition of anonymity: ``There is an expressed
Israeli commitment, when the crisis is over, to discuss with
Americans coordination of future Israeli activities that may have
bearing on American interests and citizens.''
   That, he said, was ``the price Israeli has paid for not being
criticized now by the United States.''
   Dan Naveh, an adviser to Arens, confirmed that Arens and Baker
discussed future coordination in the days after the kidnapping.
   ``They agreed not to get into this issue during the days of the
crisis, but in the future,'' Naveh said, and stressed that ``the
conclusion was to discuss the issue, not necessarily reach an
agreement.''
   He did not describe the agreement for consultation as an
exchange, but acknowledged that American criticism had abated.
   Avi Pazner, an adviser to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, said:
``In the first days after we captured Obeid, there was some
unhappiness in Washington about it. ... Since then we have
straightened out these matters through constant dialogue, and there
is no problem today.''
   The source close to the government said the Baker-Arens agreement
caused concern in military and intelligence circles.
   ``Israel always prided itself on its autonomy in terms of
strategy,'' the source said. ``There's a feeling that, in order to
get off the hook for a few days, Arens has mortgaged Israel's
freedom of maneuver.''
   A U.S. congresswoman who met with Shamir on Friday said she was
encouraged by hopes of resolving the hostage situation, but she also
said she was anxious about American hostage Terry A. Anderson, the
captive held longest.
   Rep. Louise Slaughter, a Democrat who represents the New York
state district where Anderson grew up, told reporters Shamir would
not give details on Israeli efforts to free the captives.
   She said she felt ``frustration, as I am sure Terry does, that
his government hasn't done much.''
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated
Press, was kidnapped March 16, 1985. Eight Westerners in addition to
the Americans are held in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
