<FIRST>r w AM-UndergroundExplosions     08-18 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Underground Explosions,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Officials Ask Feds To Halt Plans For Series of Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor and city manager of Del Rio, Texas,
asked the Defense Nuclear Agency on Friday to abandon consideration
of a local ranch for a series of underground explosions designed to
simulate the impact of Soviet nuclear warheads on subterranean
command centers.
   Petitions signed by nearly 12,000 Del Rio area residents opposed
to the tests on the Buck King ranch were presented to Vice Adm. John
T. Parker Jr., director of the Defense Nuclear Agency.
   The Del Rio officials are concerned about the impact of the
explosions on the border city's sole source of drinking water, San
Felipe Springs, which was contaminated by an unknown substance in an
underground cave-in earlier this week, forcing residents to boil or
drink bottled water for two days.
   ``We appreciate the opportunity to meet with the Del Rio mayor
and city manager. We better understand the concerns of the
citizens,'' Parker said after the session with Mayor Alfredo
Gutierrez Jr., a physician, and City Manager Jeffrey Pomeranz.
   ``We're going to do everything that is possible to stop it and we
so indicated to DNA,'' Gutierrez said.
   The Mexican government has also inquired about possible
explosions, in an Aug. 4 letter that the State Department answered
Thursday, an official at State said Friday.
   The official said the letter advises Mexico that an environmental
assessment of the site must still be completed before any tests
would be done.
   Agency spokeswoman Cheri Abdelnour said the agency continues to
assess the Del Rio site _ currently the only location nationally
under consideration for the series of underground explosions _ and
will not make a final decision until technical and environmental
assessments are completed.
   The environmental assessment may take until January 1990 to
finish, she said.
   ``Clearly, we will not be doing anything until that assessment is
made _ the technical assessment as well as the environmental
assessment,'' she said.
   The DNA, an agency of the Defense Department, spent two years
picking a site for the tests.
   The explosions would start with a 1,000-pound charge in 1990,
increasing to 470 tons, an equivalent of 300 tons of TNT, in
November 1992.
   Ms. Abdelnour said the tests would be performed with the same
conventional explosives used by the mining industry, and do not
involve nuclear or radioactive devices.
   ``They are designed to have no significant adverse impact on the
environment, including the water system,'' Ms. Abdelnour said.
   But Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texxas, said local officials and residents
have expressed great concern about the impact on the explosions on
the springs, which provides water to the city of 40,000 and to
nearby Laughlin Air Force Base.
   ``Given the 12,000 people who have signed a petition, and the
great local concern about the tests, I think it would save the DNA's
money to simply go ahead and make the decision and look for another
test area,'' Gramm said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
