<FIRST>u i AM-Cuba-Angola     08-18 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Angola,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Castro Says Attacks Could Delay Withdrawl of Cuban Troops from Angola</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuban President Fidel Castro has warned that
guerrilla attacks on Cuban troops in Angola could delay the promised
withdrawal of the soldiers from that African country, Cuba's
official news agency said Friday.
   The Prensa Latina agency said that in a letter to U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, Castro accused
anti-communist rebels of attacking Cuban forces.
   ``These criminal and irresponsible actions could have serious
consequences,'' Castro said in the letter, according to the Prensa
Latina dispatch monitored in Mexico City. ``They could influence in
an adverse way the compliance with the timetable on withdrawal of
Cuban troops from Angola.''
   Cuba, under an agreement on a U.N. plan for independence for
Namibia, pledged to withdraw all of its troops from Angola by July
1, 1991.
   Prensa Latina quoted Castro's letter as saying: ``On the morning
of Aug. 14 a group of 15-20 armed subversives of UNITA ambushed a
Cuban truck 16 miles north of Cubal'' and killed six Cuban soldiers.
   ``Because of this act, the Cuban government wants to reiterate
that it will act in whatever manner guarantees, in whatever
circumstance, the security of its internationalist combatants in
Angola,'' the letter said.
   UNITA is the acronym for the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola, a rebel group that has been battling
Angola's Marxist government since Angola gained its independence
from Portugal in 1975.
   Cuba's deputy foreign minister, Ricardo Alarcon Quesada, has said
Cuba had up to 50,000 military personnel in Angola helping the
government fight the rebels. About 1,000 Cuban soldiers have been
killed in Angola in the past 10 years, according to a report by
Jorge Risquet, a member of Cuba's Communist Party Politburo.
   Western estimates are that 5,000 Cuban troopers have been killed
in Angola. UNITA claims that figure is low.
   Namibia, also known as South-West Africa, has been administered
by South Africa since the end of World War I. South Africa in
December agreed to the U.N. independence plan for the territory
sandwiched between Angola and South Africa with the condition that
Cuba withdraw its military force from Angola.
</TEXT>
