<FIRST>r a AM-UnisysRestructuring     08-18 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unisys Restructuring,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unisys To Cut 6,000 Jobs In Restructuring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIRA BILLIK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp. will cut more than 6,000 jobs _
as much as 8 percent of the computer company's worldwide workforce _
by the end of 1990, in a restructuring plan announced Friday.
   The plan is, in effect, an acknowledgement by the hard-driving
chairman of Unisys, W. Michael Blumenthal, that the growth plans of
the nation's third-largest computer maker were too ambitious.
   ``The basic strategies are working as planned ... but our
operational profitability has clearly been inadequate for several
reasons, including the need to work off excess inventories, weaker
than expected U.S. demand, and sharper competition in all industry
segments worldwide,'' Blumenthal said in a statement.
   Blumenthal had envisioned turning Unisys into a $20 billion
company by 1993 to make the company a more credible competitor to
No. 1 International Business Machines Corp.
   Company spokesman Michael A. Stugrin said Friday the $20 billion
goal was merely a dollar figure indicating the growth the company
wanted to achieve.
   ``In the 1989-90 time frame, our major emphasis is operational
profitability and profit margins. We're looking for growth in
revenue and in market share.''
   The restructuring plan, part of a review of all company
operations to be completed by September, is designed to combat an
unexpected drop in domestic demand and tougher competition in the
industry worldwide.
   It follows a 67 percent drop in second-quarter earnings and a
first-half loss of $25.1 million for the company formed in 1986 by
the $4.8 billion purchase of Sperry Corp. by Burroughs Corp.
   Blumenthal said Unisys will cut annual costs by $400 million by
the end of 1990.
   Over the same period, Unisys plans to cut its worldwide workforce
of 88,000 by 7 to 8 percent through attrition and layoffs, Stugrin
said. That amounts to between 6,000 and 7,000 workers, he said.
   Since Unisys has been under a hiring and salary freeze since the
end of the second quarter, employees who retire or leave the company
will not be replaced, Stugrin said.
   Stugrin said a major focus of the job cuts will be in the United
States, where he said ``the softest market conditions prevail,
unfortunately.''
   He said Unisys had ``taken pains to make sure our people
understand the trends in the industry and in the marketplace'' and
that the company had ``a sense of determination to see this through
and go on to better conditions.''
   In the second quarter, Unisys recorded net income of $53.6
million compared with $162.3 million for the same period a year
earlier, the decline attributed to a drop in inventory, pricing
pressure from competitors, and the Pentagon's temporary suspension
of its defense business.
   Blumenthal had also attributed the earnings drop to the rise in
the dollar, decreasing the dollar value of sales made in foreign
currencies.
   In the first half of the year, Unisys lost $25.1 million,
compared with a profit of $311.6 million a year earlier.
   Blumenthal said Unisys is confident it will achieve positive
results and greater profits in 1990.
   In addition to being a major computer maker, Unisys is the
nation's 15th largest defense contractor and received $1.4 billion
in contracts from the Pentagon in 1988.
   IBM's revenue this year will be nearly $60 billion. Digital
Equipment Corp. ranks second with nearly $13 billion in annual
revenue. Unisys is third with a little under $10 billion in revenue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
