<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     08-18 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN Chief Urges Iran, Iraq, To Release POWs and Negotiate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
urged Iran and Iraq on Friday to release prisoners, withdraw their
troops to recognized borders and resume stalled negotiations for a
peace treaty.
   ``As we observe the anniversary of the cease-fire, I call on the
leaders of Iran and Iraq to join me in a renewed effort to complete
this task'' of implementing the U.N. peace plan ``as the way to
achieve an overall political settlement,'' he said in a statement.
   He called for security and stability in the region, and ``peace
which only can be lasting if it is base on the principle of no
victor, no vanquished.''
   A U.N.-mediated cease-fire took effect Aug. 20, 1988, and peace
negotiations began in Geneva five days later, under U.N. auspices.
   The cease-fire has held, but talks stalled after several
sessions. The U.N. plan for withdrawal and repatriation of POWs has
not been implemented and Iraq has injected new elements, including
clearing of the Shatt-al-Arab waterway, the southern border between
the Persian Gulf neighbors.
   In his statement, Perez de Cuellar said the U.N. plan, Security
Council Resolution 598 ``cannot be renegotiated. It represents a
peace plan that must be implemented.''
   ``Countless lives have been spared'' and tension has been reduced
because of the truce, he said, but ``there is no reason for
complacency, for the silencing of guns does not mean the restoration
of security and stability in the region.''
</TEXT>
