<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 2030EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Baltics     08-18 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Baltics,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wisconsin Senator to Speak in Riga</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin has decided to allow the first
visit to Soviet Latvia by a U.S. senator, who plans to give a speech
there urging greater independence for the Baltic republic, officials
said Friday.
   Sen. Robert Kasten, R-Wis., was scheduled to leave Saturday for
the Latvian capital of Riga where he was to take part Monday in a
conference protesting the forcible annexation of the three Baltic
republics by Moscow during World War II. He was to deliver a speech
blaming Soviet authorities for environmental pollution in Latvia.
   ``The government in Moscow is not accountable to the people of
Latvia, or even to the people of Moscow _ and the result is
environmental disaster,'' Kasten was to say in the speech, which was
provided in advance to The Associated Press.
   State Department officials, who spoke on condition they not be
further identified, described the Kremlin decision to allow Kasten
to travel to Latvia and deliver such a critical speech as another
sign of change in the Soviet Union.
   The Bush administration did not object to the visit, said the
officials, despite long-standing U.S. policy not to recognize
Moscow's 1940 annexation of Latvia and its two sister republics,
Lithuania and Estonia. Under this policy, U.S. officials are barred
from having business contacts with senior Communist Party and
government officials in the Baltics republics.
   Kasten was taking part in the ``International Conference on
Self-Determination,'' organized by the National Independence
Movement of Latvia. In a news release, the group described itself as
``an organization campaigning for Latvia's independence from the
U.S.S.R.''
   The group said other congressional visits were expected to Latvia
this autumn.
   Kasten said in his prepared remarks ``officials in Moscow who
make decisions about the use of resources have no interest in
protecting the environment of the Baltic region. Their interest is
in promoting heavy industry _ and in removing the pollution caused
by that industry from the region of Moscow.''
   ``The answer is decentralization, a government closer to the
people. Decisions about the Latvian environment need to be made by
the Latvians _ the people whose children will have to inherit the
Latvia environment from their parents,'' said the speech.
   Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia scored a victory last month when
the national parliament gave preliminary approval to legislation
that would grant them greater economic autonomy, including the right
to print their own currency, starting next Jan. 1.
   That autonomy would include greater control over heavy
industries, which are now run by ministries based in Moscow.
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda signalled on Thursday that
further liberalization was in the wind by suggesting a
reorganization of the Soviet Union to grant even more power to its
15 constituent republics at the expense of central authorites in
Moscow.
</TEXT>
