<HEAD>Contra Leader Announces Return to Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leader of the Nicaraguan
Resistance, the executive branch of the Contra rebels, said Friday
he would return to Nicaragua and join the political opposition.
   Under terms of a Central American peace plan, Nicaragua's
Sandinista government has offered amnesty to rebels who return and
enter the domestic political process.
   Roberto Ferrey, who has been a member of the rebel executive
board since 1987, made his announcement in letters to Joao Baena
Soares, secretary-general of the Organization of American States,
and Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, Roman Catholic archbishop of
Managua.
   In a statement released to news organizations, Ferrey said he
would return on Tuesday. His letter said he would join the National
Opposition Union, a diverse coalition of opposition parties.
   Central American presidents agreed earlier this month to disband
the U.S.-supported rebels before the end of the year. In return,
Nicaragua agreed to hold free and fair elections in February.
   About 11,000 Contras and 12,000 dependents live in camps in
Honduras. Congress ended military aid last year, but provides $4.5
million a month in humanitarian assistance.
   Nicaragua and the Contras agreed March 21 to suspend military
operations, but negotiations toward a permanent end to the
7-year-old war have made little progress.
