<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Refugees     08-18 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Refugees,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks on East German Refugees at Impasse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl's chief of staff
met with a top East German official Friday but reported the two
Germanies are at an impasse over ways to deal with a crush of East
German refugees.
   West Germany closed its embassy in Hungary Monday because of the
number of East Germans who went there seeking to escape to the West.
   Kohl's chief of staff, Rudolf Seiters, met in East Berlin for two
hours with East Germany's deputy foreign minister, Herbert
Krolikowski.
   ``Unfortunately it has to be said that East Germany is not
prepared to go beyond its original promise,'' Seiters told reporters
after the meeting.
   Communist East Germany has said would-be refugees who return
voluntarily will not be punished but it has given them no assurances
their applications to emigrate will be approved.
   Kohl said earlier Friday that he was willing to personally take
up the issue with East German leader Erich Honecker if that was
necessary to ease the strained relations between the two German
states.
   Honecker's has said the relations will become even more difficult
if West Germany continues to shelter more than 300 East Germans at
its embassies and diplomatic missions in Hungary, Poland,
Czechoslovakia and East Berlin.
   West Germany has issued more than 800 passports to other East
German refugees in Hungary who arrived after the embassy was closed.
   Seiters said West Germany wants an impovement in relations ``but
for the foreseeable future they are going to be strained.'' No
further negotiations were agreed to.
   West German government spokesman Herbert Schmuelling told a news
conference earlier Friday that Kohl received a letter from Honecker
Thursday night in reply to Kohl's request that joint efforts be made
to resolve the refugee situation.
   Schmuelling declined to disclose details of the letter but
government sources said Honecker's message resulted in Seiters'
being sent to meet with Krolikowski.
   The failure of that meeting could put pressure on Kohl to travel
to East Berlin to meet with Honecker.
   ``There is certainly no meeting scheduled as a normal course of
events, but it could be that if matters intensify at the Budapest
embassy, that direct contacts would be demanded,'' Kohl told the ARD
broadcast network Friday afternoon. ``I would do this immediately if
it appeared necessary.''
   Honecker made an official trip to Bonn in September 1987. Kohl
has not returned the visit and has suggested such a meeting depends
in part on improved relations.
   East Germans, angered at the lack of reform in their country,
have been going by the hundreds to neighboring Hungary, which began
dismantling its barbed-wire border with neutral Austria in May. East
Germans can travel freely to Hungary as another Soviet-bloc country.
   At least 1,600 East Germans are thought to have escaped
undetected, based on the number of refugees showing up at the West
German Embassy in Vienna for help in obtaining West German documents.
   Foreign Ministry sources reported Thursday that 1,100 East
Germans sought papers from the Vienna embassy during the first two
weeks of August.
   East Germans are automatically entitled to West German
citizenship under the West German constitution but they need exit
visas from their government to go to the West.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
