<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     08-18 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Meets with Alliance Linked to Radicals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa has met
with leaders of a political alliance with links to radical Sinhalese
and appealed for a cease-fire, an official said Friday.
   The official in the presidential secretariat spoke on condition
he not be identified.
   He said Premadasa met with leaders of the Sri Lanka Progressive
Front Thursday and suggesed a week-long cease-fire as the first step
toward peace negotiations with the radicals. He said no decision was
reached during the 90-minute talks.
   It was the first meeting between the president and the front
which is believed to have close links to Sinhalese groups that have
been waging a terrorist campaign against the government. The
violence has taken at least 4,000 lives.
   Samuel Dias Bandaranayake, president of the front, told The
Associated Press he asked Premadasa to step down and hold
parliamentary and presidential elections.
   He said he also called for abrogating a 1987 agreement between
Sri Lanka and India, which was aimed at ending the war by ethnic
Tamil separatists demanding an independent nation.
   Sinhalese militants rejected the accord, saying it gave too many
concessions to the minority Tamils and infringed on Sri Lanka's
sovereignity by allowing Indian troops to operate on the island
nation.
   The Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people. They claim discrimination by the
predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese.
   About 60 million Tamils live in southern India and under the 1987
pact India sent more than 40,000 military personnel to Sri Lanka to
enforce the plan that promised Tamils limited autonomy in exchange
for ending the guerrilla war.
   But the militant Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam rejected the
accord and has battled the Indian forces.
   At least 11,000 people, including 1,000 Indian soldiers, have
been killed in the separatist war launched by Tamil activists in
1983.
</TEXT>
