<FIRST>u a AM-TeenAssault     08-18 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen Assault,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youth Surrenders to Authorities in Alleged Sexual Assault</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE P. BAYLISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man charged in a group sexual assault on a
17-year-old girl surrendered to police Friday, and a warrant has
issued for another suspect whose police lieutenant father
investigated the case, officials said.
   The young man pleaded innocent before Family Court Judge Julio
Fuentes to charges of conspiracy to commit sexual assault and
aggravated criminal sexual contact in the March 1 attack, said an
official familiar with the case who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The 18-year-old man, who was not identified despite his age
because the alleged crime occurred when he was 17, was released to
his parents' custody.
   On May 24, five high school students were arrested and charged
with participating in the assault on a special education student in
the affluent suburb of Glen Ridge. Officials at Glen Ridge High
School described many of those charged as student leaders, including
the captains of several school teams.
   Prosecutors alleged that the girl was assaulted with a broomstick
and a baseball bat at the home of two of the student athletes. The
girl went to West Orange High School, but lives in Glen Ridge and
knew the suspects.
   Fuentes on Friday postponed until Oct. 5 a hearing on whether to
try the young man and two other juveniles charged in the case as
adults, the official said.
   The lieutenant's son, 19-year-old Richard Corcoran Jr., is
expected to surrender Monday, the Essex County prosecutor's office
said in a news release. The release did not state when the warrant
for him was issued.
   Corcoran is to be arraigned in Essex County Superior Court on
charges of conspiracy to commit sexual assault, aggravated sexual
assault and aggravated sexual conduct, the release said.
   Corcoran's father is Glen Ridge's chief detective and led the
investigation into the incident. He was taken off the case five
weeks after his son was identified as one of 13 people present
during the assault.
   Prosecutors originally described Corcoran as a witness, but said
the charges were brought after new evidence was obtained.
   Prosecutor's spokesman Ray Weiss declined to describe the
evidence, saying the case was still under investigation.
   Prosecutors have said the attack occurred in the home of Kevin
and Kyle Scherzer, 18-year-old twins who have been charged in the
case. Charges also were filed against Peter Quigley, 18, and the two
other juveniles.
   All are free on bond. A grand jury is scheduled to examine the
case next month.
   The charges against Corcoran resulted from a joint investigation
by Glen Ridge police and the prosecutor's office, the release said.
The probe began when it was learned the young man was present during
the attack.
   ``The fact that charges have been filed against Richard Corcoran
Jr. in no way implies that the Glen Ridge Police Department
committed any impropriety in connection with the investigation,''
the statement said.
   Glen Ridge police will continue to be involved in the
investigation, the prosecutor's office said. Glen Ridge Police Chief
Thomas Dugan declined to comment on the case or Lt. Corcoran's role
in it.
</TEXT>
