<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-ForestFire     08-18 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Forest Fire,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Forces Evacuation of Tourists on Thassos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tourists have been evacuated from the
resort island of Thassos in the northern Aegean because of a fire in
its mountain woodlands, officials said Friday.
   ``Ferryboats have been plying back and forth ... and just about
all visitors have left the island,'' said Christos Panagis, a harbor
officer in Kavala on the mainland 90 minutes from Thassos by boat.
   A police officer reached by telephone on Thassos said he could
not say how many tourists were evacuated but the process was orderly.
   An Athens radio station said Kavala fire officials believed the
fire, which started in four places simultaneously, was caused by
arson.
   Agriculture Minister Stavros Dimas said Friday that 25 percent of
the fires that have destroyed 50,000 acres of forest in 10 days were
started by arsonists.
   Air currents on the mountainous terrain of Thassos made it
difficult for five fire-fighting aircraft to dump water on the fires
moving toward the evacuated villages of Sotiros, Kallirahi, Agios
Giorgis, Prinos, Maries and Rahoni, officials said..
   Panagis said flames could be seen from the harbor in Limeni, the
island's main town, but fire-breaks were expected to keep the flames
away from the town.
   Thassos was put under a state of emergency Thursday. Soldiers and
fire-fighting equipment from throughout northern Greece were moved
in to combat the blaze.
   The Thassos police officer, who would not give his name, said
some barns and abandoned dwellings on the outskirts of villages had
been burned.
   The national forest fire control center would not say how large
an area had been destroyed by the fire, which began early Thursday,
but unofficial estimates put it at more than 8,600 acres.
</TEXT>
