<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1934EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-VAMortgages     08-18 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-VA Mortgages,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Blocks New Cost Formula For Foreclosures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Friday blocked the
Department of Veterans Affairs from implementing a regulation next
week on VA home loans that the mortgage industry says will leave it
holding the bag more often when borrowers default.
   U.S. District Judge George H. Revercomb said in his preliminary
injunction that VA appeared to have exceeded its legal authority
when it added the cost of borrowing funds to its formula for
determining the worth of foreclosed property.
   The regulations, which had been due to take effect Monday, would
change the calculation to arrive at how much the property is worth,
the standard VA uses to determine whether it will purchase
foreclosed properties with VA-guaranteed mortgages.
   The injunction remains in effect until a full hearing on the
complaint by the Mortgage Bankers Association can be heard. The
association, which represents some 2,200 mortgage lending
institutions, said in a statement that the hearing may not take
place for several months.
   ``This decision signals a victory for mortgage lenders, but the
real beneficiaries will be veterans who will be able to continue to
have access to low-downpayment VA mortgages,'' said Warren Lasko,
executive vice president of the organization.
   The organization says implementation of the regulation ``would
have seriously impaired a program that has successfully served over
13 million veteran homebuyers.''
   Under the veterans loan program, the VA guarantees to the
mortgage lender that it will pay 40 percent or 50 percent of the
mortgage debt if the borrower defaults. The maximum guarantee is
$36,000.
   Until 1984, VA bought the foreclosed property in nearly every
case, ``even when it did not make financial sense to do so,''
Revercomb noted in his ruling. But Congress, in the Deficit
Reduction Act, required a ``no-bid formula'' to specify when VA
would purchase the properties.
   VA, under the regulations, is required to calculate what the
property is worth by taking its fair market value _ the price it
would command in the real estate market _ and subtracting a variety
of costs. The VA would not repurchase homes that it would end up
reselling at a loss.
   The lawsuit was filed after the VA issued regulations July 19
adding ``cost of funds'' to the net worth formula. That is the cost
to the government of borrowing money to buy the foreclosed property
until it can be resold. The association contends this cost is not
permitted in the formula prescribed by Congress.
   ``When the regulation at issue here goes into effect, it is
undeniable that some mortgage bankers will be concretely and
monetarily injured because the VA will purchase fewer foreclosed
homes than it does now, thus placing more of the potential loss on
the mortgage banker,'' Revercomb said.
   Neither VA nor the Justice Department would comment immediately
on the ruling.
   Foreclosure actions on VA-backed loans have risen sharply in
recent years, due largely to the real estate slump in Texas and
Oklahoma. The Government National Mortgage Association, an arm of
the Department of Housing and Urban Development, says six lenders
defaulted in 1988 that had financial problems linked to the
so-called ``no-bids.''
   The president's budget message this year estimated the new
regulation would result in 10 percent fewer property acquisitions.
The industry group says its average loss on a piece of property VA
does not acquire is more than $18,000.
   According to a General Accounting Office report in July,
foreclosures rose from 13,729 in fiscal 1981 to 43,316 in 1987. In
those same two years, VA annual losses rose from $51 million to $615
million, GAO said.
   The industry group says its losses from VA's refusal to bid on
foreclosed property totaled $200 million last year.
   The report by GAO, the investigative arm of Congress, supported
the new regulations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
