<FIRST>u i AM-Palme     08-18 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palme,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Grants New Trial For Man Convicted in Palme Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court agreed Friday to a hold
a new trial next month for the man convicted in the slaying of Prime
Minister Olof Palme, the national TT news agency said.
   Christer Pettersson was sentenced to life in prison last month
after his conviction. Pettersson, a 42 year old with a lengthy
criminal record, denied shooting the four-term prime minister and
appealed.
   The prosecution also appealed because it wanted to convict
Pettersson of attempted murder in the wounding of Palme's widow,
Lisbeth, in the attack in February 1986. Pettersson was convicted of
the lesser charge of endangering Mrs. Palme's life.
   In Sweden, reviews by appellate courts are automatic if either
side appeals, but the appellate court has the choice of either
recalling witnesses or simply reviewing the records of the lower
court.
   The makeup of the appeals court differs from the district court,
in that a majority on the jury are professional jurists and a
minority are lay jurors.
   In the district court, the six lay jurors voted to convict
Pettersson and the two judges voted to acquit.
   The new trial will begin Sept. 12 in the Svea Court of Appeals,
the TT news agency said.
   Palme was shot Feb. 28, 1986 while walking home from a movie with
his wife.
   Mrs. Palme claimed she saw Pettersson a few feet away immediately
after her husband was shot.
   Another witness, however, testified he saw Pettersson at a train
station nowhere near the scene of the shooting a short while after
the murder.
   Defense attorney Arne Liljeros said a new witness who did not
testify at the first trial also claims to have seen Pettersson at
the train station.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
