<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Pact     08-18 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Pact,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politburo Member Confirms Secret Soviet-Nazi Pact, Urges Condemnation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politburo member Alexander Yakovlev conceded in an
interview published today that there was no doubt that the Soviet
Union and Nazi Germany secretly agreed to divide Eastern Europe.
   Yakovlev, who heads a parliamentary panel charged with finding
the truth about the 1939 Molotov-Ribbentrop pact, is the first
member of the ruling Politburo to reverse decades of Kremlin denials
that secret protocols dividing Poland and the Baltic states existed.
   ``There was, without doubt, a collusion,'' he told the Communist
Party daily. He said the agreements should be ``unequivocally
condemned.''
   The issue is at the heart of a drive by Latvia, Lithuania and
Estonia to gain more independence from the Soviet Union by
challenging the legitimacy of its control over the Baltic region.
   Yakovlev, echoing an approach taken in the past few weeks among
Soviet historians, denied that the secret pact had any bearing on
the Baltic states' current legal status.
   ``It is necessary to admit that neither the treaty nor protocol
determined the legal and political status of Lithuania, Latvia and
Estonia,'' he said. ``It is even more far-fetched to seek some kind
of interrelation between the present status of the three republics
and the non-aggression treaty.''
   ``I believe that we'll be acting responsibly and in a politically
principled way by having unequivocally condemned the pre-war Soviet
leadership's deviation from Leninist principles of foreign policy,
no matter how it is explained,'' he added.
   Soviet history books contend the Baltic republics voluntarily
joined the Soviet Union. The United States subscribes to many Balts'
claims that they were forced into the union by the occupying Red
Army and does not recognize the Baltic annexation.
   The republics plan a series of protests and other events to
commemorate the anniversary of the pact on Wednesday, including a
human chain stretching from Estonia to Lithuania.
   Yakovlev's commission has not issued its formal conclusions, but
members have said publicly the report will say the protocols existed
and condemn them.
   For decades, the Soviet Union denied the existence of the secret
protocols to the non-aggression pact, which was signed by foreign
ministers Joachim Von Ribbentrop and Vyacheslav Molotov one week
before Germany invaded Poland.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev told the Congress of People's
Deputies in June that it was difficult to form a conclusion on the
protocols because no one had been able to locate the original
documents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
