<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-NATO     08-18 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-NATO,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greece Will Participate in NATO Exercise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greece will participate in one NATO
military exercise later this year but not another one because of its
dispute with fellow NATO member Turkey, the Athens News Agency
reported Friday.
   The semiofficial agency quoted Defense Ministry sources as saying
Greece would take part in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization's
``Deterrent Force'' exercise in the western Mediterranean from Oct.
9-Nov. 14.
   The sources, who were not identified, said Greece will not
participate in the ``Display Determination'' maneuvers in late
September and early October in the eastern Mediterranean, Black Sea
and certain parts of Turkish territory because of the exclusion of
the Greek island of Limnos from the exercise.
   Greece has refused since 1985 to join in any NATO exercises in
the Aegean that excludes Limnos, off Turkey's western coast.
   Turkey claims Limnos has been militarized in violation of a 1922
treaty but Greece claims that treaty was annulled by another treaty
in 1936.
   Other countries scheduled to take part in the ``Deterrent Force''
operation are the United States, Italy and Turkey.
</TEXT>
