<FIRST>u a AM-EngineFailure 2ndLd-Writethru a0691 08-18 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Engine Failure, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0691,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plane Lands Safely After Engine Fails</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Morrison said ..., with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
engine manufacturer, comment from FAA; pick up 8th graf: `Erp said ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Trans World Airlines MD-80 airliner landed
safely Friday at Lambert St. Louis International Airport after an
engine came apart on takeoff and a two-foot piece of it narrowly
missed a man on the ground.
   ``I heard a large explosion and then I heard a lot of debris
hitting the roof,'' said Mark Erp, 29, manager of an auto body shop
in Kinloch, next to St. Louis' Lambert airport.
   ``Then a big hunk came through the roof and hit the floor about
10 or 15 feet from me,'' he said. ``I had been walking that way.
Needless to say, I just dived away. I didn't know if there was more
coming.''
   Officials said Flight 223 from St. Louis to San Francisco had
just taken off about 10:15 a.m. when passengers heard a loud pop and
the pilot announced that the plane was returning to the airport. The
plane made a routine landing and there were no injuries, said TWA
spokesman Don Morrison.
   Morrison said the flight was canceled, and the 112 passengers
were put on another flight.
   Morrison said the engine was designed to eject loose parts to
minimize problems. ``We understand some pieces fell, and we're
investigating,'' Morrison said.
   Morrison said the engine part that fell was a cone, the rear
cover for one of the plane's Pratt &amp; Whitney engines.
   Fred Farrar, a Federal Aviation Administration spokesman in
Washington, said a piece of cowling that wraps around the engine
apparently came off.
   Farrar said the plane could have been flown safely without the
cowling but that the pilot probably did the right thing by aborting
the flight. ``Given the fact that we have 19,000 flights per day in
this country, we may have one report like this a month,'' Farrar
said.
   Morrison said the plane was being examined to determine the cause
of the engine failure.
   Erp said the engine part that fell into his shop was a metal cone
about 2 feet long that weighed about 15 pounds. He said it ripped a
5-foot-square hole in the roof of the building.
   ``We started to pick it up but it was red hot,'' he said. ``It
was still too hot to touch about 30 minutes later.''
   Erp said TWA officials who reclaimed the debris were at the shop
only briefly. ``They just took the cone and picked up some smaller
pieces and left,'' Erp said. ``They didn't say a whole lot. I guess
they didn't want to talk about it.''
</TEXT>
