<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 2342EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HostageStandoff     08-18 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostage Standoff,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Counselors Looking for Homes for Nine Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine Laotian children orphaned by the
murder-suicide of their parents following a tense 6{-hour hostage
drama were in the temporary custody of relatives Friday, authorities
said.
   Church and county counselors said they have begun to look for
permanent homes for the youngsters.
   Bao Cha, mother of the children, ages one to 13, was fatally shot
Thursday evening by her husband, Dang Cha Xiong, who then put the
handgun to his own head as eight of their nine children huddled in
another room of their apartment.
   The ninth child, a 12-year-old boy, fled from the apartment
earlier through a window and alerted police that his father was
inside with a handgun, threatening his mother and playing Russian
roulette with the other children.
   None of the children was injured.
   Deputy Police Chief Lucian Neely said Dang, 35, had been
convicted last year of two misdemeanor counts of abuse and cruelty
to his children, and was prohibited under the terms of his probation
from visiting his wife or children.
   Neely said Dang served four months in county jail on the original
cruelty charges, and that he was returned to jail twice since then,
in January and again in June, for violating terms of his probation
by visiting his family.
   Dang had been released from jail on the most recent probation
violation on Monday, and Neely said investigators believe that he
went to his wife's apartment Thursday because he blamed her for his
probation violation arrest.
   ``There's no way I can ever say what the motive was, but the
timing suggests something related to that,'' the deputy chief said
of the probation violations.
   More than 50 officers surrounded the home in a neat apartment
complex populated largely by Asian refugee families near the
University of the Pacific campus. Hostage negotiators talked with
Dang by telephone for several hours.
   Neely said Dang sounded cooperative on the telephone. But after
Dang said he would surrender and lay down his gun, police heard four
shots.
   Officers rushed the apartment and found the children in a front
room and the two wounded parents in a rear bedroom. The mother was
pronounced dead within minutes and the father about two hours later.
   Police did not fire any shots during the siege, Neely said.
   Neely said officers originally believed that several of the
hostages were children of neighbors, but that later interviews with
family members confirmed all nine were Dang's children.
   He said the children spent Thursday night with relatives, and
that county Child Protective Services officers and representatives
of church-related refugee services agencies were jointly taking
responsibility for arranging permanent placement of the children.
   Stockton has a large community of refugees from Southeast Asia
served by several public and volunteer social service agencies.
   Five Stockton children killed last Jan. 17 by a deranged gunman
in a school yard were also refugees from Southeast Asia, as were
most of the 29 children wounded in that attack.
   In a statement Friday, Stockton Mayor Barbara Fass noted that
earlier incident, and the image of her city projected by another
incident involving refugee children.
   ``I think it's the media that's giving the city a bad reputation.
It's a hostage situation, a family feud like that happens,
unfortunately, in every major city in the country,'' Fass said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890818-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 2226EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-TruckFire-Ammunition     08-18 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Truck Fire-Ammunition,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ammunition Truck Fire Kills One, Backs Up Traffic for Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCK SPRINGS, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck carrying 40,000 rounds of
ammunition for warplanes went up in flames and explosions early
Friday, killing the driver, injuring her husband and closing an
interstate for hours, authorities said.
   The tractor-trailer rig, loaded with 20mm shells for aircraft
cannon, veered off Interstate 17 into a ditch and caught fire in a
remote area about 30 miles north of Phoenix around 1 a.m., officials
said.
   ``The shells kept exploding; it was like fireworks,'' said Rock
Springs Fire Chief Pete Davis. ``There were shells for about 100
yards on either side. You couldn't walk without stepping on one.''
   Although no evacuations were necessary, the sporadic explosions
kept authorities at bay until about 5:30 a.m., Davis said.
   The body of the driver, Lois Bailey, 38, of Coleman, Ala., wasn't
found for hours because of the danger, said State Department of
Public Safety spokesman Allan Schmidt.
   Her 33-year-old husband, Rick, was in serious condition at John
C. Lincoln Hospital in Phoenix, hospital spokeswoman Lisa Boulay
said.
   The backup on I-17, the major link between Phoenix and Flagstaff,
stretched 10 miles and traffic was delayed up to two hours, Schmidt
said. The highway was not fully reopened until all it had been
cleared of shells more than 14 hours after the accident.
   People were kept several hundred yards from the accident scene as
a four-person Army explosives team recovered 400 of an estimated 600
unexploded shells, Schmidt said.
   ``There is no way we could recover everything today,'' he said.
``This armament is spread throughout this area.''
   The truck, hauling the ammunition from Fort Huachuca in Sierra
Vista in southeast Arizona to the Navajo Army Depot near Flagstaff,
apparently was traveling through a storm when it veered left into a
guardrail, Schmidt said.
   Schmidt said it was not known what caused the truck to veer.
``The whole load came forward, crushing the cab,'' Schmidt said.
``Some of the ammunition was thrown. The fire was all-consuming.''
   Bailey, who was sleeping while his wife drove, apparently crawled
several hundred yards across the interstate to the Rock Springs
general store.
   By the time officials were able to approach the truck, all but a
few boxes of the ammunition had exploded, Schmidt said. Spent
casings littered the area.
   The shipment being hauled under a contract with the military
originated in San Antonio, said Lt. Col. Ed Cooke of Kelly Air Force
Base there. The 37,000 pounds of Class D ammunition was taken to
Fort Huachuca from a depot at Lackland Air Force Base operatated by
Kelly, Cooke said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890818-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 0022EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LBJReunion     08-18 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LBJ Reunion,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aides Planning for 25th Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former aides of Lyndon B. Johnson are
planning a 25th anniversary reunion they hope will bring together
U.S. and Vietnamese officials for the first time to discuss the war
that tore the administration apart.
   Organizers also hope next year's gathering to mark President
Johnson's inauguration in January 1965 will be the largest reunion
ever of a presidential administration.
   Sponsored by the Lyndon Baines Johnson Foundation, the events are
scheduled for April 6-7 in Washington, D.C., and May 3-5 in Austin,
said Robert Hardesty, a former Johnson aide.
   Harry Middleton, director of the LBJ Library at the University of
Texas, is chairman of program, which includes a daylong symposium on
the Vietnam War. Former Defense Secretary Robert McNamara will be
invited, said Harry McPherson, chairman of the symposium.
   McPherson, a special counsel to Johnson and today a lawyer in
Washington, also hopes members of the North Vietnamese, Chinese and
Soviet governments will participate.
   He said he is inviting officials of America's adversaries in the
war through journalist and author Stanley Karnow.
   ``These are people who were well-placed in the defense and
foreign ministries of those governments. We would like to know a lot
more of the options our enemy was considering during the war. Having
them join in would offer historians a tremendous opportunity,''
McPherson said.
   Other events will include a speech by former U.S. Rep. Barbara
Jordan and a barbecue at the LBJ Ranch to discuss Johnson's ``Great
Society'' programs, said Hardesty, a speech writer for Johnson and
later president of Southwest Texas State University.
   Johnson, harried by the rising tide of public opinion against the
Vietnam War, chose not to run for a second term. He died in 1973.
   Two events are planned in Washington: an April 6 reunion at the
historic Mayflower Hotel for members of the Johnson administration,
and a program the next day at the National Press Club to discuss
Johnson and his legacy.
   Similar discussions will be conducted May 5 at the LBJ Library in
Austin. From such discussions, the planners expect to produce a
documentary film.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
