<HEAD>Girl in Lukens Case Ordered Held in Custody</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who had accused U.S. Rep.
Donald Lukens of having sex with her was ordered held in custody
Thursday on two charges filed by her mother.
   Franklin County Juvenile Court referee Jeff Liston ruled that
Rosie Coffman is out of control and that he would hold her until
trial.
   A trial date was not set, but it is to be held within 10 days.
   Ms. Coffman, 17, was arrested Wednesday and charged with criminal
damaging and menacing, based on complaints filed by her mother, Anna
Coffman, of Columbus.
   The referee's decision was made after Rosie Coffman's first court
appearance on the charges.
   Rosie Coffman's allegations against Lukens led to his May 26
conviction and subsequent sentencing on a misdemeanor charge of
contributing to the unruliness of a minor. The 58-year-old
Republican was sentenced to 30 days in jail and fined $500 by
Franklin County Domestic Relations Court Judge Ronald Solove.
   The aggravated menacing charge stemmed from a July 27 incident in
which Rosie Coffman allegedly threatened to hit her mother with a
telephone. According to testimony, Rosie would not get off the phone
when asked by her mother.
   The criminal damaging charge resulted from an incident on Aug. 13
at the Coffman residence. According to testimony, Rosie Coffman
tried to pry open a door to the house after she was locked out.
   Rosie Coffman was being held in the county's juvenile detention
center.
   The girl and her mother were key figures in Lukens' trial.
   Rosie Coffman claimed she was paid by Lukens to have sex with him
at his Columbus apartment last November, when she was 16. She said
Lukens knew she was underage at the time.
   Anna Coffman's complaint to Columbus television station WSYX late
last year led to an investigation that resulted in Lukens'
indictment in February.
   She testified that during a meeting with Lukens at a fast-food
restaurant in November, Lukens offered to find her a government job
after she confronted him with accusations that he had sex with her
daughter.
   The meeting was secretly videotaped by the television station.
   Mrs. Coffman was jailed in June for a probation violation
stemming from a 1983 drunken driving conviction. She was released to
serve the rest of her 2{-month sentence at her home, where her
movement is monitored by an electronic band attached to her ankle.
