<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 0608EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w AM-NTSBProblems 1stLd-Writethru b0302-b0303 08-18 1279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NTSB Problems, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0302-b0303, Adv 21,1310</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, Aug 21 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Staff Shortages, Other Woes at NTSB</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This recasts b0302-b0303 of Aug. 16. A spot story, highlighting
the Banks memo, moved in the Fri AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Transportation Safety Board, now
in its second year under an acting director, is struggling to cope
with a shrinking investigtive staff and a tight budget as it tries
to learn the causes of the nation's worst air, sea and ground
accidents.
   Four congressmen say the situation is worsening and recently
wrote President Bush, asking him to nominate a director as a first
step in rebuilding morale and retaining the agency's reputation as a
leading safety advocate.
   More pointedly, a top NTSB official has complained that his
investigative staff may dwindle so much by year's end that the
agency will have to curtail by one-third the 3,000 or so accident
investigtions it undertakes each year.
   ``The bureau's situation is critical and worsening,'' wrote the
official, Herbert Banks, the NTSB's field operations director.
   Criticism of the agency's actions _ or lack of them _ also comes
from former employees, who charge that the acting chairman, James
Kolstad, is afraid to make waves within the government or in the
industries his agencies is supposed to watch over.
   Kolstad has been acting director since Aug. 14, 1988, after Jim
Burnett failed to win senatorial approval for a fourth two-year term
as chairman.
   Burnett, who had acquired a reputation as a strong, independent
safety advocate, is widely believe to have angered Sen. Wendell
Ford, D-Ky. and the chairman of the Senate aviation subcommittee,
with a speech blasting Ford's proposal to separate the Federal
Aviation Administration from the Transportation Department.
   Burnett's renomination languished without the Senate even holding
a hearing into the matter.
   Since then, Kolstad has become the target of criticism that he
has not dealt with morale problems, has not pushed for increases in
the NTSB's $25.4 million budget, and has not stopped the outflow of
investigators.
   Recently, four ranking members of the House Space, Science and
Technology Committee told Bush that he should nominate a chairman.
   ``We believe that continued uncertainty may have a detrimental
effect on the activities of the board and its respected leadership
role in transportation safety,'' said the letter. The congressmen
said low morale ``could lead to the loss of valuable expertise and
experience.''
   It was signed by Rep. Robert Roe, D-N.J., the committee's
chairman; Rep. Robert Walker of Pennsylvania, the ranking
Republican; Rep. Tim Valentine, D-S.C., chairman of the panel's
transportation subcommittee; and Rep. Tom Lewis, R-Fla., the
subcommittee's ranking GOP member.
   For his part, Kolstad said in an interview that he believes
morale is better than it was when he took over. But he added:
   ``There is a concern that we have people in an acting capacity,
because it suggests that a lot of change that might otherwise occur
can't occur. There is frustration among some staff people. It's in
everyone's interest that the matter be resolved.''
   Burnett's supporters, speaking anonymously, maintain that while
Bush may favor Burnett, a longtime political supporter and campaign
activist for Bush in Arkansas, some White House advisers dislike
Burnett's outspokeness on safety issues.
   These sources maintain that there has been extensive industry
lobbying to keep Kolstad, a former public relations vice president
for Frontier Airlines, as chairman.
   As for the future of the board's investigations, Banks, the field
operations director, projected in a May 11 memo that six more
investigators would quit by the end of the year, making the NTSB to
unable to live up to its congressional mandate to investigate all
airplane crashes.
   His memo, forecasting that the agency would have to cut the
number of accidents it investigates a year by 900, never made it to
the board. It was sent back by the board's staff director, Lloyd
Miller, preventing the issue from being debated by the board and,
perhaps, being aired at a public hearing.
   Miller, like Kolstad, disagreed with the severity of Banks'
assessment and thought the situation not serious enough to be put
before the board. Banks declined to discuss the memo with a reporter.
   For his part, Kolstad discounted Bank's concerns as ``overly
pessimistic'' and said no major investigations or critical safety
problems would be affected at the NTSB, which examines airplane
crashes, sea disasters, major highway accidents and pipeline breaks.
   ``There has been a cutback'' in investigations, Kolstad said.
``But, frankly, we've got fewer accidents; the accident rate is
improving. That doesn't suggest we have enough people to investigate
the accidents that exist, because we don't, but I think we're doing
a better job on the ones that we are investigating.''
   Major investigations now under way include two recent incidents
involving explosive engine failures in DC-10s, other airliner
accidents, oil spills in Alaska and elsewhere, and several freight
train derailments.
   Over the last decade, the NTSB's staff has been reduced from more
than 400 to 324, with many key investigators leaving for
higher-paying, private jobs.
   Some NTSB staff members praise Kolstad as personable and
competent. Private air safety consultant Charles Miller, once the
NTSB's director of accident investigtions, describes the acting
chairman as a ``fine individual'' who recognizes his limitations.
   Others once associated with the agency have a different opinion.
   ``Kolstad is a caretaker who doesn't take care of the board,''
said former NTSB public affairs director Ira J. Furman, a Woodmere,
N.Y., lawyer who stays close to transportation safety issues and
still visits accident sites as a media consultant.
   Furman, who left the board in 1987, when Burnett was chairman,
said Kolstad has failed to push hard within the Bush administration
for a bigger agency budget.
   J. Peter Kissinger, who resigned from the agency's staff last
week after being shifted from managing director of the staff to a
job with considerably less responsibility, said Kolstad ``doesn't
want to rock the boat.''
   While the NTSB has no regulatory power of its own, it is the
government's primary accident investigation agency and makes
recommendations to Congress, other agencies and transportation
industries.
   Burnett and Kolstad have sharply different styles and are often
at odds on safety issues. The former chairman is sometimes the only
dissenter on the board; the acting chairman has been low key, rarely
taking strong positions in open meetings.
   Critics of the NTSB cite several incidents as evidence of
problems:
   _The board failed to investigate the complaint this spring of 60
air traffic controllers in Cleveland who signed a petition citing
high-altitude ``air traffic chaos'' and calling for steps to
alleviate the ``hazardous environment.''
   Lloyd Miller, the acting managing director, headed off the
petition before it reached the board, contending it would be a bad
precedent to investigate what might be a labor-management problem.
   _Kolstad was the board member assigned to the Exxon Valdez oil
spill but did not go to Alaska to head the investigation.
   Kolstad answered that charge be saying that he has been very
active in the inquiry and that he decided not to go because other
high government officials were going and he did not see the need for
``sending another big name to the scene.''
   _While imposing a hiring freeze to meet its budget, the board
held a meeting for top personnel in Miami and the acting chairman
made two official trips to Europe.
   Kolstad said that the Miami meeting provided important dialogue
with industry representatives and that the board had gotten ``a good
deal'' on hotel accommodations and other expenses. He said both
European trips were worthwhile and part of his official duties.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Aug. 21</NOTE>
