<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 0156EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights     08-18 0801</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0840</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit shrank to $8.17 billion
in June, the smallest monthly imbalance since December 1984, the
government said.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday the June deficit showed a
dramatic 18.9 percent narrowing from a revised May figure of $10.08
billion, reflecting record U.S. export sales and a drop in imports.
   The June report, which was significantly better than had been
expected, was hailed by the Bush administration as evidence that
American manufacturers were enjoying continued success in
penetrating foreign markets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bell Atlantic Corp. and one of its striking
unions reached tentative agreement on the framework of a new
contract, but unresolved local issues and continuing differences
with another union prevented an end to a 13-day strike.
   The agreement Thursday between Bell Atlantic and the
Communications Workers of America on broad issues was interpreted as
a sign the strike could end within days. But the company was still
negotiating with the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers.
   Three other regional Bell companies also are being struck by the
same two unions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent securities trader whose highly
publicized arrest in an insider trading case two years ago caused a
sensation on Wall Street said he will plead guilty to mail fraud as
part of an agreement with federal prosecutors.
   Robert M. Freeman, 47, also quit his job Thursday as head of
Goldman Sachs &amp; Co.'s arbitrage operation. In a letter, he told the
firm he decided to plea to halt the ordeal of a criminal
investigation that began 2{ years ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines has agreed to buy 26 more
Airbus Industrie jetliners for $2.7 billion, giving the carrier
confirmed orders for 61 of the low-noise, high-technology jets and
options for 79 more.
   The order, which confirms options Northwest has held since April
1987, calls for 20 A340s, which cost $93 million each and seat up to
280 passengers, and six A330s, which cost $89 million each and seat
up to 330 passengers, Northwest spokesman Bob Gibbons said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor leaders condemned the multibillion-dollar
hostile takeover bid for Britain's BAT Industries PLC and its U.S.
affiliates, pledging to enlist public opinion plus state and federal
lawmakers in their fight.
   The takeover ``would jeopardize the livelihoods of 55,000
American workers,'' John DeConcini, international president of the
Bakery, Confectionery and Tobacco Workers International Union, said
Thursday.
   An investment group headed by Anglo-French financier Sir James
Goldsmith, British merchant banker Jacob Rothschild, Austrian
investor Kerry Packer last month made an offer for BAT that it
valued at some $21.6 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuelan president Carlos Andres
Perez said Venezuela will seek a 50 percent reduction of its
estimated $20.3 billion debt with commercial banks.
   Perez, speaking Thursday in his twice monthly press conference,
added that the position was not an ultimatum but said, ``the
conclusion is that we must seek more or less this 50 percent
reduction because it is what we need.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ISSAQUAH, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has
subpoenaed several top officials and former employees of Egghead
Inc. as part of an investigation of allegations of securities fraud.
   Egghead, which owns Egghead Discount Software, one of the
nation's largest personal computer software chains, said Thursday
the investigation apparently was triggered by a class-action lawsuit
filed July 18 in U.S. District Court in Seattle by shareholders.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 462 money market mutual
funds rose by $2.29 billion in the latest week to a new all-time
high of $340.51 billion, the Investment Company Institute says.
   It was the seventh straight week of new records in the fund
assets, despite a decline in interest rates that has made such
investments less attractive.
   The rise reported Thursday broke the record set a week earlier of
$338.21 billion, revised downward slightly from the $338.35 billion
figure originally reported.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LANTANA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's supermarket tabloid king could
soon be telling readers in Spanish about sightings of the ``fantasma
de Elvis'' or aliens from ``espacio exterior.''
   The new owners of the National Enquirer and Weekly World News
tabloids say they are proceeding with expansion plans that include a
Spanish-language edition and international editions.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Concern about interest rates shook the stock market Thursday and
sent prices down in the busiest day this week.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 13.66 points to
finish at 2,679.63, after trading down about 25 points during the
session.
   Bond prices fell on fresh signs of economic strength.
   The dollar rose sharply worldwide.
   Copper futures prices rocketed higher; soybeans for August
delivery tumbled; energy futures were lower; most livestock and meat
futures advanced; and precious metals were narrowly mixed.
</TEXT>
