<FIRST>r f PM-TrumpShuttle-Pearls     08-18 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trump Shuttle-Pearls,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Shuttle Attendants Wearing Pearls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire developer Donald Trump promised to
make his air shuttle service a diamond when he bought it from
Eastern Airlines, but he's settling for false pearls.
   Female flight attendants employed by Trump Shuttle are now
required to wear ``faux'' pearl necklaces and earrings as part of
their uniforms, provided by the airline.
   ``It's a very nice look,'' Trump Shuttle spokeswoman Joan Fudala
said Thursday. ``It does give a very professional look to the
uniform.''
   The single-strand necklaces are about 15 inches long, Ms. Fudala
said. She noted that false pearls have been given new respectability
by First Lady Barbara Bush, who has admitted to wearing them.
   The spokeswoman said she didn't know the cost of the pearls.
Trump Shuttle, which links New York with Boston and Washington,
employs 255 flight attendants, most of them women. Their uniforms
are navy blue with burgundy stripes on the sleeves.
   Trump, who started operating the shuttle on June 8, shortly after
a federal bankruptcy judge approved the $365 million purchase from
strikebound Eastern, has pledged to spend as much as $2 million on
each plane for refurbishing, safety checks and repainting.
   ``I want the shuttle to be a diamond,'' he has said.
   The interiors of Trump's 21 Boeing 727s will be redone in
burgundy and saddle-brown tones with chrome and maple wood veneer
accents. Like the pearls, the pink marble vanities in the new
lavatories will be imitation.
   Although flight attendants often wear their own jewelry, it is
not considered a mandatory part of the uniform in the airline
business, said Barbara Steffen, a flight attendant for Trans World
Airlines.
   Since most shuttle passengers are more concerned about arriving
on time than fancy amenities, however, the flight attendants might
be casting pearls before swine.
</TEXT>
