<DOCNO> AP890818-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 0203EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SteelImports     08-18 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel Imports,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Imports Up Three Months Straight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel imports rose in June for the third
consecutive month but are running sharply below 1988 for the first
half of the year, according to the American Iron and Steel Institute.
   U.S. steel exports in June continued to run substantially ahead
of recent years. June exports totaled 403,000 tons, compared with
355,000 tons in May and 126,000 tons in June 1988.
   For the first half, exports totaled 2.2 million tons, compared
with 670,000 tons in the first six months of 1988, the AISI said
Thursday.
   First-half imports totaled 8.7 million tons, down 21 percent from
11.03 million tons in the 1988 period. The shipments during the
first half of this year represented 17.3 percent, down from 20.8
percent a year earlier.
   In June, imports fell by 5.2 percent to 1.55 million tons. The
United States imported 1.47 tons of steel in May, 1.34 million tons
in April and 1.22 million tons in March, the Washington, D.C.,
producers' group said based on its interpretation of Commerce
Department reports.
   The June imports represented 18.3 percent of the domestic market,
May 17.2 percent, April 16.5 percent and March 14.4 percent.
   President Bush on July 18 granted a 30-month extension to quotas
that were due to expire Sept. 30. The quotas are designed to limit
imports to 18.5 percent of the domestic market.
   The AISI said the rise in imports coincides with a weakening of
the world market for steel and confirms the industry's contention
that other countries increase their exports to the United States
when business elsewhere softens.
   The American Institute for Imported Steel, meanwhile, said that
U.S. producers imported 1.1 million tons of semi-finished steel in
the first half.
   ``Without imported steel slab, domestic steel producers would be
unable to meet demand. Imports of finished steel products also
benefit U.S. users and distributors by relieving shortages and
cutting costs,'' said John Griffin, president of the importers'
association and president of the Houston importer Maurice Pincoffs
Co.
</TEXT>
