<FIRST>r f PM-ColumbiaSavings     08-18 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Columbia Savings,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Resigns at Thrift Known for `Junk Bond' Investments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president and chief operating
officer of Columbia Savings &amp; Loan Association has announced his
resignation just 18 months after joining the thrift.
   Lawrence K. Fish, who said Thursday he was resigning effective
Sept. 30, comes as Columbia tries to devise a new financial strategy
after Congress barred savings and loans from holding junk bonds as
part of the multibillion thrift bailout.
   Fish was credited with helping Columbia decentralize operations,
with senior managers assuming more responsibility.
   But Columbia said it no longer needed both a chief executive and
chief operating officer after the restructuring, which was
undertaken following a period of rapid growth.
   Columbia last week reported that its second-quarter profits
plunged to $6.4 million from $27.1 million in the same period in
1988, reflecting a big drop from its securities-investment activity.
   Fish, 44, had a salary of $385,000 in 1988 and $1.5 million in
bonuses for a total of nearly $2 million. Columbia Chairman Thomas
Spiegel was paid $5.6 million in 1987 and $4.1 million last year.
   Siegel said a search was under way for someone to lead Columbia's
thrift operations permanently.
   The thrift, known for its large holdings of high-yield, high-risk
bonds, has about 30 percent of its $13.1 billion in total assets
invested in junk bonds.
   But the savings and loan bailout bill signed by President Bush
last week requires thrifts to liquidate their holding in such bonds
within five years.
   ``Columbia has got a real problem on its hands,'' said Bert Ely,
an Alexandria, Va.-based financial institutions consultant.
``They're going to have to do a massive downsizing as they get rid
of the junk bonds and try to decide just what is going to be their
business.''
   Columbia also is known for its close ties to California political
figures, and its relationship with former Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. financier Michael Milken, who was indicted earlier this year on
securities fraud charges.
   Milken raised much of Columbia's junk-bond financing and the
thrift has said it has provided documents to federal investigators
as part of a continuing probe into Milken's activities. Milken
headed Drexel's Beverly Hills-based high-yield bond department until
resigning following his March indictment.
</TEXT>
