<FIRST>r f PM-Amway-AnimalTests     08-18 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Amway-Animal Tests,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amway Corp. Nixes Animal Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADA, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amway Corp. has switched from animal tests to
test tubes in its studies on new products but says it may use
animals if ordered by the government.
   Company spokeswoman Kim Bruyn said Thursday the nation's
second-largest direct marketer ended its use of animals in testing
on June 5.
   Also, Amway decided against introducing a new pesticide because
the Environmental Protection Agency would have required animal
tests, she added.
   But Amway might perform animal testings if the government were to
order it on a product, Bruyn said. ``That hasn't come up yet, but it
could,'' she said.
   The company declined to contribute to the Cosmetics, Toiletry and
Fragrance Association's campaign to ban such testing in the
cosmetics industry, Bruyn said.
   Avon Products Inc., the nation's largest direct marketer,
announced on June 22 it had stopped animal testing. Revlon Inc. also
ended the tests this year, a decision praised by an animal rights
organization, People for Ethical Treatment of Animals.
</TEXT>
