<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 0220EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-EnquirerPlans     08-18 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Enquirer Plans,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Fantasma de Elvis'? National Enquirer Moving Ahead With Expansion
Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANTANA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Generoso Pope ruled the National
Enquirer, executives often proposed taking the often outrageous
tabloid beyond American supermarket checkout lines.
   The plans always were rejected by a man who often diverted his
energies to elaborate Christmas decorations and meticulous
landscaping around the publication's headquarters here.
   But the new owners of the National Enquirer and Weekly World News
tabloids say they see no obstacles for expansion plans that include
Spanish-language and international editions.
   Although no formal deals have been made for foreign editions,
talks are continuing with several British publishers, including
Robert Maxwell, who unsuccessfully tried to acquire the Enquirer's
publisher, GP Group Inc., following Pope's death in October.
   ``We are looking at a number of possibilities to publish outside
the United States and Mr. Maxwell is just one of those we have
spoken with,'' said Michael Boylan, president of Macfadden Holdings
Inc.
   Macfadden and Boston Ventures, a media-oriented investment firm,
paid $412.5 million for GP Group in April.
   The National Enquirer, which Pope purchased from Hearst Corp. in
1952 for $75,000, is the nation's leading tabloid with weekly
circulation of about 4.3 million. The more sensational Weekly World
News sells about 1.3 million.
   Murdoch Magazines' runner-up Star sells about 3.6 million copies
weekly, and Globe Communications Corp. reports a total weekly
circulation of about 3.2 million from its Sun, Globe and National
Examiner papers.
   Macfadden owns several romance and teen monthly publications, the
largest of which is True Story, with circulation of 1.3 million.
Boston Ventures last year acquired Motown Records in a venture with
MCA Inc.
   Macfadden is in early stages of planning a Spanish-language
edition targeted for the large Hispanic populations in such cities
as New York, Miami, Los Angeles and San Antonio, Texas, said Boylan.
   ``We want it to be basically the same paper, but we'll tailor it
to include people and celebrities the Hispanic community knows and
follows,'' said Boylan, who would not predict a date for the new
edition.
   Boylan said the United Kingdom likely would be the beachhead for
the overseas expansion, which could begin by early next year. He
said other countries, such as Australia, also were being studied.
   He described Macfadden's proposed foreign tabloids as a
combination of the stories from the U.S. editions and other articles
of local or international interest.
   While New York-based Macfadden hasn't tampered with Pope's
editorial formula _ although some other eccentricities have been
dropped such as a $1 million Christmas tree and keeping the company
grass four inches high _ analysts have predicted that cost-cutting
measures will be needed to cover the high acquisition price.
   In June, Macfadden announced the layoffs of 20 workers from
editorial, advertising and other departments. An additional 37 jobs
were trimmed last month when the News printing operation was
transferred from Pompano Beach to Atlanta.
   The price of the Enqurier was raised from 75 cents to 85 cents
following the purchase and the Weekly World News rose a nickle to 70
cents.
   Last year, the Enquirer and News reportedly earned $15 million on
revenue of about $150 million.
   Boylan also said Macfadden remained interested in launching a
soap opera publication but had not yet decided on a format or when
such a publication could appear.
   Boylan said distribution of the U.S. projects could be handled by
the company's DSI unit, which has nearly 600 full- and part-time
workers managing rack space at about 19,000 supermarkets and
retailers.
</TEXT>
