<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-18 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Steady</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was down in quiet trading in Europe
today, and spot gold was steady.
   The dollar slipped half a pfennig against the West German mark in
the first half-hour of trading but did not fall below 1.9600 marks.
   One dealer at a large West German bank said he expected a narrow
1.9600-1.9650-mark trading range until the release of U.S. consumer
price data for July.
   One dealer at a public-sector bank in Frankfurt said he expected
the dollar to decline in the coming week.
   Rates for the dollar this morning, compared with Thursday's
closing rates, included: 1.9610 West German marks, down from 1.9690;
1.6905 Swiss francs, down from 1.6980; 6.6215 French francs, down
from 6.6325; 2.2110 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2190; 1,408.50
Italian lire, down from 1,412.00; 1.1795 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1815.
   In London, one British pound fetched $1.5639, more expensive for
buyers than Thursday's $1.5590.
   In Tokyo, the dollar firmed to 143.58 yen, up 1.20 yen from the
close on Thursday. In London this morning, the dollar traded at
143.16 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $366.25 a troy ounce,
down from $366.35 Thursday. At midmorning the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $366.30 an ounce.
   Gold traded in Zurich at $366.50, compared to $365.25 per troy
ounce late Thursday.
   In Hong Kong, gold closed at $367.01 per troy ounce, up from
Thursday's closing price of $366.45 per troy ounce.
   Silver bullion traded in London at $5.25 a troy ounce, down from
$5.20.
</TEXT>
