<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 0735EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     08-18 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Gains Against Yen, Nikkei Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Improved U.S. trade figures helped push the dollar
higher against the yen today, while stock prices declined, traders
said.
   The dollar opened at 143.50 yen, up 1.18 yen from Thursday's
close. It finished trading at 143.52 yen after ranging between
143.05 and 143.58 yen.
   Traders said the dollar's higher opening was due to
better-than-expected U.S. trade figures released Thursday, which
triggered dollar buying in London and New York.
   The U.S. trade deficit in June fell to $8.2 billion, down 18.9
percent from the previous month's $10.1 billion.
   But the dollar gradually moved downward from the opening because
``market players were selling the dollar for profit taking,'' said a
trader with the Bank of Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   By the end of the day, however, the dollar had returned to its
opening level.
   ``There was no real reason to sell (dollars),'' said Sumio
Fukushima of Sumitomo Bank.
   He said the dollar appeared to be in a ``box,'' with dealers
unwilling to let it escape from a narrow range.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
shed 26.97 points, or 0.08 percent, closing at 35,063.14. It had
gained a marginal 5.96 points Thursday.
   Trading focused on high-priced issues, such as Sony, TDK and
Japan Victor Corp., said Haruhito Ichimura, an analyst for Nippon
Kangyo Kakumaru Securities.
   Electricals and precision instrument issues attracted strong
buyer interest, he said.
   ``The decline of the yen (on the exchange market) has been a plus
for export issues,'' Ichimura said.
   Trading was thin, with only 450 million shares changing hands on
the first section, unchanged from Thursday.
   Ichimura said the market was likely to return to its usual volume
on Monday when market participants who have been on vacation return
to work.
 
</TEXT>
