<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 0947EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-OldsmobileTrucks     08-18 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oldsmobile Trucks,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Truck Lines On Tap for '90 at Oldsmobile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new minivan and a sport-utility vehicle will
begin appearing next year in what some may think are unlikely places
_ Oldsmobile dealerships.
   It will be the first time that Oldsmobile dealers have marketed
trucks in the history of the General Motors Corp. division.
Oldsmobile cars traditionally have been sold to middle-age,
well-established consumers. Minivans and sport vehicles are aimed at
a younger market.
   Oldsmobile officials have been trying to change the division's
long-standing image, mainly through its Cutlass line of cars and an
advertising campaign featuring the slogan ``This is not your
father's Oldsmobile.''
   A four-door, sport-utility vehicle will be made at GM's Moraine,
Ohio, plant, GM Truck &amp; Bus Group spokeswoman Mary Ann Tyler said
Thursday.
   ``Oldsmobile will sell a version of the new vehicle that is going
to be introduced as a 1990 model next summer,'' she said, adding she
didn't know what the vehicle would be named.
   The Moraine plant now makes Chevrolet S-10 and GMC S-15 pickup
trucks.
   Previously, GM announced that Oldsmobile dealers would sell
versions of its new minivan, called the Silhouette, next year. That
vehicle, being made now in North Tarrytown, N.Y., along with
Chevrolet Lumina and Pontiac Trans Sport minivans, will go on sale
later this year.
   Clifford Vaughan, vice president and group executive for the
Truck &amp; Bus Group, said in a recent interview with the Oakland Press
of Pontiac, Mich., Oldsmobile will get a top-of-the-line version of
the four-door sport-utility vehicle.
   The company has said it plans to introduce a four-door model of
the Chevrolet Blazer next year.
   Analyst Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities Co. International
Inc. in New York City said she was concerned with ``badge
engineering,'' or making minor, if any, changes in a car and putting
a different nameplate on it.
   ``They are doing the same thing with the minivan,'' she said.
``It's going right back to what they used to do _ making everything
look alike.''
   However, Heaney said the decision to put a sport-utility vehicle
in Oldsmobile dealerships may be a good one.
   ``It moves the Olds image a little bit upscale and the Jeep
products are expensive,'' she said. ``Those are upscale buyers,
maybe that's GM's strategy.''
</TEXT>
