<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1020EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     08-18 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0367</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mostly lower in early
trading, pressured by new economic data that suggested inflation
might not be easing.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 1.33 points to
2,678.30 at 10 a.m. EDT, 30 minutes after the opening bell.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 6 to 5 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 486 issues down, 396 up and 558 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 19.60 million shares.
   The Labor Department announced today that consumer inflation rose
a modest 0.2 percent in July, held down by the sharpest drop in
gasoline prices in nearly three years.
   The number was in line with expectations, analysts said. But many
investors were focusing on the 0.4 percent rise in the index
excluding food and energy, the most volatile components.
   ``The CPI report, while it looks good on the headline, when you
read further in there is concern that we have seen the lows in
inflation and will be moving higher in the months ahead,'' said
James Solloway, economist with Argus Research Corp.
   Solloway said the market's weakness reflected some disappointment
that the Federal Reserve is not going to ease credit conditions in
the near future.
   Prices for the first seven months of 1989 rose at a 5.5 percent
annual rate, more than a full percentage point higher than the 4.4
percent increases in both 1988 and 1987, the government said.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was up
0.04 to 191.99.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was off
0.15 to 378.19.
   On Thursday, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 13.66
points to finish at 2,679.63, after trading down about 25 points
during the session.
   Declining issues outnumbered gainers by a margin of about 8 to 5
in nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
887 issues down, 561 up and 540 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 157.56 million
shares, up from 150.06 million in Wednesday's session.
</TEXT>
