<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1050EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-FarmComputers Adv21 1stLd-Writethru 08-18 0884</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Farm Computers, Adv 21, 1st Ld-Writethru,0913</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barnyard Software: Farmers Exploit Computers To Reap Profits</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lead</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNION GROVE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Badtke's new farm implement won't
milk Elsie or plow the back 40, but it can identify his most
productive cows and calculate the best time to water the crops.
   Badtke is one of a growing number of farmers nationwide who have
added a personal computer to their collection of tools to make a
living off the land.
   Farmers are using computers to help plan their finances, manage
their herds and tell them when to irrigate. Despite the time it
takes to learn how to use a computer, they say the technology can
make their operations more efficient and let them reap more profits
in the uncertain world of modern-day agriculture.
   Badtke said he plans to use his computer to rank his cows, so he
knows which are the most efficient.
   ``By culling cows at the right time we could be saving on feed,''
he said, noting that he spends about $60,000 a year on cattle feed.
``That's what you're after, to gain more of an edge.''
   ``Farming is definitely a business. It was a business 10 years
ago, but the margins have been narrowed and the costs of being wrong
are so high that you can't afford to be wrong too often,'' said
Arlin Brannstrom, assistant director of the North Central Computer
Institute in Madison, a resource for agricultural software.
   ``I'm sure a lot of farms were lost because they didn't have
enough information,'' he said.
   The farm computer business started to sprout around the beginning
of the decade, at the same time the agricultural economy was sliding
into a recession.
   ``In the 70s, there was tremendous expansion in agriculture. It
gave a lot of prosperity to a lot of people,'' said Gary Randolph,
president of Harvest Computer Systems, a farm software company in
Alexandria, Ind. ``In the 80s, things tightened up.''
   ``It just happened that this technology came around in the 80s,''
he said. ``It was fortuitous _ the economy created a need and the
technology filled that need.''
   Estimates vary on the number of farmers using computers. John
Brunz, executive director of the Association of Agricultural
Computing Companies, said numbers range from 8 percent to 20 percent.
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture says 15 percent of farm
operators in 1988 with gross sales of $250,000 or more were using
computers for record keeping. The department says farmers in that
category accounted for more than half of all farm sales.
   The North Central Computer Institute lists about 1,900 titles of
different agricultural software, some developed by private companies
and others by universities.
   ``There's been a very rapid growth,'' Brannstrom said.
``Obviously 10 years ago there was almost nothing on the shelf.''
   The computer programs range from basic accounting to helping
farmers tend their crops.
   For example, researchers at the University of Wisconsin this year
introduced a computer program that tells potato farmers the best
times to apply pesticides and irrigate.
   George Rice, who supervised the project, said the program
combines principles of horticulture, entomology, plant pathology and
agronomy, but all a farmer needs to know is simple data, such as
temperatures and humidity.
   Without such assistance, Rice said, a farmer would be ``flying in
the dark.''
   ``He might use irrigation when the soil already has water,'' he
said. ``He might spray when he doesn't have to apply as much
pesticide.''
   The program costs about $245, but as Rice said, ``it could pay
for itself with one application of pesticide, or one
misapplication.''
   The computer program this year saved about $250,000 for the R.D.
Offutt Co., of Fargo, N.D., which owns several potato farms, said
Dale Steevens, an agronomist for the company.
   Steevens said information from the program allowed operators to
wait longer before spraying fungicides.
   ``Before, it was just a best guess, based on previous
experience,'' he said.
   Farmers also use home computers to tap databases that provide
up-to-the-minute information on the weather, commodity markets and
world events that can shape the agriculture economy.
   A company that sells such a service is AgriData Resources Inc.,
in Milwaukee, which started in 1981.
   Ed Markham, president of the company, said until recently,
farmers focused on ways to expand production, ``but there's been
very little emphasis on marketing the product and running the farm
as a business.''
   One of AgriData's customers is Robert Vogts, a farmer in
Arlington, Wis., who grows corn and peas.
   Vogts said while the information is useful in planning, ``you've
still got to make the decision when to buy and sell.''
   On one occasion, Vogts said, he was waiting for corn prices to
reach a recommended target before selling. The price came close to
the target, but then dropped quickly, and Vogts said in retrospect,
he should not have followed the recommendations so strictly.
   But Vogts and others say computer equipment is well worth the
investment, especially in relation to other farm machinery that can
cost more than $100,000.
   ``A computer investment doesn't compare,'' said Norlin Hein, a
professor of agricultural economics at the University of Missouri.
``It's about the same price as a used pickup truck, and not a very
good used pickup.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday, Aug. 21.</NOTE>
