<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   08-18 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Gain On Export News, Crop Estimate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
higher in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade,
bolstered by new export business and a private firm's surprisingly
low crop estimates.
   The early gains were limited, however, by forecasts for rain in
the Midwest this weekend and next week.
   ``All the news, with the exception of weather, is bullish,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Chicago.
   Among the positive fundamentals were new crop estimates from
Memphis-based Sparks Commodities Inc., a private analytical firm,
that were lower than the government projections issued last week.
   Sparks pegged the U.S soybean crop at 1.84 billion bushels,
compared to the Agriculture Department's estimate of 1.91 billion,
and Sparks pegged the corn crop at 7.05 billion bushels compared to
the USDA's projected 7.35 billion.
   Buying of corn and wheat futures was also stimulated by news that
Mexico had purchased more than 400,000 metric tons of U.S. corn and
that China bought 150,000 metric tons of corn and 100,000 metric
tons of wheat.
   The sales of U.S. grain to China were the first in two years and
could portend more business down the road.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.97{ a bushel; corn was 1
cent to 2} cents higher with September at $2.38 a bushel; oats were
1{ cents to 1} cents higher with September at $1.38} a bushel;
soybeans were 3{ cents to 9 cents higher with August at $6.17 a
bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mixed in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Today is the last
trading day for the August live cattle and hog contracts.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .05 cent higher with August at
73.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .08 cent lower to .05 cent
higher with August at 84.57 cents a pound; live hogs were .12 cent
lower to .65 cent higher with August at 48.50 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .37 cent lower to .40 cent higher with August at
27 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Thursday.
</TEXT>
