<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern-Bakes 1stLd-Writethru   08-18 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Bakes, 1st Ld-Writethru,0752</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says Eastern Will Be Bigger Than Planned</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with new grafs 1-6 to UPDATE with American Airlines saying
it's frustrated on South American routes; picks up 2nd graf pvs bg'ng,
``We will ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines claims it's doing so well
rebuilding from a crippling strike that it will be bigger than
expected, and the carrier may decide not to sell its prized South
American routes.
   American Airlines, the chief bidder for Eastern's usually
profitable Latin routes, expressed frustration at the lack of
progress in negotiations on the sale, The Miami Herald reported in
today's editions.
   ``We're discouraged (because) the talks are so intermittent that
it's hard to define the status,'' said American spokesman Ed
Stewart. ``The frustration factor is very real _ it's really not
clear that they want to sell.''
   Eastern President Phil Bakes told The Associated Press the
carrier will be selling fewer assets than anticipated when it first
began trying to come back from the strike and Chapter 11 bankruptcy
reorganization.
   Bakes wouldn't go into details on the South American route
negotiations and said he didn't ``want to set odds'' on whether they
would be sold.
   ``We have made no final decision to sell South America. We have
been in negotiations ... We don't have an agreement and our board
has not made a decision to sell South America,'' Bakes said.
   ``We will have more employees, it will service more cities and
we'll have more airplanes,'' Bakes said in an interview.
   A pilots union spokesman Thursday expressed doubt about Bakes'
projections and said Eastern is raising safety concerns by rushing
its rebuilding efforts.
   But Bakes said management is pleased about Eastern's progress
since it announced plans to emerge at two-thirds its pre-strike size
from Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization. The walkout by the
airline's three unions began March 4.
   ``What we announced last April was the impossible, and there were
a lot of skeptics, to say the least,'' Bakes said in the interview
Wednesday. ``The fact is, we're exceeding targets (and) we will
accelerate the schedule a little bit.''
   Bakes detailed the revised, increased plans:
   _Instead of 17,000 employees planned, there will be
``18,000-plus, maybe more.''
   _Instead of 1,700 pilots planned, there will be more ``in the
next year or two, maybe in the next few months in small groups.''
   _Instead of 157 aircraft, Eastern next year will fly 165 to 180
planes and also has the first nine of 40 new Boeing aircraft on
order available for 1992.
   _Instead of 800 daily flights serving 77 cities, Eastern will
probably add cities and flights, but no figures have been decided
upon.
   _Instead of $1.8 billion in assets sales, the figure may be as
low as $1.5 billion. Fewer assets may be sold because transactions
such as aircraft sales, Philadelphia gates and the Northeast shuttle
sale have earned more money than expected and Eastern is winning
back customers at faster rates than expected.
   Ron Cole, a spokesman for Eastern's pilots union, noted reports
that Eastern is falling hundreds of millions of dollars behind on
revenue.
   ``I don't see how he can sit there with a straight face and say
they're doing better than anticipated,'' he said.
   The Air Line Pilots Association, which represents pilots at
nearly every major carrier, is considering a nationwide suspension
of service to show support for Eastern's strikers. The union's
executive council is in a two-day meeting.
   Cole claimed Eastern flights experienced at least two unsafe
landings in recent days because of inexperienced pilots.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said the company had anticipated
financial losses throughout this year and that losses have been less
than expected. Matell said the unions continue to try to use safety
allegations as a weapon against the company.
   Union leaders said Eastern also is having trouble keeping up with
maintenance of its aircraft because it lacks mechanics and spare
parts.
   Bakes said 750 to 800 union pilots have crossed picket lines, but
later clarified that about 100 of those are pilots who signed
preferential recall lists after Eastern stopped taking union pilots
back. He said it has graduated 300 new pilots and has 700 in
training.
   ALPA contends any union pilot must get job preference over a
pilot still in training, but Bakes said Eastern is committed to
protecting the pilots in training.
</TEXT>
