<DOCNO> AP890818-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1326EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-TickerTalk Adv21   08-18 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 21,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday August 21</HEAD>
<HEAD>Swinging Moods On Wall Street</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It doesn't take much to shatter deeply held
convictions on Wall Street.
   Just when investors become convinced of one scenario, the
economic winds shift, so-called in-depth analyses are blown away and
it's time to change strategies.
   Investors recently got comfortable with the notion that the
economy was sliding into a possibly severe recession and adjusted
their portfolios accordingly, accumulating so-called `defensive'
issues such as food, tobacco and soaps.
   The new thought is that the economy is stronger than expected, as
suggested by the latest government statistics on everything from
retail sales and homebuilding to trade and industrial production.
   Stock strategists are now talking of a revival in cyclical
stocks, those that rise and fall with changes in the economy. Autos,
chemicals, steel, metals and paper, which fit into this category,
had been depressed lately compared to the rest of the market.
   Some strategists say the market began to show it was shifting
gears about two weeks ago with the emergence of Phelps Dodge Corp.,
the largest domestic producer of copper at about the time the July
employment report was released. Other cyclicals have since followed.
   ``The psychology is that the turndown is getting near the
bottom,'' said John Burnett, senior vice president for Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette. ``If people can justify going out and buying GM
then they think things are OK.''
   The July employment report showed joblessness down a notch to 5.2
percent and job growth stronger than expected. June job growth also
was revised upward. That was followed by unexpectedly strong July
retail sales last week. But the real kicker in the retail sales
report were the revisions to May and June figures, which suggested
that three months back consumers were actually buying more than many
investors had realized.
   That made an imminent consumer-led recession almost impossible,
stock strategists concluded. Overnight, those who days earlier
warned of recession this year softened their predictions.
   Subsequent reports on homebuilding, industrial production and
trade led economists to conclude that the economy is in a modest
expansion.
   ``A market that responds to ancient history as this market has
done is lacking in long-term conviction,'' said Alfred E. Goldman,
vice president at going.''
   Richard McCabe, manager of market analysis at Merrill Lynch &amp;
Co., says people have lost sight of what the numbers mean.
   ``I wonder why people seem to hang their hats on one number when
experience shows that's going to change,'' he said.
   The numbers rekindled fears in some sectors of a renewed
inflationary surge. Investors have scurried to shift their
portfolios around and change investment strategies.
   Economist Edward Yardeni of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.,
says the excessive mood swings and volatility are the result of
shortsightedness brought on by the October 1987 stock market crash.
   ``The crash unnerved a lot of investors,'' Yardeni said. ``They
thought recession and depression but the economy fooled them and
continued to grow at a very solid pace. So investors lost confidence
and the ability to get a handle on the economy.''
   The mood swings have been more volatile than the underlying
economy, Yardeni is quick to add.
   Yardeni says despite the market swings he has remained bullish
throughout the year in recommending ``rustbowl'' stocks such as
chemicals, aluminum and steel.
   But there is plenty of uncertainty left and the market isn't
totally convinced yet that defensive stocks are passe. For the time
being, many analysts believe, the ``hold some, fold some'' strategy
is the safest.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday, Aug. 21.</NOTE>
</DOC>
