<FIRST>r f AM-Warner-Chris-Craft     08-18 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warner-Chris-Craft,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warner, Chris-Craft Take Step Toward Settling Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Communications Inc. and Chris-Craft
Industries Inc. took a big step Friday toward disentangling their
corporate ties, announcing settlement of several legal disputes that
have blocked the separation.
   The relationship was forged several years ago when Warner, the
entertainment giant, recruited Chris-Craft to help it fend off
unwanted takeover overtures.
   Chris-Craft became Warner's largest shareholder, controlling an
18 percent interest in Warner through its majority-owned subsidiary,
BHC Communications Inc., while Warner bought a 42.5 percent stake in
BHC.
   But Warner indicated this spring it wanted to sever those ties
after it agreed to merge with, and later to be acquired by, media
giant Time Inc.
   Warner dropped its right to match any offer Chris-Craft may get
for its stake in Warner and gave Chris-Craft a choice of options on
what it wanted done with Warner's stake in BHC.
   They have been in court in Delaware trying to resolve several
issues resulting from the Warner deal with Time and Friday's
announcement described the settlement of some of those legal
disputes.
   The Time offer for Warner called for a payment of $70 a share in
cash for half of Warner's outstanding stock followed by an exchange
of each remaining Warner share for a package of a still undetermined
mix of cash and securities valued at $70.
   Under Friday's settlement, it was agreed that Warner's interest
in BHC would be distributed to Warner stockholders as part of the
package of cash and securities comprising the second part of Time's
tender offer for Warner.
   In addition, Warner agreed to repurchase 1.3 million of BHC's 6.5
million shares of Warner Series B convertible preferred stock for
$143.7 million.
   That purchase will leave Chris-Craft with about 6 percent of
Warner's common and preferred stock, pending completion of the
second half of the tender offer.
   The settlement also provided that the Warner stake in BHC that is
being spun off to Warner shareholders will comprise 40 percent of
the equity and 6.25 percent of the voting power in new BHC.
Chris-Craft controls the rest.
   The settlement leaves unresolved Chris-Craft's assertion that it
has the right to judge the fairness of the second phase of the
tender offer for Warner because it is the lone holder of Warner
Series B convertible preferred stock.
   Warner contends no such right exists and the dispute remains at
issue in Delaware Chancery Court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
