<HEAD>London Shares End at 1989 Closing High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices continued their upward march Friday,
as bullish corporate news, encouraging economic data and scattered
speculative buying pushed the main index to a new 1989 high.
   The market opened stronger and then shot higher on Thursday's
release of a U.S. government report that said Wellcome PLC's AIDS
drug, AZT, is safer and much more effective against the disease than
earlier studies have shown.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 15.1
points, or 0.6 percent, higher at 2,375.1, a new 1989 closing high.
   Wellcome's stock surged $2.56 a share to $10.03.
   The Financial Times 30-share index ended up 4.0 points at
1,979.0. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 8.01 points to
close at 1,334.40.
   Volume came to 426.3 million shares Friday, down from 544.3
million Thursday.
