<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-18 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat, Corn Futures Dip; Beans Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat and corn futures prices dipped Friday on
confirmation of large foreign purchases of those grains while
soybean futures closed higher following a private forecast for a
surprisingly small crop.
   The decline in the wheat and corn markets ``was a perfect example
of buy the rumor, sell the fact,'' said William Biedermann, director
of research for Allendale Inc., a futures brokerage in Crystal Lake,
Ill.
   The Agriculture Department said Mexico purchased more than
400,000 metric tons of U.S. corn Thursday and China bought 150,000
metric tons of corn and 100,000 metric tons of wheat, the first U.S.
grain purchases by China in two years.
   Biedermann said the foreign sales had been expected since Aug. 9,
when several grain exporters bought large quantities of futures
contracts, apparently to hedge purchases on the cash market of grain
they planned to sell overseas.
   Soybean prices were buoyed by active cash markets for soybean
meal and oil, and by crop estimates from Memphis, Tenn.-based Sparks
Commodities Inc., a private analytical firm, that were lower than
the government projections issued last week.
   Sparks pegged the U.S soybean crop at 1.84 billion bushels
compared to the USDA's estimate of 1.91 billion, and Sparks pegged
the corn crop at 7.05 billion bushels compared to the USDA's
projected 7.35 billion.
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents to 5 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.92\ a bushel; corn was 1{
cents lower to 1\ cents higher with September at $2.35\ a bushel;
oats were unchanged to 1 cent higher with September at $1.38 a
bushel; soybeans were 5 cents lower to 8 cents higher with August at
$6.16 a bushel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
