<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0220</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A late rally helped push the stock market higher
just before the close today after a fairly quiet, mixed day of
trading.
   The market opened weak in response to a drop in the bond market
after a Labor Department report that showed consumer inflation rose
0.2 percent in July.
   Although the number was in line with expectations, investors
focused on the 0.4 percent rise in the Consumer Price Index
excluding food and energy, the most volatile components, analysts
said.
   The data was interpreted as another indication that the Federal
Reserve was unlikely to lower interest rates.
   The bond market later changed direction, pulling stocks along
with it.
   ``The bond market tells the whole story,'' said Charles Jensen,
chief technical analyst with MKI Securities Corp. ``Stocks followed
along with the reaction of the bond market.''
   Although some blue-chip issues showed strong gains, the market
remained generally trendless with the broader market lagging behind.
   Airline stocks helped push the Dow Jones transportation average
higher. UAL Corp., parent of United Airlines, rose amid news that it
had two new potential bidders. McGraw Hill stock also gained
strongly as speculation resurfaced that Paramount Communications
Inc. was interested in buying the company.
</TEXT>
