<FIRST>u f AM-UAL Bjt   08-18 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAL, Bjt,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL Suitors Reportedly Include Bass, British Airways-Morgan Stanley
Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp.'s stock price continued gaining altitude
Friday as speculators bet that suitors which reportedly now include
Texas investor Robert Bass and a team of British Airways PLC and
Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. would engage in a bidding war.
   UAL rose $4.62{ a share at $271 late Friday on the New York Stock
Exchange. That followed a gain of $14.62{ on Thursday and more than
$90 a share overall since a buyout proposal by California investor
Marvin Davis was disclosed some two weeks ago.
   ``My guess is that the interest ranges from very serious on the
part of some firms to others who are just exploring the feasibility
of getting involved,'' said Robert Decker, airline analyst for Duff
&amp; Phelps.
   ``Other than Davis' bid, there isn't enough information out there
to make an educated guess. But it's my sense that we're approaching
the upper limits of what anybody is going to pay for the company,''
he said.
   Davis on Wednesday sweetened his proposal to $6.19 billion, or
$275 a share, from the initial $5.4 billion, or $240 a share and has
indicated he might be willing to go even higher after reviewing
internal company data.
   UAL's directors met Thursday and later stated it was premature to
decide whether the company would be sold.
   UAL confirmed it had been contacted by other potential bidders
and had held discussions with an employee group, but declined to
identify any of the parties.
   In addition to Bass and British Airways-Morgan Stanley, Pan Am
Corp. has stated it was interested in a possible merger with UAL,
the parent of United Airlines.
   Also said to be eyeing UAL are the United unit of the Air Line
Pilots Association, which represents United's 7,125 pilots and
offered unsuccessfully to buy the company in 1987; and Chairman
Stephen Wolf, who reportedl is exploring a bid by current UAL
management, possibly in conjunction with the pilots.
   All of the groups declined to comment Friday, citing policies
regarding speculative reports.
   United spokeswoman Sara Dornacker said the company would not
expand on its comments made after the board meeting Thursday,
although she said the directors' next regularly scheduled meeting
was Sept. 27.
   In a statement issued early Friday, Davis said he and his
associates were awaiting ``with interest the board's conclusions and
continue to look forward to working with UAL's board, management and
labor groups to develop a transaction that works to the benefit of
all parties concerned.''
   ``My guess is that they're buying time to continue with their own
analysis of what UAL is worth,'' said Decker. ``Once they get that
completed, they'll be in better position to decide who they talk
with and about how much.''
   Decker also said the pilots' union likely was being courted _ or
would be _ by any group with serious designs on acquiring UAL.
   ``It's improbable any deal could be done without some form of
cooperation from the pilots, and probably the machinists as well,''
he said. ``It may not come down to a share of ownership _ though
that's possible _ but any acquirer would have a hard time getting
financing without some promise of cooperation.
   ``That gives lenders comfort that they won't be facing a
strike,'' he said.
</TEXT>
