<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern     08-18 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two `Hard Landings' at Eastern Due to New Pilots, ALPA Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-UAL, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unsafe landings occurred on two Eastern Airlines
flights recently because of inexperienced pilots hired to replace
strikers, the Air Line Pilots Association contended Friday. But both
Eastern and the federal agency responsible for air safety disputed
the claims.
   The union representing pilots at most major U.S. airlines said
the incidents involved ``hard landings'' at airports in Atlanta and
Chicago. The airplanes were damaged in both cases but there were no
injuries, the pilots union said.
   A spokesman for the Federal Aviation Administration said the
Chicago incident, in which a tail cone fell off, didn't involve a
hard landing but was due to a mechanical malfunction.
   In the Atlanta case, Eastern performed the required inspection
after the hard landing, replaced the affected parts and put the
plane back into service, said the spokesman, Fred Farrar.
   ``These are not inexperienced pilots,'' Farrar said from
Washington.
   He said the FAA's information on the incidents was based on
reports made by Eastern.
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak in Miami confirmed that the
incidents occurred, but said they were not caused by the pilots
being unseasoned. The Chicago incident resulted from a mechanical
problem and was not a hard landing, while the hard landing in
Atlanta apparently was due to weather conditions or the jet being
overweight, she said.
   ``Inexperienced pilots were not a factor,'' Ms. Ceremsak said.
``This is another example of the pilots attempting to string
unrelated incidents together to further their cause.''
   The pilots association made the charges in a statement released
from Washington, where its executive council is considering calling
for a nationwide suspension of service on virtually all domestic
carriers to show support for Eastern's strikers.
   The pilots union struck Eastern on March 4 in sympathy with a
walkout by the Machinists union. But veteran pilots by the dozens
crossed picket lines last week and Eastern last Friday said it had
stopped hiring new pilots or taking strikers back.
   Of the four pilots involved in the two incidents, three were
hired by Eastern since the strike and one had little experience in
the type of aircraft he was flying at the time, the pilots union
said.
   ``While `hard landings' are not unheard of in everyday airline
operations, it is unusual to find two of them involving new-hire
pilots in such a short period of time at the same airline,'' the
statement read. ``These incidents illustrate the ongoing problems
that Eastern has had because of its inexperienced pilot group.''
   The pilots union said its information was obtained from
observation posts and by monitoring radio frequencies at major
airports where Eastern operates.
   In the first incident, on July 29 in Chicago, a McDonnell-Douglas
DC-9 aircraft lost its tail cone because of the impact of a hard
landing, according to the pilots union. The inflatable evacuation
slide also was jarred loose and trailed the plane on the ground as
it taxied to the gate, it said.
   But Farrar and Ms. Ceremsak said the tail cone came off because a
lever attached to it released accidentally. ``There is no evidence
of a hard landing,'' Farrar said, referring to the DC-9 episode.
   The first officer, who was flying the approach, was a new hire,
the pilots union said. It said the captain was an Eastern veteran
but he had spent most of his time at the carrier as an instructor or
in the position of second officer, a non-flying post.
   In the Atlanta incident on Aug. 12, a Lockheed L-1011 jumbo jet
bounced on the runway during a landing attempt, the pilots union
said. The pilots aborted the landing, performed a ``go around'' for
another approach and successfully completed the second attempt, the
union said.
   The captain and the first officer were both new hires, the
statement said.
   The pilots union said the damaged aircraft was still in a hangar.
   Farrar and Ms. Ceremsak disputed that claim, saying the L-1011
sustained no damage and was put back in service after some of the
seals on its landing gear were replaced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
