<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-18 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Worldwide</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar slipped in worldwide trading Friday as
dealers cashed in on the currency's dramatic run-up in the previous
session.
   Gold prices were mixed. On the Commodity Exchange in New York,
gold bullion for current delivery lost 20 cents to finish at $368.10
a troy ounce. Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid
later at $366 an ounce, down 20 cents from Thursday.
   Buying interest in the dollar abated following the climb
triggered by Thursday's release of a better-than-expected U.S. trade
report for July, which boosted the U.S. currency to levels not seen
since its most recent rally in June.
   ``The dollar is right back to where we were before the trade
number came out,'' said Michael McDonald, a trader with Harris Trust
&amp; Savings Bank in Chicago.
   A Labor Department report released Friday showed that drops in
energy and clothing prices held the rise in July consumer prices to
just 0.2 percent, a further indication that inflation is restrained.
   But traders characterized the report as a non-event since it was
largely within expectations. ``Most people are anticipating the
(Federal Reserve) will not be easing interest rates in the next week
or two,'' McDonald said.
   With a battery of Japanese government bonds due to mature next
week, traders were speculating whether any of that money would flow
to U.S. securities. But the threat of central bank intervention
overseas during the weekend made them reluctant to bid the dollar
higher.
   The dollar held to a narrow range, and trading was active, said
David Ogg, a vice president at Credit Suisse.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 143.52 Japanese yen, up
from 142.32. Later in London, the dollar traded lower at 142.75 yen.
In New York, the dollar closed at 142.60 yen, down from 143.53 yen
on Thursday.
   In London, one British pound cost at cost $1.5655 late Friday,
more expensive for buyers than Thursday's late $1.5590. In New York,
one pound cost $1.5659, more expensive than $1.5605 on Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Thursday
included: 1.9562 West German marks, down from 1.9637; 1.6855 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6925; 6.5955 French francs, down from 6.6280;
1,403.00 Italian lire, down from 1,412.25, and 1.1178 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1819.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday
included: 1.9555 West German marks, down from 1.9690; 1.6860 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6980; 6.5945 French francs, down from 6.6325;
2.2080 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2190; 1,405.75 Italian lire, down
from 1,412.00, and 1.1787 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1815.
   Gold prices were higher overseas. In London, gold closed at
$366.65 bid a troy ounce, up from $366.35. The Zurich closing price
was a bid $366.75, up from $365.25. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold
closed at $366.50 bid, up from $366.45.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery slipped to $5.238 a troy ounce from $5.246 on
Thursday. But in London the metal traded at a late bid price of
$5.25 a troy ounce, up from $5.20.
</TEXT>
