<FIRST>r f AM-StockTrades     08-18 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stock Trades,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hatch Alleges Fraud In Stock Trades By Two North Dakota Men</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two North Dakota men have made fraudulent stock
transactions which resulted in losses of nearly $200,000 to Twin
Cities area brokers, Minnesota Commerce Commissioner Michael Hatch
alleged Friday.
   Hatch alleged in cease-and-desist orders that Ryan Westgard and
Darrell Adams, both of Grand Forks, N.D., since May have made
numerous stock and stock option purchases on credit and then
defaulted.
   Westgard and Adams appeared to be acting with other parties,
Hatch alleged, and he said total losses could exceed $400,000.
   Adams did not immediately return a reporter's telephone call for
comment, and there was no response to calls made to Westgard's
residence Friday afternoon.
   Hatch's orders list Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., John G. Kinnard
&amp; Co. Inc., Craig-Hallum Inc., Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. and
L'Argent Securities Inc. as brokers who have lost money because of
the men's trades.
   So far, he said, it appears that all of the transactions involved
the purchase of USX Corp. common stock, USX Corp. common stock
options or Angeion common stock.
   The orders prohibit Westgard and Adams from engaging in such
transactions or any other activities that violate Minnesota or
federal securities statutes.
   Hatch said his investigation is continuing and further orders may
be issued. The Securities and Exchange Commission also has been
contacted, he said.
</TEXT>
