<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1747EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     08-18 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Narrowly Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices finished mixed Friday as buying by
bargain-hunters offset the early prices declines that followed the
latest consumer inflation report.
   Prices of long-term Treasury and corporate bonds edged up, but
prices of shorter-term Treasury issues and tax-exempt bonds slipped.
   The price of the Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond rose 1-16
point, or less than $1 for every $1,000 in face value, as its yield
dipped to 8.15 percent from 8.16 percent late Thursday.
   Prices fell after the Labor Department reported that its Consumer
Price Index rose 0.2 percent in July. While that increase was widely
expected, some traders were disappointed by a 0.4 percent rise in
prices other than for food and energy. That increase was up from a
0.3 percent increase in June.
   Kevin Flanagan, money market economist for Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc., said that while the report was ``nothing alarming, the market
was being skittish.''
   He said any indication that inflation is accelerating encourages
speculation that the Federal Reserve will not soon relax its credit
policy.
   He said there were also concerns that brokerage houses that
bought Treasury issues auctioned last week were still trying to find
buyers for the securities.
   But Flanagan said prices moved higher later in the day,
recovering most of the day's lost ground as buyers emerged at the
higher yields.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
issues lost [ point, intermediate securities fell 3-32 point and
long-term issues rose as much as 3-32 point, according to figures
provided by Telerate Inc., a financial information service.
   The movement of a point equals a change of $10 in the price of a
bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, fell 0.72 to 1,177.36.
   Corporate bonds prices edged up. Moody's Investment Grade
Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return on a portfolio of
80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose
0.22 to 328.25.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell [ point. The average yield to maturity
rose to 7.32 percent from 7.31 percent late Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 8.09 percent as the
discount dropped 5 basis points to 7.83 percent. Yields on six-month
bills rose to 8.28 percent as the discount rose 1 basis point to
7.85 percent. Yields on one-year bills rose to 8.30 percent as the
discount rose 2 basis points to 7.73 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 8~ percent, unchanged from late Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
