<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   08-18 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Rise in Afternoon Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market closed higher Friday, ending
with a rally after a relatively quiet session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.34 points to
finish at 2,687.97, a gain of 3.98 points on the week.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 6 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
776 issues up, 661 down and 544 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board totaled 145.81 million
shares, down from 157.56 million in the previous session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 174.245 million shares.
   Stocks opened weaker in response to a slide in the bond market
after a Labor Department report on consumer prices that raised
concern about the inflation outlook over the next few months.
   The Labor Department's Consumer Price Index rose 0.2 percent in
July, in line with the market consensus.
   ``People felt that since it was in line with expectations, the
Fed wouldn't have to ease credit at the present time,'' said Brad
Weeks, head of equity trading at the investment firm of Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette.
   But without food and energy costs, the most volatile components
of the index, consumer prices rose a heftier 0.4 percent, raising
inflation worries.
   ``The report looks good on the surface but when you read further
in there is concern that we have seen the lows in inflation and will
be moving higher in the months ahead,'' said James Solloway,
economist with Argus Research Corp.
   Stocks firmed slightly at midday as bonds turned higher and by
late afternoon prices were strengthening.
   But uncertainty about the impact of the the so-called ``double
witching hour'' _ the expiration of stock-index futures and options
that don't expire quarterly _ dampened the rally.
   Volume remained low throughout the session with computerized
program strategies dominating most of the activity, said Weeks.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market gained $12.033 billion, or 0.36
percent, in value from Thursday.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
0.69 to 192.64.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, UAL Corp. rose 4| to
271 amid reports that the company had drawn two more potential
bidders. McGraw Hill gained 6 to 85{ on renewed speculation that
Paramount Communications Inc. might make a bid for the company.
   Texas Utilities rose [ to 32], Maytag advanced 1} to 23\ and
General Electric gained \ to 58.
   Meanwhile, Philip Morris closed down 1{ at 156{, Navistar fell [
to 4} and Exxon remained unchanged at 43}.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 1.57 to 395.84, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index went up 1.58 to 346.03.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
finished at 461.97, 1.14 higher. At the American Stock Exchange, the
market value index closed at 379.18, up 0.84.
</TEXT>
