<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures End Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures ended a lackluster week by finishing
mixed Friday, with no major developments to influence prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the September contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, rose
12 cents to close at $18.80 per 42-gallon barrel. Contract months
for later delivery were narrowly mixed.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded regular
gasoline for September delivery edged up 0.38 cent to 52.73 cents a
gallon.
   Heating oil futures for September slipped 0.01 cent lower,
settling at 51.03 cents a gallon.
   Analysts said the market was driven mainly by technical factors
in the absence of news on oil supplies or production.
   ``It just fits into technical wiggle and jiggle,'' said Peter
Beutel, assistant director of the energy group at Elders Futures Inc.
   The oil market has been in the summer doldrums for some time.
Traders are looking forward to Labor Day for a pickup in activity
and beyond that to the next scheduled meeting, on Sept. 23, of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
