<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 1801EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-18 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Rally Ends On Profit-Taking and Easing Tensions in
Peru</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Profit-taking put an end to a seven-day runup in copper futures
prices Friday on New York's Commodity Exchange but chart-watchers
said technical signals pointed toward further gains.
   ``This might actually help,'' analyst Stephen Platt, of Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc., said of the moderately steep decline. He said
the market had fallen back to prices it had skipped over on its way
up and cited a theory that markets must fill such gaps before
resuming a trend.
   On other futures markets Friday, precious metals retreated while
futures prices for energy, grains, soybeans, livestock and meat were
mixed.
   Copper settled 1.50 cents to 2.35 cents lower with the contract
for spot delivery at $1.2465 a pound and the more actively traded
September contract at $1.2390.
   Spot prices had climbed as high as $1.2680 on Thursday, which
represented a gain of more than 15 percent since Aug. 8.
   The rally had been linked to indications that production
problems, including ongoing miner strikes in Canada and Peru, were
beginning to make a dent in copper stockpiles.
   Analysts said Friday's decline was largely a due to pre-weekend
profit-taking after the nearly vertical run-up.
   Platt said prospects for a settlement of the 5-day-old Peruvian
strike appeared to be improving. He said the miners must return to
work to qualify for wage bonuses and some observers believe those
bonuses are enough incentive to bring the strike to an end.
   But both Platt and Peter Cardillo, commodities trading adviser
with Josephthal &amp; Co., said the market continued to look strong from
a technical perspective.
   Gold and silver futures prices fell slightly on the Comex in
response to the Labor Department's report of a modest 0.2 percent
rise in consumer prices last month.
   Low inflation rates or falling prices tend to discourage investor
buying of precious metals.
   Gold settled 20 cents to 70 cents lower with August at $368.10 a
troy ounce; silver was .08 cent to 1 cent lower with September at
$5.255 a troy ounce.
   Wheat and corn futures prices retreated on confirmation of large
foreign purchases of those grains while soybean futures closed
higher following a private forecast for a surprisingly small crop.
   Memphis-based Sparks Commodities Inc. pegged the U.S soybean crop
at 1.84 billion bushels compared to the Agriculture Department's
estimate last week of 1.91 billion, and Sparks pegged the corn crop
at 7.05 billion bushels compared to the USDA's projected 7.35
billion.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 5 cents lower with September at $3.92\
a bushel; corn was unchanged to 1\ cents lower with September at
$2.34} a bushel; oats were unchanged to 1\ cents higher with
September at $1.38\ a bushel; soybeans were 4\ cents lower to 7}
cents higher with August at $6.15} a bushel.
   Reports of a gasoline refinery shutdown in Venezuela boosted
gasoline futures prices on the New York Mercantile Exchange. Crude
oil futures were mixed and heating oil was lower.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 4 cents lower to 12
cents higher with September at $18.80 a barrel; heating oil was .01
cent to .07 cent lower with September at 51.03 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .15 cent lower to .38 cent higher with
September at 52.73 cents a gallon.
   Livestock and meat futures were narrowly mixed on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the August contracts for live cattle and
hogs expired Friday. August live cattle finished 2 cents higher at
73.97 cents a pound; August hogs ended .90 cent higher at 48.75
cents a pound.
   Other live cattle contracts settled .08 cent lower to .20 cent
higher with September at 74.75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .08
cent lower to .18 cent higher with August at 84.57 cents a pound;
hogs were .15 cent lower to .40 cent higher with October at 41.05
cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were unchanged to .40 cent higher
with August at 27.17 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
