<FIRST>r f AM-CumminsLayoffs     08-18 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cummins Layoffs,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cummins Announces Layoffs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decrease in orders for heavy-duty truck
engines has forced Cummins Engine Co. to lay off about 100
production workers at its Indiana plants, the company announced
Friday.
   The layoffs, effective Aug. 28, will affect workers at Cummins
plants in Columbus, Indianapolis, Seymour and Madison, said Ann C.
Smith, a Cummins spokeswoman.
   The company also blamed the layoffs on production adjustments by
some of its customers. Cummins produces diesel engines, components
and power systems.
   The founding family of the Columbus-based, worldwide engine-maker
staged a major stock purchase last month to insulate Cummins from a
possible takeover.
   J. Irwin Miller, the company's board chairman, and members of his
family paid about $72 million to buy back 8.8 percent of Cummins
stock held by the U.S. arm of British conglomerate Hanson PLC.
   Nine days later, Industrial Equity (Pacific) Ltd., a Hong
Kong-based investiment concerned, filed notice with the Securities
and Exchange Commission that it acquired 9.9 percent of Cummins.
   Cummins officials have said IEP's holdings would not generate the
concern among shareholders that Hanson's did.
   Cummins employs 26,100 employees worldwide.
</TEXT>
