<FIRST>r f AM-PBASettlement     08-18 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PBA Settlement,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Provincetown Boston Airlines Suit Settled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An out-of-court settlement has been approved by a
federal court judge giving $2.4 million to former shareholders of
Provincetown Boston Airlines, which declared bankruptcy in 1985.
   Once the nation's largest commuter carrier, PBA is now operated
by Continental Airlines.
   A class-action suit was filed against the airline by shareholders
citing PBA's failure to disclose a long-standing investigation of
the airline by the Federal Aviation Administration.
   ``According to federal securities laws, an investor must be given
all of the necessary information to make an intelligent decision and
this obviously was not the case here,'' said Jeffrey Herrmann, a
Saddle Brook, N.J., attorney who represented the shareholders in the
4{-year-old suit.
   ``I'm delighted that the shareholders received a return on their
investment and in most cases, a complete recovery of the damages
they suffered as a result of the defendant's action,'' Herrmann said.
   PBA ran into troubles during a rapid expansion in the mid-1980s,
most notably two fatal air crashes in Boston Harbor and Florida.
   U.S. District Court Judge Charles E. Stewart Jr. approved the
settlement.
</TEXT>
