<FIRST>r f AM-Eastern-American     08-18 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-American,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say American Efforts to Buy Eastern Assets on Hold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines said Friday that
negotiations have lapsed in its attempt to buy routes and other
property for sale by Eastern Airlines, which is undergoing
bankruptcy reorganization because of a strike.
   ``As far as we know, discussions are in abeyance. Things change
so much we're not exactly sure what they're trying to sell,'' said
American spokeswoman Mary O'Neill.
   Discussions had been on-and-off, she said, but ``we got the
indication that they weren't looking to sell.''
   Miami-based Eastern had expressed interest in selling airport
property and its South American routes as part of a profound
restructuring to re-emerge from bankruptcy as a smaller airline.
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak in Miami said, ``There has
been no final decision to sell South America, and to the extent that
there have been discussions, we would not want to comment.''
   Eastern President Phil Bakes told The Associated Press the
carrier will be selling fewer assets than anticipated when it first
began trying to come back from its March 4 strike and subsequent
Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization.
   Bakes wouldn't go into details on the South American route
negotiations and said he didn't ``want to set odds'' on whether they
would be sold.
   ``We will have more employees, it will service more cities and
we'll have more airplanes,'' Bakes said in an interview.
   Eastern at first said it would need to sell $1.8 billion in
assets, but Bakes on Wednesday trimmed that estimate to $1.5 billion.
</TEXT>
