<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 2050EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Husky-Libya     08-18 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Husky-Libya,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Husky Oil, Two Partners Enter Agreement With Libya</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALGARY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Husky Oil Ltd. and two partners have signed an oil
production sharing agreement with Libya.
   The three, including OMV Exploration and Production Ltd. of
Austria and Petrobras International SA, an arm of Brazil's state oil
company, have committed $100 million to the venture, Husky said.
   Jamie Blair, Husky International president, said Thursday his
firm's share of the transaction will cost $35 million.
   Husky said the three exploration and production sharing
agreements with the National Oil Corp. of Libya cover five on-shore
exploration blocks in the Sirte and Ghadames Basins.
   The program includes 14 wells.
   ``Both basins already have oil production,'' Blair said. ``We
think the potential of these prospects is significant to Husky as a
company.''
   About 20 years after it nationalized foreign oil holdings, the
Libyan government faces severely reduced reserves.
   Libya now cannot produce enough oil to fill the production quota
assigned to it by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</TEXT>
