<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 2052EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-GEEngines     08-18 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GE Engines,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>GE's Lynn Plant Wins Navy Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Navy said Friday that General Electric Co.
won a heated competition with Pratt &amp; Whitney Aircraft Co. to
produce engines for F-A18 Hornet jets. GE estimated the eventual
value of the contract at up to $2 billion.
   The Navy placed an immediate order for 132 of the F-404 turbofan
engines, which are assembled at GE's plant in Lynn. In addition, the
Navy said GE would be the ``sole source'' for all additional
purchases of the engines, a status GE had enjoyed until 1984.
   In an unusual move five years ago, the Defense Department forced
GE to turn over plans for the F-404 engines to Pratt &amp; Whitney in an
effort to stimulate competition and reduce costs.
   Since then, Pratt &amp; Whitney, a division of United Technologies
Corp. of Hartford, Conn., has been a second source of the engines,
which cost between $1 million and $2 million apiece.
   In Lynn, where GE has eliminated 4,300 jobs over the past 2{
years, there was ``a great deal of relief and happiness'' Friday,
said company spokesman Robert N. Salvucci.
   Salvucci said 1,500 employees have been working on the engines,
and 100 to 150 more workers will be added in the second quarter of
1990 because of the Navy's decision.
   The F-A18, a carrier-based fighter and attack jet, is used by the
Canadian, Australian and Spanish air forces as well as the U.S. Navy
and Marines. It has also recently been selected by the governments
of Switzerland and Kuwait.
   Pratt &amp; Whitney said the Navy's decision would have no immediate
impact on employment in Hartford, because the company has a backlog
of orders that will last into 1991. Pratt &amp; Whitney spokesman
Brayton Harris said the company would not speculate on the eventual
impact.
</TEXT>
