<FILEID>AP-NR-08-18-89 2059EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-DisneyPay     08-18 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Disney Pay,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disney President Makes $74 Million on Stock Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president and chief operating officer
of Walt Disney Co. made a $74.2 million profit in July by selling
shares he purchased six months earlier under the company's stock
option plan.
   The sale by Frank G. Wells, revealed in a filing with the
Securities and Exchange Commission, was done in part because Wells
``wanted to do some estate planning,'' Disney spokesman Erwin Okun
said Friday.
   ``He has no plans to leave,'' Okun said. ``He's highly optimistic
about the long-range prospects, and he recently signed a contract
through 1994.''
   Okun said Wells made a cash purchase of 850,000 Disney shares at
the option exercise price of $14.36 each in January for a total of
$12.2 million. Wells sold the shares on July 18 and July 19 at a
market price of $101.60, or $86.4 million.
   Under the program, he still holds options to buy 42,000 shares at
the same low $14.36. That's the amount, adjusted for a stock split,
the shares were selling for when he joined the company in September
1984.
   Wells' salary this year is $400,000, and he received a $3.7
million bonus in January, an amount determined by the company's net
income.
   And there's more.
   ``In November he gets options on another 369,000 shares under his
contract (at the same $14.36),'' Okun said.
   Last year, Wells' boss, Disney chairman and chief executive
officer Michael D. Eisner, was paid a salary of $750,000 and his
performance-based bonus was $6.8 million.
   But he made a $32.6 million profit on shares purchased and sold
under the option program, and Okun said he has the option of buying
948,143 shares at the low rate. If he exercised the the option and
could sell the shares at Friday's stock price, he would pocket more
than $92 million.
   The year Eisner and Wells signed on with Disney, the company
earned $97.2 million. In the fiscal year that ended Sept. 31, the
earnings had jumped to $522 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
